<FIRST>r a AM-SRP     01-06 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SRP,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Official Says Contractor Change Adds To SRP Delays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The change in contractors at the Savannah
River Plant is ``aggravating'' the already long delay in restarting
the weapons plant's nuclear reactors, according to a Department of
Energy official.
   ``The engineering continuity is being lost'' as Du Pont Co.
prepares to turn over operations at SRP on April 1 to Westinghouse
Savannah River Co., said Richard W. Starostecki, the DOE's deputy
assistant secretary for safety, health and quality assurance.
   ``There's a lot of turmoil that is natural when you have a change
in management,'' Starostecki told the Aiken Standard. The complex
near Aiken produces tritium for nuclear bombs.
   The DOE official told the Augusta Chronicle on Thursday that the
first reactor still could be restarted by October. He also said
reports of cracks discovered in reactor cooling lines are ``not a
new issue.''
   The Augusta newspaper reported that SRP officials are reviewing
criteria used to determine when a cracked cooling pipe is replaced.
Officials are monitoring about 25 cracks in cooling lines at the
three reactors _ 15 of which are in the K-Reactor, which is the one
slated to be restarted first.
   At present, the cracks will not delay the restart, the newspaper
said.
   DOE officials also said Wednesday they expect Congress to approve
their planned request for up to $300 million toward building the new
military production reactors.
   The request is the first by the DOE's New Production Reactor
office, and is part of a proposed $6.8 billion project to build
reactors at SRP and the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory.
   The DOE would rely primarily on the SRP reactor to supply
perishable tritium gas for U.S. nuclear weapons in the next century.
The smaller Idaho reactor would serve as backup.
   Ronald W. Cochran, acting director of the NPR office, said he is
confident that Congress will approve the funding. This year's
appropriation will go toward safety analysis, environmental planning
and reactor design, he said.
   Construction of the Savannah River NPR is expected to start in
1991 or 1992, providing thousands of construction and engineering
jobs for the Aiken area.
   Cochran said the defense officials are concerned about current
delays at SRP because of the plant's major role in the military
project.
   Starostecki, who helped oversee commercial nuclear power for
about 12 years as a member of the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, said only aggressive, clearly-defined management can
deal with equipment problems that inevitably develop with all
nuclear reactors.
   While praising Westinghouse's qualifications, he said he is
frustrated with how long it's taking to complete
earthquake-resistance improvements and other work at SRP's reactors.
   SRP's three operable production reactors _ P, K and L _ have been
shut down since last summer for a DOE-ordered upgrade of management
and hardware.
   The 1950s-era reactors are the nation's only source of perishable
tritium gas, an essential component of nuclear weapons.
   Starostecki said SRP needs a management team with clear lines of
responsibility, and authority to promptly ``find and fix'' reactor
safety problems.
   The DOE hopes to authorize restart of the K reactor this year,
with the others to follow, but no current ``target dates'' have been
announced.
   He has recently sent teams of experts to SRP to investigate
cracking found in several reactor coolant pipes, but said Tuesday
the investigators have ``not brought back anything startling.''
   The commercial nuclear industry has learned to deal with pipe
cracking, he said, and SRP must benefit from that knowledge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
