<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TeenStarved 3rdLd-Writethru a0833 01-06 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Starved, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0833,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pastor Relied On God To Save Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Dr. George ..., to DELETE outdated reference
to charges not filed; SUBS grafs 9-11, `Cottam, sitting . .., to UPDATE
with wife charged; picks up 12th graf pvs, `Social service ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WLK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NUANGOLA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former minister, unemployed and too proud
to accept handouts, looked to God to provide for his family _ until
the day his teen-age son died of starvation. On Thursday he was
charged with murder.
   Larry Cottam, a former Seventh-Day Adventist minister who was
fired from his job as a truck driver last March, rejected public
assistance and refused to send his children to public school, where
they would have qualified for school breakfast and lunch programs,
neighbors and officials said.
   ``His belief (was that) God would provide,'' said Roy
Dieffenbach, Cottam's former boss at Norandex Inc. in Wilkes-Barre.
   Authorities on Wednesday found no food in the well-kept house in
a middle-class, suburban neighborhood in northeastern Pennsylvania,
where Cottam's 14-year-old son, Eric, died of starvation.
   Cottam, his wife and daughter were all hospitalized for
malnutrition.
   Dr. George E. Hudock Jr., the Luzerne County coroner, on
Wednesday ruled the teen-ager's death a homicide.
   Hudock said the teen-ager had not eaten in at least three weeks
and weighed 69 pounds, about 80 pounds less than normal for his
height, 5-feet-10.
   Cottam, 39, was listed in fair condition Thursday at Mercy
Hospital in Wilkes-Barre. His wife, Leona, 37, and daughter, Laura,
12, were listed in serious condition at the hospital.
   Cottam and his wife were arraigned Thursday at the hospital on
one count each of criminal homicide and two counts each of reckless
endangerment and endangering the welfare of their children.
   They could face the death penalty if convicted on the homicide
charge. District Magistrate Donald Swank set a preliminary hearing
for Jan. 13.
   Social service agencies will take custody of the daughter,
District Attorney Correale F. Stevens said.
   Cottam said he blamed himself for the tragedy.
   ``I don't hold God responsible. The error was on my part, not
God's,'' Cottam told WBRE-TV in Wilkes-Barre on Wednesday night.
``My wife and I feel terrible about Eric's death, but my faith in
God is not shaken.''
   Cottam was pastor of four local Seventh-Day Adventist churches,
with a total congregation of about 250, when he was transferred to
Pittsburgh. The family moved back to Nuangola in 1985 after he lost
his post in Pittsburgh.
   Dieffenbach said he fired Cottam in March over a dispute
involving the condition of a truck that Cottam refused to drive
without two new tires.
   Those who know the Cottams said the close-knit family kept to
themselves and rarely left their modest two-story home.
   Larry and Leona Cottam had kept their children out of school
since they returned to the area in 1985 and in May won a two-year
court battle to educate them at home.
   Elsa Heintzelman, a Crestwood School District official, said
Eric's death could have been prevented if the children were enrolled
in public schools. She said the children would have qualified for
school meal programs.
   ``We've all been very sad that this happened because it need not
have happened at all,'' Ms. Heintzelman said.
   Richard Deane, superintendent of the school district, said the
children were smart and had scored well on standardized tests.
   Ms. Heintzelman said the school district was concerned about the
children's welfare because they were so isolated, and also
questioned whether the Cottams were qualified to teach at home.
   According to Ms. Heintzelman, Eric and Laura Cottam weren't
allowed to talk to adults without their parents being present and
weren't allowed to take part in activities with other children.
   The Wilkes-Barre Times Leader on Thursday reported that the
family lived on savings and cut costs wherever possible. The
newspaper said the Cottams had unplugged their refrigerator, bought
day-old bread and kept their house cold.
</TEXT>
