<FIRST>r w PM-MayorBarry     01-06 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayor Barry,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Rebuffs Suggestions That He Submit To Drug Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington Mayor Marion Barry Jr., whose
association with a drug suspect is being investigated by federal
prosecutors, has brushed aside suggestions that he submit to a drug
test to defuse the controversy.
   Barry told reporters Thursday that he has been drug-free in
previous tests. He repeatedly has denied using drugs or knowingly
associating with drug users.
   Barry said he has taken drug tests twice a year during routine
physical examinations.
   ``I've taken a drug test for five years in a row,'' he said.
``I've released them twice a year.''
   That comment caught Barry's press secretary, John White, by
surprise.
   ``I've been here 18 months, and I've never handled the release
(of a test),'' White said. ``I don't know anything about that.''
   Barry's physician, Dr. Vincent J. Roux, said he doesn't recall
giving Barry drug tests.
   ``I'm not sure I have ever given the mayor a drug test,'' Roux
told WUSA-TV. ``I don't remember.'' The physician said he last
examined Barry about six months ago.
   Barry, mayor of the nation's capital for a decade, is facing his
most serious political crisis following disclosures that he met last
month with a man who is the subject of a city police drug
investigation.
   Police called off an attempt to make an undercover purchase of
drugs from the man, Charles Lewis, after detectives encountered one
of the mayor's security guards while Barry was at the hotel where
Lewis was staying, authorities have said.
   Sources familiar with the investigation say the U.S. attorney's
office has subpoenaed Barry's telephone records and other documents.
Barry has acknowledged calling Assistant Police Chief Isaac Fulwood,
who is supervising the city's drug investigation, but has said he
was trying to speed up the probe and not influence its outcome.
   U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens is investigating the incident, and is
expected to interview Barry. The mayor refused on Thursday to answer
questions about whether he would talk to prosecutors.
   Barry has acknowledged visiting Lewis, whom he described as an
acquaintance, but he denied any involvement with drugs or knowledge
that Lewis was the target of a city police drug investigation.
   The mayor said in a statement released Wednesday night that he
would cooperate with the federal probe.
   Lewis, a former city government employee, later coordinated a
joint personnel project between the governments of the city and the
Virgin Islands. He was fired from that job in April after Virgin
Islands officials became concerned that the project was becoming too
costly.
   Federal sources have said that Stephens has expanded his
investigation to include the Virgin Islands agreement, and the
Interior Department, which acts as comptroller for the island
territory, is also auditing the program.
   Joyce Fleischman, a spokeswoman for the inspector general for the
Interior Department, said auditors had not yet found a written
contract for the $260,000 project.
   District of Columbia law requires that such projects have formal,
written contracts.
   Investigators are trying to learn whether city officials billed
personal purchases to the Virgin Islands government and whether
other spending irregularities occurred.
   Auditors say that the names of some persons staying in St. Thomas
hotel rooms reserved for city officials working on the project do
not match a master list of employees provided by the city government.
</TEXT>
