<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DeficitCommission     01-06 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deficit Commission,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Ruling Casts Doubt On Future Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Economic Commission, already
facing an uncertain future, has lost a court battle to keep its
deliberations secret.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green ruled late Thursday in favor
of a suit brought by several news organizations, who had contended
that the commission's efforts to bar the public from several
upcoming hearings represented a violation of a federal open meeting
law.
   The 14-member advisory commission was created by Congress in
hopes that the panel could come up with a package of spending cuts
and tax hikes that would break the seven-year deadlock on the budget
deficit.
   Drew Lewis, co-chairman of the commission, had argued that the
commission would be unable to complete its job if it could not
hammer out differences in private.
   The commission attorneys had also contended that the members of
the panel were so prestigious that their public discussions on
economic matters could create chaos in financial markets reacting to
partial news reports on the deliberations.
   But in her ruling, Green said that Congress could have exempted
the commission from the open meetings requirements of federal law
but decided not to do so.
   ``Fully recognizing that the commission's composition would be
prestigious and its activities significant to the national need and
the international community, Congress made a deliberate choice to
make this commission subject to the open meeting requirements,'' the
judge said in her ruling.
   The judge said that her ruling did not mean that the commission
was prevented from ever meeting behind closed doors, but she said
any closed-door sessions would have to meet the strict definition in
the law that holding the session in public would ``significantly
frustrate implementation of a proposed agency action.''
   The lawsuit challenging the closed meeting was filed by The
Washington Post, The Wall Street Journal, the Bureau of National
Affairs, which publishes financial newsletters, and Stephen
Wildstrom, an editor at Business Week.
   Public Citizen, a consumer organization founded by Ralph Nader,
joined in the case.
   Eleanor Smith, an attorney with Public Citizen, said the judge's
ruling was a victory for the public's right to know.
   ``The commission's policy deliberations touch the life and
livelihood of every American, and it is exactly that kind of
discussion that the law requires to be conducted in the open in our
democracy,'' Smith said in a statement.
   David Mathiason, executive director of the commission, said the
panel's attorneys had not yet read the ruling and therefore he could
not comment on whether the commission would appeal the decision.
   Mathiason said no decision had been made on whether to cancel the
commission's next meetings, on Tuesday and Wednesday.
   The commission had already canceled a session in early December
after Green had issued a temporary restraining order blocking the
panel from closing the meeting.
   The judge's ruling, if not overturned, would mean that the
commission would have to hold its debates on ways to cut the deficit
in open sessions. The public hearings the commission has held so far
have revealed deep divisions on the panel over whether new taxes
will be needed to balance the budget.
   Because of this, critics had said it was doubtful that the panel
would be able to craft a plan that would find favor with
President-elect Bush and Congress.
   Bush, who derided the commission during the campaign as a
stalking horse for tax increases, last month appointed former Sen.
Paul Laxalt, R-Nev., and former Rep. Thomas Ashley, D-Ohio, as his
representatives on the panel, but he maintained his stance that no
increase in taxes will be needed to balance the budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
