<FIRST>r i PM-BRF-Malaysia-Maids     01-06 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF-Malaysia-Maids,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malaysia Lifts Freeze On Maids From Philippines, Doubles Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today lifted the freeze
on recruiting maids from the Philippines to work in Malaysia, but
doubled the cost for the domestic workers' services and imposed a
new immigration quota.
   The cost of employing a maid now is 4,000 ringgits ($1,477) per
month, and under government orders only 420 maids can be recruited
monthly from the Philippines, said Richard Ng, head of the
Association of Agents of Domestic Helpers Malaysia.
   Ng said 14 agencies are empowered to hire maids from the
Philippines, charging employers 1,500 ringgits ($554) a month per
their services.
   The maids are paid about 400 ringgits ($148) a month.
   They are about 3,600 Filipina maids in Malaysia. The freeze was
imposed last year after Philippines President Corazon Aquino banned
maids from taking overseas jobs. She lifted it in October.
</TEXT>
