<FIRST>r w PM-ContraPeacePlan     01-06 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Peace Plan,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Leaders Urging Bush To Impose Sanctions Against Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Nicaragua's Contra resistance are
urging the incoming Bush administration to impose sanctions against
the country's Sandinista government to enforce any agreements
reached in an expected diplomatic offensive.
   Alfredo Cesar, the Contra's chief negotiator, said Thursday that
agreement also has been reached inside the Contra movement on a
modified peace plan to be presented next month at a summit meeting
of Central American presidents in El Salvador.
   Cesar said the plan was discussed with U.S. officials Thursday at
a meeting at the State Department.
   At a news conference, Cesar said the peace plan, a modification
of an initiative presented last June, is supported by all Contra
leaders. He said U.S. officials had expressed the hope ``that the
proposal would be one, not several.''
   Cesar predicted the United States will begin a major and extended
diplomatic effort to achieve democratic reform in Nicaragua soon
after President-elect Bush takes office.
   He said it is likely that military efforts against the
Sandinistas will be put on the back burner, at least for the time
being.
   ``I have no doubt myself that the Bush administration will make a
very serious diplomatic effort _ with bipartisan support from
Congress _ as the first way to get a solution,'' he said. ``It will
be a serious effort that will last several months.''
   But he said the necessary leverage to pressure the Sandinistas to
make binding commitments and concessions can only come through
imposing strong sanctions on an escalating scale.
   ``At this moment the military wing of the resistance is idle,
it's intact but it's idle; the troops are sitting in border camps,''
Cesar said.
   ``So the leverage for the upcoming phase of the negotiations has
to come from the United States and the diplomatic pressure from the
big countries of Latin America,'' he said.
   Cesar added: ``One of the most important changes I would expect
is sanctions for not complying'' with an agreement. ``That has been
the key element missing from past efforts.''
   He said sanctions should be applied against the Sandinista regime
not only by the United States but by the nations of Europe and Latin
America as well.
   Sanctions should range, Cesar said, ``from diplomatic isolation _
passing through economic pressure _ and even the use of force if
necessary.''
   ``If sanctions are not applied, the new initiative will face a
very high risk of failing also,'' he said.
   Cesar said that the U.S. officials with whom he and other Contra
leaders met made no commitments and were ``very clear in saying they
could not speak for the Bush administration.''
   Cesar said Contra leaders will offer a single, unified peace
proposal including three major modifications and additions to
previous plans.
   They are:
   _ The elimination of some sections that Cesar said were
considered ``too perfectionist.'' For example, Cesar said the
Contras dropped a condition that all Sandinista-appointed
magistrates resign. Instead they called on the Sandinistas to give
assurances that the nation's Supreme Court ``will be composed of
independent people.''
   _ The timetable of the plan was adjusted to provide ``more
flexibility and more graduality.'' Deadlines of 15 to 30 days for
meeting conditions of the plan have been extended to 60 days or so,
Cesar said.
   _A new section has been added proposing a national and
international effort to rebuild Nicaragua's economy once democratic
reforms are under way. Cesar said this would include an appeal to
the United States, Europe and Latin America for economic aid.
   ``That is a totally new element,'' Cesar said of the final point.
</TEXT>
