<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-US     01-06 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-US,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Says U.S. Navy Exercises Violated Canal Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. naval forces violated a major
treaty by staging ``intimidating, provocative and unapproved''
military exercises in the Panama Canal, the Defense Forces said.
   A communique from the Defense Forces, commanded by strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noreiga, said Thursday's manuevers violated the
Torrijos-Carter Treaty because all U.S. and Panamanian military
operations in the canal must be coordinated by both countires.
   The communique said nine U.S. Navy combat patrol boats ``fully
armed with its crew in a state of readiness'' took part in morning
exercises Thursday at the canal's Pacific Ocean entrance. It said
the boats were escorted by two U.S. Black Hawk helicopters.
   Under the treaty signed in September 1977, all military
operations in the 50-mile waterway linking the Pacific and Atlantic
oceans must be coordinated by a canal defense group that includes
representatives of both countries.
   Canal-based U.S. military officials could not be immediately
reached for comment.
   The Panamanian military said it considered the exercise ``an
intimidating, provocative and unapproved action against the civilian
population and members of the national and international merchant
marine community.''
   The communique said participating in the exercise were three
103-foot patrol boats, four 45-foot patrol boats and two 20-foot
patrol boats with outboard motors.
   The Defense Forces said it lodged complaints with the U.S.
government and the canal defense group but received no explanation.
   A Panamanian television station Thursday night broadcast a tape
of the exercise near the Point of the Americas, at the canal's
Pacific Ocean entrance.
   The U.S. military's Southern Command operates along the canal,
with about 13,000 troops and 11 military installations.
   About 3,000 U.S. troops left Panama in March after the U.S.
government imposed economic sanctions against Panama in an attempt
to force out Noreiga, the Panamanian strongman.
   Last February, the Noriega-dominated National Assembly ousted
elected President Eric Arturo Delvalle and replaced him with
Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma.
   Delvalle had tried to dismiss Noriega in February after a federal
grand jury in Miami indicted the military leader on drug trafficking
charges.
</TEXT>
