<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-UN Bjt   01-06 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-UN, Bjt,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Libya Trade Charges, U.N. Resolution to Condemn U.S. Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead expected after session reconvenes about 11 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya and the United States disputed each
other's facts, honor and circumstances in the downing of two Libyan
jets by U.S. warplanes during a contentious emergency session of the
U.N. Security Council.
   The two sides are expected to resume their verbal dogfight today
when the session moves into its second day.
   Libyan Ambassador Ali Sunni Muntasser, who sought the urgent
meeting, called the U.S. action a ``premediated act of aggression
and a prelude to large-scale aggression'' against economic and
military installations.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun told the council the two U.S.
Navy fighter jets that shot down the MiG-23s over the Mediterranean
on Wednesday acted in self-defense because they faced ``imminent
threat of being shot down by the intercepting Libyan aircraft.''
   Okun said the United States considers the matter closed.
   Libya repeated its claim that the jets were unarmed
reconnaissance planes.
   That disputed a Pentagon videotape shot from one of the U.S. jets
showing one Libyan plane carrying four missiles. The videotape,
released Thursday, showed the U.S. fighters tried high-speed
maneuvers five times to avoid the MiG planes before they fired.
   Libya wants the 15-member Security Council, the most powerful
U.N. body, to formally condemn the U.S. military action.
   On Thursday, the United States and Libya traded charges and six
other speakers _ representing the Arab League, Bahrain, Burkina
Faso, Cuba, Syria and Tunisia _ condemned the U.S. action.
   However, the United States and Britain, two of five permanent
members with veto power, were expected to kill any resolution of
condemnation. British Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe said Thursday
that the U.S. account of the clash showed ``it is clear they acted
in self-defense.''
   The United States, Britain and France cast vetoes to kill a
condemnation in the council of the April 1986 U.S. air raid against
Libya in Benghazi and Tripoli. About 100 people were killed in the
attack, including the daughter of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   The other permanent council members are China and the Soviet
Union, whose Foreign Ministry spokesman, Gennedy I. Gerasimov,
sharply criticized the U.S. attack as a show of ``state terrorism.''
   Other members of the Security Council are Algeria, Brazil,
Canada, Colombia, Ethiopia, Finland, Malaysia, Nepal, Senegal and
Yugoslavia.
   Soviet Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov told reporters the
Soviet Union had warned the United States before Thursday's attack
not to escalate tensions with Libya over an alleged Libyan chemical
weapons plant.
   ``We gave a warning signal to Washington to show restraint in
that area,'' Belonogov said, ``not to raise the tension in the area.
We were concerned by this (U.S. anti-Libyan) campaign in connection
with a so-called chemical weapons plant.''
   Belongov urged the United States to consider Libya's offer of
inspection of the plant, 60 miles southwest of Tripoli, the Libyan
capital. The United States says such an inspection would be
inconclusive because the plant could be quickly dismantled and the
offending materials hidden.
   Libya claims the plant is only for the manufacturing of
pharmaceuticals but the United States and Britain say it is intended
to produce chemical weapons and is ready to go on line.
   U.S. officials have denied any connection between the air action
and allegations about the chemical plant.
   Okun, the acting permanent U.S. representative, said ``when it
comes to a choice beween the word of the Libyans and the word of the
United States, I think the world knows whose word to accept.''
   In Washington, the Reagan administration has made no final
decision about whether to attack the plant, but Pentagon contingency
plans suggest the first-ever use of cruise missiles with non-nuclear
warheads, sources say.
   The sources said use of the unmanned Tomahawk cruise missile is
``a preferred contingency'' because no pilots would be involved and
because of the missile's accuracy.
</TEXT>
