<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher Again, Shares Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher Friday against the
Japanese yen, while share prices slightly rebounded on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 125.97 yen, up 0.64 yen from Thursday's
close of 125.33 yen. It opened at 126.10 yen and traded between
125.70-126.15 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed 25.75 points or 0.09
percent higher to finish trading at 30,209.54, despite a decline
during morning trading.
   A majority of institutional investors however have moved to the
sidelines following reports Emperor Hirohito, 87, was in serious
condition, one dealer said, speaking on condition he not be
identified.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened higher in Tokyo
following overnight gains in New York, where it finished at 125.98
yen.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer attributed the dollar's firmness to
investors' expectations of higher U.S. interest rates.
   It is widely believed in Tokyo that the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board will raise its discount rate if December's jobless figure, due
out later Friday, shows economic strength. The discount rate is the
central bank's lending charge to financial institutions.
