<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     01-06 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Again, Share Prices Up A Bit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the U.S. dollar and share prices finished
higher in Tokyo markets today amid concerns over Japanese Emperor
Hirohito's health and the upcoming release of the U.S. jobless
figure, dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 125.97 yen, up 0.64 yen from Thursday's
finish of 125.33 yen. Opening higher at 126.10 yen, the U.S.
currency moved in a range of 125.70-126.15 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 59.87-point
loser Thursday, regained 25.75 points or 0.09 percent to end trading
at 30,209.54.
   The Nikkei index started higher in Tokyo following an overnight
gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York, but it quickly
plunged after news reports about the weakening yen and the emperor's
condition taking a turn for the worse.
   But the index recovered from its morning loss when
defense-related issues began attracting investors, said a dealer
with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   Investors increasingly bought steels in the afternoon, which
helped the index's recovery, said the dealer, who spoke on the
condition he not be named.
   Some investors remained on the sidelines ahead of the U.S.
jobless figure for December, due out later today in Washington, the
dealer said. But he said market sentiment was quite optimistic,
expecting no major changes in U.S. economic policy before the
President-elect Bush takes office Jan. 20.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 850 million
shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed higher than its
Thursday finish, though slightly lower than its opening today in
cautious trading in anticipation of the U.S. unemployment rate,
dealers said.
   It was widely believed that the currency's higher opening in
Tokyo followed its overnight one-yen jump in New York, where it
finished at 125.98 yen.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer said the dollar's firmness was a result of
investors' expectation for a U.S. interest rate hike if the jobless
rate improves.
   Some Tokyo investors believed that U.S. banks might raise their
discount rates if the jobless rate is lower, which would indicate
the U.S. economy has been steadily growing.
   An estimated $8.8 billion were exchanged in spot trading.
</TEXT>
