<FIRST>r i PM-Libya     01-06 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Moves Jets To Desert, Claims U.S. Preparing For Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Libya-UN, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya reportedly is moving its jet fighters to desert
oases and posting machine gun nests around public buildings, saying
the United States plans an attack to follow up on its downing of two
Libyan planes.
   The Rome newspaper Il Messaggero reported from Tripoli on
Thursday that Libyan fighter jets were transferred inland from
coastal bases, some as far south as the heart of the Sahara desert,
to be out of range of possible attack by U.S. naval forces in the
Mediterranean.
   An Italian in Tripoli said by telephone that the capital's
streets were calm but that public buildings were fortified with
machine gun posts one day after U.S. jets shot down two Libyan MiG
fighters over the Mediterranean.
   Soldiers stood in for traffic police in the streets, the Yugoslav
news agency Tanjug said.
   The government refused entry to 30 foreign journalists at Tripoli
airport Thursday, and an aide at the Information Ministry indicated
the 200 journalists now in Libya also may be asked to leave.
   The Libyan government newspaper Al-Fajr El-Jadid on Thursday said
the shooting ``clearly demonstrates that the United States intends
to attack Libya. The United States (fleet in the Mediterranean) is
there to attack Libya and the attack against our airplanes is
evidence of this.''
   The Reagan administration said Libya was lying when it claimed
the planes were unarmed reconnaissance aircraft. Pentagon spokesman
Dan Howard said photos from an American jet showed one of the
fighters carried four missiles.
   A U.S. videotape of the incident, released Thursday, showed the
U.S. fighters tried high-speed maneuvers five times to avoid the MiG
planes before they fired.
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi did not appear publicly or had issued no
statements by Thursday evening. On Wednesday, the Libyan leader
denounced the incident as American ``terrorism'' and vowed to ``meet
challenge with challenge.''
   On Thursday, Libyan officials promised Western journalists who
arrived earlier in Tripoli a visit to a plant that the U.S.
administration charges was built recently to manufacture chemical
weapons. Gadhafi insists the plant is a pharmaceutical factory.
   By evening, the promised visit to the site, in Rabta 60 miles
southwest of Tripoli, had not materialized.
   Syria's health minister, Mohammed Ayad Chatti, who said he
visited the plant recently, told reporters the facility was ``a
small factory, not high-tech,'' and that it manufactures medicine.
   Asked about reports it was ringed with missiles and artillery, he
replied, ``That's because it cost a lot.''
   Wednesday's attack was the second U.S. strike against Libyan
targets in less than two years.
   The United States bombed Libya in April 1986 for suspected Libyan
involvement in a West Berlin disco frequented by U.S. servicemen.
   Libya's official media said Palestinian leader Col. Saeed Mousa
arrived in Tripoli on Wednesday night and issued a statement
supporting Libya after the U.S. action.
   Mousa, also known as Abu Mousa, leads the Fatah-Uprising faction,
which is backed by Syria. It broke with Yasser Arafat, chairman of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, in 1983.
   On Wednesday night, Libyan media reported a message of solidarity
from Ahmed Jibril, who leads the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command. The group has been mentioned as a
possible suspect in last month's bombing of a Pan Am jetliner in
Scotland, in which 270 people were killed.
</TEXT>
