<FIRST>r a PM-People-ZsaZsa     01-06 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Zsa Zsa,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Escorted Off Delta Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police escorted actress Zsa Zsa Gabor off a Delta
Air Lines flight after she refused to keep her dogs in travel
kennels, an airline spokesman said.
   Ms. Gabor, 69, was traveling from Los Angeles to her home in Palm
Beach, Fla., with an assistant and two Shih Tzu dogs when the
confrontation occurred Thursday night during a stopover at
Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.
   During the flight, she ``removed her two (dogs) from their
kennels,'' airline spokesman William D. Berry said. ``The Delta
agent came aboard. He asked her six times to comply. She refused to
comply. Each time he was responded to with considerable vulgarity.''
   Atlanta police officers were then called by the agent to escort
Ms. Gabor off the aircraft.
   Dogs are not permitted to run free in the cabin of the airplane,
Berry said.
   ``Passengers complained,'' he said. ``The captain asked her to
put them back in the kennel. All she had to do was leave the dogs in
the kennel, but she would not comply. We asked her to do nothing
more than any other passenger.''
   Ms. Gabor contended the dogs were not disturbing anyone, and said
the Delta agent on the plane ``was screaming at me like I was some
criminal.''
   ``I was so upset you can't imagine. This is not the end of
this,'' she said before boarding an Eastern Airlines flight to
complete the last leg of her trip.
   ``If I live to be 100 I'll never understand why five policemen
would have to come and take me off the plane,'' Ms. Gabor said. ``As
long as I live, I don't want to hear the word Delta.''
</TEXT>
