<FIRST>r i PM-AfricanStudents     01-06 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-African Students,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Claims Africans Confess, Boycott Continues In Beijing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associatzd Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African students in Beijing today demanded China
release three Africans being held in Nanking and boycotted classes
for a third day.
   The students also called on China to change the way it spells the
word Africa because the Chinese characters have a bad meaning and
called for a public apology from Chinese students who participated
in anti-black demonstrations.
   ``We want freedom for our brothers in Nanking,'' said one student
from Mali.
   A snowstorm delayed the flight of a group of African diplomats
heading from the capital to the eastern city of Nanking for talks
with African students and Chinese officials.
   On Thursday, an official report said the three African students,
held by police following a brawl in Nanking that triggered racial
unrest in four cities, admitted they broke the law.
   One of the three remained under arrest and apparently faced a
trial, while the two others were being punished with 15 days of
``disciplinary detention,'' the Xinhua News Agency said.
   A fourth African student detained by Nanking police was released
Thursday, it said.
   Students contacted in Nanking questioned the truth of the Xinhua
report. ``It is very easy for the Chinese to put words in people's
mouths, especially when they are in jail and cannot speak for
themselves,'' said Carl Ameho, a student from Ghana.
   On Thursday, about 45 African students held 10 days at a guest
house following the Christmas Eve brawl returned to Hehai
University, the scene of the fight.
   They were among 140 students, mostly from Africa, who tried to
flee to Beijing in the face of the Chinese protests last week but
were taken by police to the guest house.
   The four were taken into custody Saturday by about 400 police
who, according to students and African diplomats, used electric
cattle prods and wooden clubs on the students. Chinese officials
deny any violence was used.
   The trouble began Christmas Eve in Nanking, when Chinese
gatekeepers refused to allow two Chinese women to attend an African
student party.
   Xinhua said Alex Dosoo of Ghana beat a university worker during
the fight. He was the only African formally arrested.
   It said Alpha Robinson of Gambia and Dossoumou Boni Lodovic of
Benin ``tried to stir up trouble'' during the brawl and were given
15 days detention. All three admitted that they broke the law, it
said.
   Hanson Ebenezer Ekow of Ghana was released, Xinhua said. Hehai
University said all four were expelled from the school.
   A student from Ghana said the Xinhua report distorted the
incident.
   He said that when he went down to the university's main gate to
see why his friends weren't being allowed in, a group of Chinese
attacked him.
   ``They began beating me,'' said the student, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Alex and the others came down to save me.
It was self-defense.''
   African students said that on their first day back Chinese
students at Hehai yelled, ``Black devil, you've returned,'' and
``Black devil, get lost.''
   Ameho said most of the students still want to leave Nanking.
Racial incidents also have occurred in Hangzhou and Wuhan.
   In Beijing, several hundred African students at the Beijing
Languages Institute continued their class boycott, prompted by
Chinese allegations that a black student accosted a Chinese woman in
her room.
   The student from Mali, who spoke on condtion of anonymity, said
the students ``also want China to change the way its spells Africa.
Other areas of the world have nicer names.''
   Africa is called ``Feizhou,'' in Chinese, which means literally
the bad continent. America, for example, is called ``Meiguo,'' or
the beautiful country.
   China denies charges of racial prejudice, and expresses
solidarity with the Third World in giving scholarships to African
students. There are about 1,500 African students from 40 nations in
China.
   Social contacts between African men and Chinese women are a
frequent source of tension.
</TEXT>
