<FIRST>r a PM-AutoSales     01-06 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Sales Surged In 1988, Manufacturers Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Retail Sales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High employment and a sound economy helped drive
car-and-truck sales to at least their third-highest level in 1988,
with domestic makes showing strong gains while imports lagged, U.S.
automakers and analysts said.
   Boosted by a surge at the end of last year, total sales of cars
and light trucks in the United States amounted to 15.44 million
vehicles in 1988, automakers reported Thursday. That was up from
14.9 million in 1987.
   Some industry analysts believe 1988 may end up as the second-best
year ever, with sales topping the 1985 mark of 15.7 million when
heavy and medium-truck import sales figures become available in
several weeks. Ray Windecker, an analyst at Ford Motor Co., said
those sales have approached 300,000 vehicles in previous years.
   The industry's record year was 1986 when sales hit 16.3 million
vehicles.
   High employment and low inflation helped boost sales, said
Jeanette Garretty, auto analyst with the Bank of America in San
Francisco.
   ``It's been a good year for the economy,'' said Garretty.
   Domestic car and light-truck sales were 11.72 million in 1988, up
7.5 percent from 10.9 million in 1987.
   In the year's final sales period, Dec. 21-31, sales of U.S.-made
cars and light trucks soared to 400,297 vehicles, up 20.7 percent
from the same period of 1987.
   Sales of imports, which had to contend with toughening
competition and a weak dollar, dropped 8.6 percent to 3.72 million
from 4.1 million in 1987.
   Among the domestic automakers, General Motors Corp. reported
sales of 3.64 million cars last year, up 2.1 percent from 3.55
million in 1987. GM said its light-truck sales rose 12.6 percent to
1.7 million vehicles.
   ``The numbers have started to move in the right way,'' said GM
President Robert Stempel, adding that the figures showed the No. 1
automaker was turning the corner after losing market share in recent
years.
   Ford said it sold 2.2 million cars, up 8.8 percent from 2.0
million the previous year. Sales of its light trucks rose 4.2
percent to 1.5 million vehicles, the company said.
   Chrysler Corp., the third-largest U.S. maker, said 1988 car sales
rose 10.2 percent to 1.1 million from 962,057 a year earlier.
Light-truck sales jumped 14.6 percent to 955,619, it said.
   Among Japanese carmakers, Toyota sales increased in 1988 to
616,529 from 583,809 in 1987.
   Honda saw its import sales drop to 393,360 from 421,688 in 1987,
but sales of its U.S.-made cars increased to 375,625 from 316,618.
   The top-selling European manufacturer was Volkswagen, although
its sales fell to 168,800 cars last year from 191,705 in 1987. The
West German company stopped assembling cars in the United States
last July.
   Volvo ranked second among European makers, with sales dropping to
97,848 for the year from 105,087 in 1987.
</TEXT>
