<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Armenia     01-06 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Prosecutors Fired For Lack Of Action During Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Armenian prosecutors have been fired and
several others disciplined for failure to halt ethnic violence
between Armenians and Azerbaijanis, Pravda said today.
   Four prosecutors received ``strong reprimands'' and the Armenian
prosecutors' committee of peers recommended a fifth resign at the
end of his term, ``pending conclusion of an investigation into
murders in the Gugar region,'' the official Communist Party
newspaper reported.
   Pravda did not elaborate on those murders, and it gave no
specific allegations against the prosecutors.
   But the newspaper did charge that illegal activities of Armenian
activists in the ``Karabakh'' committee ``often went unpunished.''
All of the disciplined prosecutors have Armenian names.
   Armenian activists have been pressuring authorities to transfer
the largely Armenian area of Nagorno-Karabakh from Azerbaijan to
Armenia to protect residents against alleged discrimination.
   Pravda said unsanctioned rallies inflamed passions and led to mob
violence. The prosecutors' panel found that concessions made by
local government and factory leaders to Karabakh committee activists
contributed to the danger, the newspaper said.
   ``As passions mounted, the prosecutors and internal affairs
(police) officials began to lose control over events, and failed to
ensure law and order, public safety and observance of the
constitution,'' Pravda said.
   The prosecutors' panel said all prosecutors in the southern
republic, which also was ravaged last month by an earthquake that
killed 55,000 people, should ``rectify the gross mistakes,
miscalculations and shortcomings in their work'' and prevent further
ethnic clashes.
</TEXT>
