<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-06 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The answer is: Dick Thomas, a former fish
and wildlife technician with the state Department of Environmental
Conservation.
   The question: Who spurred dozens of media mavens, including TV's
Jeopardy, to seek the answer to the time-honored question, ``How
much wood would a woodchuck chuck if a woodchuck could chuck wood?''
   Thomas came up with an answer _ 700 pounds _ to the woodchuck
riddle during some idle moments last June. In the intervening six
months, his little joke has popped up all over America.
   Last week, it popped up on the TV game show Jeopardy, which
provides contestants with answers and asks them to pose the matching
question.
   The phone at Thomas' home in the upstate town of Caledonia
immediately started ringing with calls from friends who wanted to be
sure he knew what happened. But Thomas was nonplussed by the
attention. He's used to it now.
   ``I've got my woodchuck file right here,'' Thomas said Thursday.
``It would be a lot bigger but I didn't start keeping it right
away.''
   The file includes stories from papers all over the country. Their
interest perked up after Thomas wrote to Fin, Fur and Feather Facts,
a normally sober Department of Conservation newsletter, last June.
   ``It's high time someone provided an answer to this question,''
he wrote.
   Thomas described woodchucks and their burrows, computed volumes
and weights, and ended, ``Next time someone asks you ... tell him,
`Oh, about 700 pounds on a good day with the wind at his back'. Then
say, `Everybody knows that.' ''
   The Wall Street Journal, which Thomas said called him three times
to get the woodchuck facts straight, provided him with an idea for
another project _ determining how many peppers Peter Piper picked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whoever stole Roger Rabbit and
Bugs Bunny here has turned the escapade into a harebrained scheme.
   The plywood cartoon characters were pilfered from Terry Higgins'
prize-winning Christmas lighting display last week.
   The next day, Higgins found a broken piece of Bugs Bunny's ear in
a plastic bag. The bag also contained a note made from letters cut
out of a newspaper directing him to a downtown parking garage.
   Bugs was recovered from a janitor at the garage, along with
another note from a group which mystifyingly called itself the
United Front For BOX.
   ``Our organization is very sorry about Bugs's ear. It was quite
honestly an accident,'' the note read. ``If you follow our
directions, you will find Roger perfectly intact. We will give you
further instructions within 24 hours.
   Higgins said he and his son waited for several days but nothing
happened.
   ``We all think it's some kids who are doing this,'' he said.
``They probably stole them and it became a big joke. Whoever wrote
these notes did a beautiful job. There is a lot of work in it.''
   Bugs has had successful ear surgery but Higgins said he's anxious
to see Roger again.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the classy Woodlands Club,
where it costs $12,500 just to join, have been admonished to cut out
the food fights or risk getting kicked out.
   ``Some of our members have never been in a club before and don't
know the protocol,'' manager Phil Swett said, trying to explain why
the club at times resembles ``Animal House'' more than ``Lifestyles
of the Rich and Famous.''
   To set the unruly straight, Swett mailed the 630 members a letter
detailing offensive behavior that has been observed at the $10
million sports, recreation and housing complex that opened last
August in this wealthy town north of Portland.
   Among the distasteful behavior cited in Swett's letter:
   _ Parents sitting idly by while their children throw food around
the dining room. Some families, Swett said, have left their dining
table with food ``literally covering the floor.''
   _ Parents leaving soiled baby diapers around the club and making
no effort to clean up ``accidents.''
   In addition to the $12,500 initiation fee, members pay a $2,500
annual fee and must spend at least $800 a year on food and drinks at
the club.
</TEXT>
