<FIRST>u i PM-Shultz-Chemical 1stLd-Writethru   01-06 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shultz-Chemical, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0484,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz: U.S. Could Deal With Libya On Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs on Shultz planning to persuade Soviets
to help close Libyan plant. Picks up graf x pvs, `Shultz, in ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chemical Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz indicated the
United States may be willing to work out a deal with Libya that
would not require the destruction of a plant said to be on the verge
of full production of poison gas.
   Shultz said Thursday en route to Paris for an international
conference on chemical weapons that he also will make a fresh
attempt this weekend to persuade the Soviet Union to help close down
the Libyan plant outside Tripoli.
   ``They (the Soviets) are very concerned about the problem,''
Shultz said. ``They were very quick to endorse the idea of this
conference.''
   Shultz has already discussed the Libyan plant with Shevardnadze.
The first time, a U.S. official said, was when they both attended a
U.N. General Assembly session in New York in late September. The
second occasion was Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit
last month to New York.
   Shultz said the United States has given the Soviets some of the
information that led U.S. analysts to be ``quite comfortable'' about
accusing Libya of being ready to begin chemical weapons production.
But, he said, ``so far as I know, we have not convinced them.''
   Shultz planned meetings today with President Francois Mitterrand
and Prime Minister Michel Rocard, Canadian Foreign Minister Joe
Clark and Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmet Abdel-Meguid.
   Shultz said Thursday on his flight from Washington that the
United States supports the destruction of the Rabta facility ``to
take care of the problem,'' but hinted the dispute might be resolved
without leveling the facility.
   ``Whether there is something else that can be done, we'll see,''
Shultz said without elaborating.
   Shultz acknowledged some of America's best friends are not
convinced the plant 60 miles southwest of Tripoli is a weapons
facility. Britain, however, said it has conclusive independent
information the plant, about to go on line, is involved in chemical
weapons production.
   The Libyan leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, has offered a one-time
inspection of the plant that he says produces pharmaceuticals.
   The State Department rejected the offer, saying the facility
could be easily changed to omit the chemical weapons production
items, then put back into production after the inspectors leave.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher says he is
``very concerned'' about U.S. allegations that West German companies
had helped Libya build the plant.
   The West German Foreign Ministry announced that its ambassador to
Libya, Juergen Helner, has asked Gadhafi to accept international
inspection of the plant.
   The forceful U.S. condemnation of the facility, which began more
than two months ago, has prompted speculation that the United States
might attack Rabta, as it did Tripoli in 1986 after accusing Libya
in the bombing of a West German nightclub.
   President Reagan's public refusal to rule out the military option
and the U.S. downing Wednesday of two Libyan jet fighters over the
Mediterranean fueled the speculation further.
   Companies in about a half-dozen industrialized countries are
suspected of assisting Libya. The State Department has urged them to
desist. As a result, Shultz said, chemical weapons have not been
produced at Rabta.
   ``They are not there yet,'' Shultz said. ``They have had some
difficulties.''
   The conference of 140 nations opens Saturday.
</TEXT>
