<FIRST>r i PM-Denmark-Taxi     01-06 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denmark-Taxi,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabbies Get Bigger Fare With Smaller Tires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers would be well advised to
carry a tape measure when they hail a Danish taxi because some
unscrupulous cabbies are driving with undersized tires to cheat the
meter, reports said today.
   Copenhagen's taxi registration branch has discovered cab owners
have equipped their vehicles with tires that are smaller than the
size approved for their cars, an the result is the meter runs five
to 12 percent too fast.
   This means that in a normal operating period of two years and
155,000 miles, the tire change can yield up to 100,000 kroner, or
$14,300 in extra fares, the Jyllands-Posten newspaper said.
   Police, while declaring the tire changing trick to be illegal,
say they lack the manpower to check tires on all taxis after an
initial inspection.
   ``We control in most cases only that the taxi meter is correctly
adjusted. This is a guarantee that the tires were legal at the time
of inspection, but that's all it does,'' motor vehicle inspector
Nyegaard Jensen was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
