<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     01-06 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Both Dollar And Gold Stronger In London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was stronger in early European
trading today and foreign currency dealers said they were nervous
about the possibility of central bank intervention. Gold prices also
rose.
   Traders attributed the dollar's rise to firming U.S. interest
rates and continuing tension in the Mediterranean where American
warplanes shot down two Libyan planes.
   ``I think we'll see the Bundesbank this morning,'' said a trader
at a large German bank in Frankfurt, referring to the West German
central bank.
   A trader at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt agreed, ``They should come
into the market.''
   The Bundesbank reportedly intervened in the market Thursday,
selling a modest amount of dollars.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.64 yen to a closing 125.97 amid concerns over
Japanese Emperor Hirohito's condition. Later, in London, it was
quoted at 126.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.7985 West German marks, up from 1.7955
   _1.5345 Swiss francs, up from 1.5195
   _6.1405 French francs, up from 6.1155
   _2.0263 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0220
   _1.1915 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1877
   Markets were closed in Italy for a national holiday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7925, slightly cheaper for
buyers than late Thursday's $1.7970.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $407.75 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $408.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $408.60, up from $407.20 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 50 cents to close at a bid
$410.44.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.97 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Thursday's bid, and its lowest level since March
1987.
</TEXT>
