<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Gulf-Ship     01-06 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Ship,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Tanker Splits In Half After Mystery Explosion, Six Reported
Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Saudi Arabian tanker broke in two today
and its stern section sank after a mystery blast believed to have
been caused by a drifting mine left six crewmen dead, authorities
said.
   Shipping executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Greek captain of the 36,904-ton Sagheera was among those killed in
the explosion in the southern end of the gulf Thursday. Two other
men were listed as missing.
   They said 26 members of the crew made up of Greek officers and
Sri Lankan seamen were rescued Thursday from lifeboats by the Omani
Coast Guard.
   The Sagheera was ripped by an explosion as it was sailing empty
into the storm-whipped Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the Persian
Gulf, en route for the Saudi port of Mina Saud. The blast started a
fire aboard the tanker.
   Shipping sources said the vessel later split in two and that one
of two salvage tugs that went to aid the blazing tanker was towing
the bow section in the Gulf of Oman toward the Omani coast.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which
monitors shipping traffic around the world, reported an explosion in
the tanker's pump-room before it caught fire.
   It did not say what could have caused the blast. But U.S. Navy
officers have been warning for weeks that winter storms could tear
mines, laid during the Iran-Iraq war, loose from their moorings,
leaving them to drift into shipping lanes.
   Winds were gusting at more than 30 miles an hour in the gulf
Thursday, with waves as high as 30 feet.
   The U.S. Navy has estimated as many as 200 mines were still
believed to be in the gulf, mainly in northern waters, despite
mine-sweeping operations by the U.S. and other navies in the
strategic waterway.
   Several vessels were hit by mines during the Iran-Iraq conflict
before fighting was halted Aug. 20 when a United Nations-sponsored
cease-fire took effect.
   No ship has been confirmed to have hit a mine since the
cease-fire began.
   The Sagheera was one of more than 500 ships attacked during the
so-called ``tanker war,'' an offshoot of the gulf conflict in which
both sides raided merchant vessels in the waterway.
   The Saudi vessel was hit by Iranian gunboats April 4 last year,
but suffered only minor damage and none of its crewmen was hurt. It
was not known whether the Sagheera was manned by the same crew
Thursday.
</TEXT>
