<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0472 01-06 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0472,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Troops May Pull Out Of Cambodia By September</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, ``While it...'' to UPDATE
with Sihanouk comment. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Heng Samrin...'' ADDS 3 grafs
after last graf pvs, ``The guerrillas'...'' No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam will withdraw its remaining
50,000 troops from Cambodia by September if a political settlement
to the war is reached, Cambodian President Heng Samrin said today.
   While it previously did not name a month, Vietnam has repeatedly
pledged to withdraw all its troops earlier than its original target
date of 1990 if a political settlement could be reached.
   Resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk was quoted as saying,
however, that Vietnamese pledges of withdrawals are false, that
peace talks have failed and that Cambodia's future can be settled
only by continued fighting.
   Heng Samrin made the pullout offer in a speech in Cambodia's
capital of Phnom Penh to mark his government's first decade in
power. Vietnam installed the government on Jan. 7, 1979, two weeks
after launching a full-scale invasion of Cambodia.
   In the speech, broadcast by the official Phnom Penh radio and
monitored in Bangkok, he accused the guerrilla opposition of
prolonging the peace negotiations by making what he called the
``unreasonable'' demand that the Phnom Penh government be dismantled
before a general election is held.
   Heng Samrin repeated that his government wanted a settlement on
the basis of a Vietnamese withdrawal along with measures to prevent
the former fanatical Khmer Rouge regime from retaking power.
   He said that ``to contribute to achieving this solution,''
Vietnam and his government ``have agreed if there is a political
solution, all Vietnamese troops will be withdrawn from Cambodia no
later than September 1989. All the points above should be
implemented with effective international control.''
   Heng Samrin said his government hopes that other parties will
keep promises to end aid and sanctuary to the Khmer Rouge and the
other guerrilla groups. Such promises have been made by China, which
arms the guerrillas, and by Thailand, which gives them territory for
bases.
   Vietnam claims to have made annual partial withdrawals of its
troops since 1982. It says the largest came in 1988, when the
Vietnamese military high command, all advisers, and 50,000 soldiers
returned home. Vietnam says the remaining 50,000 troops will be
repatriated by 1990, whether there is a political solution or not.
   The guerrillas' demand that the Heng Samrin government be
dismantled has been one of the major barriers in the peace talks.
   The major peace forums have been meetings in France between
Cambodia's Prime Minister Hun Sen and Sihanouk, and multilateral
talks, the second round of which are scheduled in Indonesia next
month.
   The Khmer Rouge radio said Sihanouk on Jan. 1 sent a note to
countries backing the resistance, telling them that the Vietnamese
troop pullout ``is not real and not unconditional.'' The radio
broacast occurred Thursday and a text of it was seen in Bangkok
today.
   In the note, Sihanouk said the supposed pullouts were mere
rotations and about 120,000 Vietnamese soldiers remained in
Cambodia, 20,000 of them in the Cambodian army. Also, 40,000 troops
in the the Cambodian army are Vietnamese naturalized as Cambodians,
he said. In addition, nearly 1 million Vietnamese colonizers were
sent to Cambodia from 1978 to 1988, he claimed.
   The radio said Sihanouk ``further said that this issue can be
solved one way only, and that is through the efforts and sacrifices
on the battlefield in Cambodia by Cambodian resistance forces which
are intensifying their activities against the Vietnamese
aggressors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
