<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HelsinkiConference     01-06 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helsinki Conference,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Praises Human Rights Accord, Discounts Challenge By Romania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to the 35-nation
Helsinki review conference said today the meeting had achieved
historic agreements on human rights, but Hungary voiced fears that
Romania could ``torpedo'' the accord.
   In a surprise move, Romania on Thursday presented the conference
with 17 suggestions for deleting or changing the draft of a final
accord.
   A Western diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Romania is seeking to change or delete commitments to religious
freedom, the freedom of movement and clauses on emigration and
tourism.
   Hungary's Communist Party daily, Nepszabadsag, described the
Romanian demands as a ``diplomatic torpedo'' that could undo two
years of hard work in Vienna, where the 35-nation review conference
opened in November 1986.
   The newspaper added, however, that ``torpedoes do not always hit
their traget, and there have been instances of their returning to
where they have been launched.''
   Tensions between Hungary and Romania have been high for years,
particularly over the plan announced last year by the Romanian
government to raze thousands of ethnic Hungarian villages and
resettle residents in industrial centers.
   U.S. ambassador Warren Zimmermann played down the Romanian
demands over the human rights accord, saying they were merely
suggestions and noting that they had been rejected Thursday by
coordinators responsible for the draft accord.
   Zimmermann told a news conference that the draft of the final
accord was an ``excellent'' document that needed very few changes to
be acceptable to the United States.
   Under the consensus mechanism of the Helsinki review process, a
final accord must be approved by all 35 participating nations to
take effect.
   ``If we are able to achieve it, it will be a document that sets a
really historic set of markers in human rights, perhaps the most
far-reaching... ever,'' Zimmermann said.
   The United States, Britain and Canada still seek improvements in
the accord to guarantee that East bloc citizens can monitor their
nations' human rights and that new Soviet laws limiting emigration
on the ground of state secrecy will not apply to those already
waiting years to emigrate.
   Among the achievements of the Vienna conference, Zimmermann
noted, is a mechanism guaranteeing continuous East-West discussion
of human rights.
   There will be a human rights conference in Paris this summer, in
Copenhagen in 1990 and in Moscow in 1991.
   In addition, the draft accord entitles states signing the
Helsinki accords to raise any human rights matter with another
participant at any time.
   Delegates hope to end the Helsinki conference by mid-January,
paving the way for new East-West talks on reducing conventional
forces to begin in Vienna in February or March.
   Negotiators from the 16 NATO and seven Warsaw Pact nations were
still working today to finish a mandate for those talks by early
next week.
   Zimmermann said he expected ``a lot of quiet diplomacy'' to try
to reach an agreement before Jan. 17, when Austria has invited the
foreign ministers of 34 non-participant nations to a three-day
closing meeting of the Helsinki review conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
