<FIRST>r p PM-DukakisSpeech     01-06 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis Speech,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caustic Dukakis Speech Rallies Liberals, Riles Critics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, labeled passionless during
his failed presidential campaign, inspired liberal followers and
riled conservative critics with a suprisingly vitriolic State of the
State speech.
   Dukakis on Thursday night lashed out at his opponents as
``gutless wonders'' and said ``baloney'' to those who accuse the
state of overspending.
   Republican leaders and conservative Democrats said they found
some of the governor's remarks bitter and even tasteless.
   All sides agreed that Dukakis was signaling his determination to
push for new taxes when he releases his plan next week to address a
shortfall of at least $636 million in the state's $11.6 billion
budget.
   Despite the budget gap, the newly combative Dukakis promised
``we're going forward, not back'' with investments in the economy,
drug-free schools and the environment.
   Dukakis' 24-minute speech broadcast from the House Chamber was
interrupted 21 times for applause. The audience included
legislators, state officials and family members.
   Referring to his critics as ``the chronic complainers and the
gloom-and-doomers,'' the Democratic governor said: ``Well, I have a
message for them tonight, because they are the gutless wonders of
Massachusetts politics. I'm not going to let them get away with it,
and neither are you.''
   The statement drew the strongest applause of the night.
   Two days after his surprise announcement that he would not seek a
fourth term in 1990, Dukakis pledged to fight harder than ever for
his agenda.
   ``Some people may think that over the next two years I intend to
ride off into the sunset. Well, they're sadly mistaken,'' he said.
   Jim Braude, head of the liberal Tax Equity Alliance for
Massachusetts, said he was very encouraged. ``He painted a picture
of a very compassionate state and said with no equivocation that
compassion costs money,'' Braude said.
   Rep. John Flood, a conservative Democrat who is chairman of the
Taxation committee and who has blamed Dukakis for the fiscal
predicament, fumed that the ``gutless wonders'' remark was tasteless.
   In his speech, Dukakis briefly mentioned his presidential
campaign as ``the adventure of my life'' and made a veiled reference
to President-elect George Bush when he said: ``Tonight is a night
for tough talk _ and no lip reading.''
</TEXT>
