<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Recorder     01-06 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Recorder,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvage Team Finds Flight Recorder 13 Months After Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A salvage team searching the
floor of the Indian Ocean today found the cockpit voice recorder of
a South African Airways jet that crashed more than 13 months ago
near Mauritius, the government said.
   All 159 people aboard the Boeing 747 from Taipei, Taiwan, to
Johannesburg died in the Nov. 28, 1987 crash that occurred minutes
before the plane was to make a scheduled stop in Port Louis in the
island nation of Mauritius.
   South Africa has not released any explanation for the cause of
the crash, but it staged an elaborate search for the flight recorder
that has cost $6 million, accoring to the Department of Transport.
   The recovery ship Stena Workhorse, using a remote-controlled
mini-submarine, found the recorder 110 miles northeast of Mauritius
at a depth of 2.5 miles, said the minister of transport, Eli Louw.
He said the recorder would be brought to South Africa for
examination as soon as possible.
