<SECOND>PM-Calif Governor,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Will Not Seek Third Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0535 to change category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian has touched off
what could be a political free-for-all with the announcement he will
not seek re-election in 1990.
   The two-term Republican, first elected in 1982 against Los
Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley, said Thursday he has no ambition to set
``some record for longevity'' and will return to private life,
perhaps in business or law.
   He ruled out a post in President-elect Bush's administration,
saying, ``I have no interest whatsoever in going to Washington.''
   Three prominent Republicans and one Democrat immediately
announced that they were considering running for governor.
   Six other prominent politicians _ three in each party _ either
said they would have announcements soon or declined to comment on
rumors they were interested.
   The 60-year-old Deukmejian said he had planned from the beginning
to serve only two terms.
   Attorney General John Van de Kamp is widely viewed as the early
front-runner for the Democratic nomination for governor. He declined
to comment Thursday on his political plans but had declared late
last year that he intended to form an exploratory committee for a
gubernatorial campaign.
   Republican Pete Wilson, elected two months ago to his second term
in the U.S. Senate, also declined to say whether he will seek
Deukmejian's office.
   Former San Francisco Mayor Diane Feinstein, a Democrat, said
after Deukmejian's announcement that she was forming an exploratory
committee, and state Sen. Bill Campbell, former state Sen. H.L.
Richardson and Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl Gates said they were
considering seeking the GOP nomination.
   Baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth also has been mentioned as
a potential Republican candidate.
</TEXT>
