<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     01-06 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Promise To Leave Afghanistan By Deadline, Rebels Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's deputy foreign
minister promised today that the Red Army will be out of Afghanistan
by Feb. 15, an Afghan guerrilla leader said after meeting with him.
   However, minister Yuli Vorontsov appeared to be reneging on a
promise that Moscow would not insist on a postwar role for
Afghanistan's communist party, said Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, leader
of the rebel delegation at the meeting.
   The two sides held a second round of direct talks in the Pakistan
capital, and Mojaddidi said they agreeed to meet again ``in a few
days.''
   Vorontsov ``promised that they will withdraw on the 15th of
February. They confirmed this,'' the guerrilla leader told reporters
after the talks.
   Vorontsov refused comment, but when he arrived in Islamabad on
Wednesday, he said the withdrawal deadline could be pushed back if
the Moslem guerrillas continue fighting.
   ``They asked for a cease-fire several times, but we said a
cease-fire is not possible,'' said Mojaddidi. ``But we said we can
stop attacking your military forces when they are leaving
Afghanistan.''
   Moscow sent more than 100,000 soldiers into Afghanistan in 1979
to help the communist government in its war with the guerrillas.
Under a U.N.-mediated accord reached in April, the Kremlin promised
to withdraw its forces by Feb. 15. Half had been pulled out by
August.
   Vorontsov and the guerrillas were at an impasse on the postwar
role of the Marxist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, said
Mojaddidi.
   Despite earlier rebel demands that Moscow stop insisting there be
a part for the communists to play in a postwar government, Vorontsov
continued to make a pitch for the Soviet Union's proteges, the
Afghan leader said.
   ``They want the present regime to participate in the future
government,'' said Mojaddidi. ``But we can't (allow that).''
   The guerrilla fighters, based in Pakistan and Iran, agreed prior
to today's talks that President Najib of Afghanistan and his Marxist
party were anathema to peace.
   Vorontsov scheduled a news conference Saturday, the final day of
his four-day trip. He will also meet Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
on Saturday.
   Mojaddidi, who is chairman of a loose alliance of seven
Pakistani-based guerrilla parties, said the only agreement that came
out of today's talks was ``that we will continue the negotiations
after a few days.'' He did not say where they would meet.
   The first Soviet-guerrilla talks were held last month in the
Saudi Arabian resort city of Taif.
</TEXT>
