<FIRST>r a PM-FratSettlement     01-06 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frat Settlement,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraternity Agrees To Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fraternity whose members disrupted two
African studies classes at the University of Wisconsin has agreed to
pay more than $40,000 to settle a lawsuit accusing them of civil
rights violations.
   The University of Illinois chapter of Acacia denied in the
tentative agreement filed in federal court Thursday that the April 8
disruptions were racially motivated.
   But Anne Sulton, an attorney for students in the two classes,
likened the incident to a ``Ku Klux Klan night ride.''
   The fraternity agreed to pay $50 to each of the students in an
African languages class and $40 to those in a class on African
storytelling.
   Ruben Cotton and James Sommers, the students who brought the
class action lawsuit alleging that the disruptions were racially
motivated and deprived students of their civil rights, will receive
$2,500 and $750 respectively.
   Their lawyers said fraternity members called Cotton ``boy'' when
he tried to stop them from throwing stink bombs and disrupting a
class. Cotton is black.
   A professor said someone jumped on his back during a melee in his
class.
   The settlement is subject to approval by U.S. District Judge John
Shabaz.
   In August, a Dane County judge placed on probation seven
fraternity members who pleaded no contest to disorderly conduct and
unauthorized presence on university property.
   They were required to donate money to charity, volunteer time to
community organizations and write essays on black history.
</TEXT>
