<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     01-06 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Raid Marcos' House In Search Of Robbers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops searched the home of former
President Ferdinand Marcos today for soldiers who allegedly were
involved in a robbery in which four people were killed, officials
said.
   Marines in battle gear surrounded the mansion in San Juan, a
suburb of Manila, but they found nothing after a two-hour search,
said Col. Emiliano Templo, deputy chief of the Philippine
Constabulary's Capital Command.
   Armed men described as soldiers on Monday held up an armored van
carrying $350,000, and three of them were killed in a shootout with
police. The other robbers escaped after killing a police officer.
   Templo said the military obtained a warrant to search the
premises after a soldier allegedly involved in the robbery told
investigators the other suspects were using the Marcos house as
their hideout.
   Templo, who led the raid, said the search was hampered because
electricity in the house was cut off shortly after Marcos and his
family fled to Hawaii during the February 1986 civilian-military
uprising that ended his 20-year rule. He said the search was
conducted with lights brought by television crews.
   Looters stripped the house of its furnishings after the Marcoses
fled, and only the caretaker and a few security guards occupy the
house now, Templo said.
</TEXT>
