<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Christmas     01-06 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-Christmas,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serbian Media Carry Entire Christmas Message By Patriarch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patriarch German called today for an
end to Serbian suffering in the ethnically troubled province of
Kosovo. His Orthodox Christmas address was carried in full for the
first time by state-run media.
   Although the Serbian patriarch's Christmas addresses have been
carried in the state press since 1987, today was the first time
communist authorities allowed the entire message to be printed.
   German called for a prayer which would ``finally end ...
suffering on the Serbian Kosovo and Metohija.'' Metohija is the
traditional Serbian name for the region renamed Kosovo despite
opposition from the Serbian Orthodox church.
   Belgrade's Politika daily also quoted the head of the Serbian
Orthodox Church as repeating an earlier statement that ``the events
in Kosovo and Metohija represent an incurable wound for the Serbian
Orthodox church.''
   Today, the eve of Serbian Orthodox Christmas, Belgrade television
was expected to carry excerpts from the Patriarch's message, TV
sources said.
   The Orthodox Serbian minority claims that harassment by ethnic
Albanians is driving them from Kosovo, the ancient Serbian heartland
that borders Albania. More than 30,000 Slavs have migrated from the
region since 1981, when at least nine people died in ethnic violence.
   Moslem ethnic Albanians, who have the highest birthrate in
Europe, comprise about 90 percent of the population of the backward
southern Yugoslav province.
   There has been an increasingly open celebration of religious
holidays in Yugoslavia in recent years, coinciding with the
communists apparent inability to curb the worst economic and social
problems in history.
</TEXT>
