<HEAD>Four Die In Apartment Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through a five-story apartment
house undergoing renovation, killing four people and injuring five,
including a man who apparently jumped from the burning building,
authorities said today.
   ``The building looks like it's probably a total loss,'' said
Police Chief Richard J. Abele.
   About 150 to 200 firefighters battled the blaze Thursday night.
   The cause of the fire was not known, but it was believed to have
spread through an elevator shaft of the brick building, which was
being renovated, said Deputy Fire Marshal Michael Kirby.
   ``It had just been inspected. It had a full book of approvals,''
said Fire Chief Harold Lamphere. ``The (smoke) alarms were ringing.
Everything was working.''
   The last of the dead were removed from the building this morning,
authorities said.
   A man who suffered fractures when he apparently jumped from the
building was at Hartford Hospital, authorities said. His condition
was not available.
   Two people suffering from smoke inhalation were in fair condition
at William H. Backus Hospital, a spokeswoman said. A firefighter and
another person were treated for minor injuries.
