<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Crash 1stLd-Writethru   01-06 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tighter Security Announced; Lockerbie Buries Two Of Its Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details of airport security
checks. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``London's Evening...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tighter security measures ordered
after the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 took effect today at British
airports, causing some passenger delays while workers closely
searched carry-on baggage.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon announced the stepped-up
security Thursday after a meeting of the National Aviation Security
Committee in London.
   The new measures are aimed primarily at American carriers, and
passengers faced long lines to have their hand baggage examined
before boarding Pan Am and TWA flights at London's Heathrow Airport.
   ``I certainly believe that it's best to take a few extra
precuations and be safe, rather than rush things and be sorry,''
said Lee Godman who was traveling to Miami.
   Channon announced Thursday immediate ``further steps to increase
safety of the security of cargo, also mislaid luggage and also to
take further steps to tighten up the existing regulations on cabin
bags.''
   ``There will be more rigorous searching on American airlines, and
on any airline where we think the threat is commensurate, but at the
moment it will be American airlines,'' he said.
   He gave no other details but said he would soon take additional
measures to increase airline security.
   Channon's announcement came hours after Lockerbie buried two
townspeople killed when wreckage and blazing jet fuel from the New
York-bound Boeing 747 rained on the southern Scottish town Dec. 21.
   The explosion killed all 259 people on the plane and 11 on the
ground.
   London's Evening Standard newspaper on Thursday reported that
experts probing the crash were concentrating on 12 passengers
believed to have joined Flight 103 in London after arriving from
airports in the Middle East.
   ``The fear is that their baggage, checked in as destined for New
York at airports with much less stringent checks than London, may
have been put on to the doomed jet without further security tests,''
the paper said.
   There was no official comment on the report from Pan Am.
   The government on Thursday announced a $1.8 million rebuilding
program in Lockerbie, where buildings were destroyed by falling
wreckage and fire.
   In the small, close-knit town, a Requiem Mass was held Thursday
for one of the victims, 10-year-old Joanne Flannigan.
   Her parents are also counted among Lockerbie's 11 dead but their
bodies have not been found.
   Joanne is survived only by brothers Stephen, 14, who was fixing
her bicycle at a neighbor's house at the time of the crash, and
David, 20, who lives away from home.
   Later Thursday, a funeral service was held at All Saints
Episcopal Church for another victim, 81-year-old Mary Lancaster.
   Searchers have recovered 242 bodies, and by Thursday night had
released 164 of them for burial or other funeral arrangements.
   Officials say they believe some of the 28 still missing may have
been cremated in the fiery fuel-fed crash that left a 30-foot-deep
crater in the town.
</TEXT>
