<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-NaziVictims 1stLd-Writethru a0550 01-06 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Nazi Victims, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>German School Says Tissue From Nazi Victims Removed From Collection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 15th graf pvs, ``He was...'' to ADD that
AP was unable to reach Drews for comment. Pickup 16th graf pvs, ``Sandberger
was...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nazi-Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official at a leading university
today said two microscopic tissue samples used for medical education
may have come from the corpses of Nazi victims, but he denied the
practice was widespread.
   A report by the television network ARD that West German
universities still use body parts from Nazi victims for medical
instruction has touched off angry reaction from Israeli officials,
who called for an official investigation.
   But administrators at three West German universities said they
knew of no tissue samples from Nazi victims at their institutions,
and a fourth school _ Tuebingen _ said it has withdrawn from its
anatomy collection the two microscopic examples it had had in store.
Officials at a fifth West German university could not immediately be
reached for comment.
   Tuebingen and Heidelberg universities are at the center of the
furor caused by the ARD television report late Monday night.
   The Israeli media also picked up on the ARD report saying the two
universities use body parts from Nazi victims, including communists
and the mentally handicapped, for medical education.
   Georg Sandberger, Tuebingen University chancellor, today said the
ARD report is incorrect and that there was no widespread use of such
tissues at his university.
   ``We conducted an inquiry after the allegations. We found we had
only two items of microscopic tissues in our collection of anatomy
that may have come from the victims of the Nazi regime,'' Sandberger
said in a telephone interview from his home in Tuebingen.
``Subsequently, I have ordered those withdrawn from the collection.''
   Sandberger said records at the school indicate the two tissue
samples may have been taken from the corpses of ``a young Polish
woman and a young German who were decapitated in Stuttgart'' during
the Nazi regime.
   He said the tissues may have been left over from the times when
Nazis delivered corpses of their victims to universities for
anatomical study.
   Sandberger said, ``In our collection now there are neither body
parts nor tissues which we can trace to this (Nazi) time.''
   The AP attempted to reach Heidelberg University officials to
comment on the media allegations, but the institute was closed
because of a local holiday.
   The university chancellor, Siegfried Kraft, was vacationing in
the Black Forest and could not be reached.
   Sandberger said the media reports were ``mainly based on wrong
information which was given by one of our professors.'' He
apparently was referring to Professor Ulrich Drews.
   Israel TV quoted Drews as saying, ``Especially at our university,
these samples (taken from corpses of Nazi victims) are very valuable
for teaching.''
   He was further quoted as saying, ``They were prepared ... in an
almost artistic manner.''
   The AP attempted to reach Drews four times by telephone at his
home to ask for comment, but there was no answer. There was also no
answer at his office.
   Sandberger said he was ``embarrassed about these comments on the
tissue _ that they couldn't be removed (from the anatomy collection)
because they were wonderfully drafted.'' He added, ``This is not the
right attitude to have toward this issue.''
   Israel TV reported that more than a thousand bodies were sent to
German universities for use in medical education during the Nazis'
12-year rule.
   Sandberger said Tuebingen University had received some corpses
during that time but that they were all buried in a Tuebingen
cemetery after the war or handed to Allied occupation authorities.
   A number of West German universities have begun responding to the
media reports that use of the remains of Nazi victims for medical
education is a widespread occurrence.
   ``Since World War II there have been no samples here from people
executed or from the bodies of the persecuted,'' said Karl Zilles,
director of the Cologne University anatomy department.
   Spokesmen at Hamburg University and Berlin Free University also
said they know of no such samples at their schools and that their
anatomical collections stem from after the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
