<FIRST>r a PM-Hastings     01-06 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Has Health Problems As Impeachment Looms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings says he has a
blockage in his coronary arteries and may seek to delay his Senate
impeachment trial.
   ``I know this much _ my life comes before anybody's
impeachment,'' the 52-year-old judge said Thursday.
   Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King said Hastings'
caseload will be reduced out of concern for his health.
   Hastings has continued to preside over civil trials since the
House impeached him Aug. 3. Senate Rules Committee hearings on his
trial are set for Jan. 26.
   He is accused of conspiring to obtain a $150,000 bribe and lying
about it at his 1983 trial, at which he was acquitted. Hastings also
is accused of breaching confidentiality about a wiretap and bringing
disrepute on the courts.
   A two-thirds majority vote in the Senate is needed to convict
Hastings and remove him from the bench.
   Hastings said cardiac catherization Dec. 28 showed one artery is
75 percent blocked and another is 50 percent blocked. More tests are
scheduled for Jan. 12, he said.
   ``If my health, according to the physical, (is satisfactory), be
assured I'll be there bright-eyed and bushy-tailed and ready to
proceed,'' Hastings said. ``If not, nobody on Earth will cause me
to.''
