<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     01-06 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Shiite Militias Battle In South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias hammered each
other's positions in south Lebanon with artillery and grenades
today, and police said at least two people were wounded.
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran called on the Syrian-backed Amal
and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah militias to end the bloodshed, saying
``vengeance will not solve anything in Lebanon,'' according to the
Islamic Republic News Agency.
   Amal and Hezbollah fighters battled with mortars, guns and
grenades in Jbaa, Ein Bouswar, Jarjou and Louwaizeh, which are
mostly deserted villlages in southern Lebanon.
   One Amal militiaman and a civilian woman were wounded in the
fighting on the edge of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone,
north of its border with Lebanon, police said.
   The latest fighting, which came after two days of calm, brought
the casualty toll to 29 killed and 78 wounded since clashes between
the militias began Dec. 31, according to police.
   Khamenei accused the Americans and the Israelis of instigating
the fighting, according to the official Iranian agency, monitored in
Nicosia.
   ``We believe the confrontation between Hezbollah and Amal is not
natural. There are hands at work trying to implement the plans of
global arrogance against the people of Lebanon,'' the news agency
quoted Khameini as saying.
   ``Global arrogance'' is the phrase used by Iran for the United
States and its allies.
   Since Dec. 31, the two militias have battled in the southern
slums of Beirut and in south Lebanon. Syrian troops stopped the
violence in Beirut.
   Amal, Arabic for hope, and Hezbollah, or Party of God, are
struggling for dominance of the 1 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest
sect.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains an estimated
40,000 troops in the country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate. But it has no military presence in south Lebanon.
   Senior officials from both sides have been shuttling between
Damascus and Tehran in recent weeks in an apparent effort to dampen
the feuding.
</TEXT>
