<FIRST>r a PM-YolkYuks     01-06 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yolk Yuks,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post Office Sees No Humor In Radio Yolks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service didn't see the humor in a radio
station's egg-in-the-mail contest, fearing the yolk would end up on
them.
   Morning disc jockeys Glenn Beck and Clydie Clyde began a contest
this week that asked KRBE-FM listeners to send in breakfast meat and
a raw egg in a regular envelope with no padding. The first to arrive
unbroken was worth $1,004.
   Eleven envelopes arrived Thursday. Six were leaking yellow and
clear goo. Five arrived unscathed. ``I think that's pretty
amazing,'' Beck said.
   Postal officials, however, were not amused, fearing one of their
$900,000 sorting machines would get yucked up with yolk. They also
reminded station officials that regulations prohibit mailing of
perishable foods.
   The station invited the postmaster and the manager of the local
post office to appear on the radio show.
   ``Hopefully, it will smooth some feathers,'' said Jim Sartorius,
KRGE operations manager.
