<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Bishops     01-06 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Bishops,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>John Paul Raises 13 to Bishops Rank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Friday consecrated 13
new bishops, including an Italian who served as secretary to Pope
Paul VI.
   Five of the new bishops were from Italy, two from Spain, two from
Tanzania and one each from the Dominican Republic, India, Guatemala
and Trinidad and Tobago.
   The pope laid his hands and then a Bible on the heads of each of
the 13 men and said the prayer of ordination. The bishops each
received a ring and a red-trimmed miter hat from the pontiff.
   The oldest of the newly consecrated bishops is Pasquale Macchi,
65, who was an assistant to Pope Paul VI throughout his 15-year
term, which ended in 1978.
   Others consecrated bishops Friday were:
   _ Giovanni Lajolo, Italy, named secretary of the Administration
of the Patrimony of the Holy See.
   _ Francesco Marchisano, Italy, named secretary of the Pontifical
Commission for the Conservation of the Artistic and Historical
Patrimony.
   _ Justin T. Samba, Tanzania, named bishop of Musoma, Tanzania.
   _ John Mendes, Trinidad and Tobago, named auxiliary bishop of
Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago.
   _ Leon A. Tharmaraj, India, named bishop of Kottar, India.
   _ Tarcisius Nglalalekumtwa, Tanzania, named coadjutor bishop of
Sumbawanga, Tanzania.
