<FIRST>r i AM_BRF--Uganda-Rebels     01-06 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM_BRF--Uganda-Rebels,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>250 Rebels Killed In Army Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops killed 250 guerrillas
last month in an army offensive in northwestern Uganda, an official
report said Friday.
   Government troops engaged in three battles with rebels of the
Holy Spirit Movement in December that claimed the lives of 30
soldiers and wounded another 20, said the newspaper New Vision.
   Maj. Gen. Fred Rwigyema, deputy army commander, said the rebels
were forced to retreat and hide among the civilian population, the
report said.
   The latest casualty figures brought to more than 700 the number
of Holy Spirit rebels reported killed by the army since last year.
   The Holy Spirit Movement, one of nine rebel groups fighting the
government, was founded in 1986 by self-proclaimed warrior priestess
Alice Lakwena. Her fighters believe oil smeared on their chests
would ward off bullets and the stones they carried would explode
like grenades.
   Most of Lakwena's 7,000 fighters have been killed and she has
escaped to Kenya.
</TEXT>
