<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Aliens     01-06 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Aliens,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nigeria Denies It Planned To Deport Hundreds For Illegal Mining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 West Africans stranded on
Nigeria's border with Benin were moved to Lagos on Friday after the
government denied it had planned to deport them for illegal mining.
   The foreigners, among 2,000 people arrested last week on charges
of illegal mining precious gems in the northern state of Kaduna,
said the government of Benin had refused them passage through its
territory.
   Internal Affairs Minister John Shagaya denied Nigeria intended to
deport them and said they were fleeing prosecution.
   The group included 201 people from Senegal, 191 from Mauritania,
27 from Mali, six from Gambia, four from Zaire and three from Sierra
Leone.
   The foreigners were to be sheltered at a trade center on the
outskirts of Lagos, where they were to be questioned, Shagaya said.
He said those found innocent would be allowed to return to their
homes in Nigeria.
</TEXT>
