<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AX7, NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Martha Layne Collins, who
taught high school before getting into politics, may be returning to
the classroom at Harvard University.
   Associates say Collins is talking to Harvard officials about a
teaching fellowship, The (Louisville) Courier-Journal reported
Thursday. The former governor was away from her Lexington office
Friday and could not be reached for comment.
   Steve Singer, director of press relations for Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government, refused to say whether Collins was
being considered for a fellowship.
   However, he said the school ``often has fellows who come from top
positions in government to teach a non-credit study group to
graduates and undergraduates. If Governor Collins were coming here,
that's what she would be doing.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentinian writer Ernesto Sabato was named
Friday to receive the 1989 Jerusalem Prize, which is awarded to an
author whose work focuses on the freedom of the individual.
   The decision was announced by the office of Jerusalem Mayor Teddy
Kollek.
   The prize, a scroll and $5,000, is to be given during the
Jerusalem International Book Fair in March.
   The jury was headed by Abba Eban, the former Israeli foreign
minister. Previous award winners include V.S. Naipaul, Graham
Greene, Simone de Beauvoir and Eugene Ionesco.
   Sabato, 77, originally a physicist, wrote his first novel, ``The
Silent Well,'' while doing post-graduate studies in Paris. In 1943
he abandoned scientific work to devote himself to writing. His
fictional works include ``The Tunnel,'' ``Of Heroes and Graves'' and
``Abadon, the Exterminator.''
   In 1983, Sabato was appointed by Argentinian President Raul
Alfonsin to head the public committee investigating the thousands of
Argentinians who were abducted, and presumed murdered, during the
earlier military regime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHELTENHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ski-jumper Eddie ``The Eagle''
Edwards, the world's best-loved Olympic loser, has been hospitalized
again for treatment of injuries he sustained in an Austrian training
session.
   After leaving an Innsbruck hospital Thursday, Edwards returned
home to western England and checked into Cheltenham General
Hospital. His mother, Janette Edwards, said the hapless ski jumper
``is very stiff from his injuries.''
   Edwards broke his collar bone and bruised a kidney when he took a
tumble Tuesday while training for a World Cup ski event.
   In a statement, Cheltenham General Hospital said Edwards was
being kept for observation: ``It is not expected to be for long,
probably a few days. He is comfortable.''
   In last winter's Calgary Olympics, the 24-year-old plasterer came
last in the 90-meter and 70-meter events and rocketed to instant
fame under the tag ``Eddie The Eagle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor says she never wants to hear the
name of Delta Air Lines again _ and Delta officials probably feel
the same way about her.
   Police escorted the 69-year-old entertainer off a Delta flight
Thursday night after she refused to keep her dogs in travel kennels,
an airline spokesman said.
   The confrontation occurred during a stopover in Atlanta. Airline
officials said Ms. Gabor, who was traveling from Los Angeles to her
home in Palm Beach, Fla., let two Shih Tzu dogs out of their kennels
in the first-class section of the Delta jet.
   ``The Delta agent came aboard,'' airline spokesman William D.
Berry said. ``He asked her six times to comply. She refused to
comply. Each time he was responded to with considerable vulgarity.''
   Atlanta police were then called to escort Ms. Gabor off the
aircraft.
   Ms. Gabor contended the dogs were not disturbing anyone, and said
the Delta agent ``was screaming at me like I was some criminal.''
   ``I was so upset you can't imagine. This is not the end of
this,'' she said before boarding an Eastern Airlines flight to
complete the trip.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheelah Ryan, winner of the nation's
single biggest lottery jackpot, has formed a foundation to help the
needy with some of her $55.1 million.
   ``It's a dream I want to live on long after I'm gone,'' Ms. Ryan
said Thursday in announcing the formation of the private, non-profit
Ryan Foundation.
   Ms. Ryan, 63, of Winter Springs, said the foundation will provide
shelter for the homeless, help the elderly, feed the hungry and
protect abused women and children.
   The former real estate saleswoman won the Florida jackpot in
September. Although other jackpots since then have exceeded $55.1
million, they have been split among multiple winners.
   Ms. Ryan said she kicked off her foundation with ``a substantial
sum'' of her winnings.
</TEXT>
