<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ElkHeads     01-06 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Elk Heads,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elk Heads Dumped at Newspaper Office in Protest Over Indian Hunting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven bloody animal heads, apparently
from deer and elk, were dumped outside a newspaper office with a
note demanding an investigation of hunting by Indians.
   The Morning News Tribune of Tacoma reported that the heads were
left Thursday night at the doorstep of the paper's office in this
suburb between Seattle and Tacoma.
   ``These remains were gathered from the area of Enumclaw in a
single day,'' the unsigned, typewritten note read. ``God only knows
how many have been killed by Indian hunters. This is only a sample.
   ``The elk and deer are being slaughtered by the Indians because
it has been allowed by the Washington State Game Department and our
governor.''
   ``The most we have is a case of illegal dumping,'' said King
County Police officer Tom Davis, adding there were no suspects.
   Many hunters have been upset by a state agreement to allow
Indians covered by federal treaties to hunt on state lands, subject
to tribal restrictions, outside the seasons that apply to
non-Indians.
</TEXT>
