<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Software     01-06 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Software,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Company, Chinese Form Software Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Friday announced it has set up a joint
venture with a U.S. company to develop computer software for
international markets.
   The company, Astro-UniHorn Computer Technology Co., is a
conglomerate of UniHorn Inc., a San Francisco-based subsidiary of
Unison Inc.; the Chinese aerospace ministry's six research
institutes; and the Great Wall Industry Corp. Several thousand
Chinese experts working for the ministry have developed software
that ``is very interesting and can be commercialized,'' said the
vice president of UniHorn, James H. Spear Jr.
   Among the new products the new company is to develop is software
that enables computers to do engineering design work, Spear said.
   He said UniHorn sought out the Chinese partners because of their
low-cost expertise.
   Unison has four other joint ventures in China, including the
Great Wall Hotel in Beijing, one of the city's largest hotels.
