<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0510 01-06 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0510,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Plans to Call Texas Woman Who Said Hedda Abused Lisa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with teacher saying she saw a
bruise but no signs of abuse. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `DiLuzio said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher testified today at the murder trial of
Joel Steinberg that she once noticed a small bruise on the face of
Lisa Steinberg but never saw any signs that the 6-year-old was being
abused.
   Steinberg is charged with fatally beating the girl, whom he
adopted illegally.
   The teacher, Elizabeth Kasowitz, said that when she questioned
Lisa about the bruise under her eye, the girl told her that her
little brother had punched her.
   ``Did she seem natural?'' asked Steinberg's lawyer, Ira London.
   ``Yes. She said it with a smile. It seemed like a plausible
explanation.''
   ``We always question children when we see visible marks,'' added
Kasowitz, a teacher for 16 years.
   Kasowitz said she and Lisa talked about the bruise a few days
before Halloween in 1987. Days later, Lisa was removed unconscious
from the apartment of Steinberg and his lover, Hedda Nussbaum. She
died of brain injuries three days later.
   Kasowitz said that she had attended faculty conferences and read
newsletters on how to spot signs that a child is being abused or
getting improper care.
   ``Did you see any of the signs on Lisa Steinberg when she was
your student?'' said London.
   ``No,'' said Kasowitz.
   The teacher said that during the time she knew Lisa, the child
seemed happy and displayed no changes in personality or behavior.
She said Lisa was late more frequently toward the end of the term
but that she did not consider the latenesses excessive.
   Another of Steinberg's lawyers, Adrian DiLuzio, said Thursday
that the defense would call a cabaret singer from Dallas who will
say she saw Ms. Nussbaum abuse Lisa.
   The first-grader's death in an affluent household led to a
re-examination of the duty and ability of neighbors, teachers and
social workers to recognize and report evidence of child abuse.
   Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer, denies that he hit the child, but
Ms. Nussbaum, the prosecution's chief witness, said he told her the
night Lisa was fatally injured that he had ``knocked Lisa down and
she didn't want to get up.''
   The cabaret singer, Marilyn Walton, has said in TV interviews
that Ms. Nussbaum was jealous of Lisa. She also has said Ms.
Nussbaum wanted Steinberg's name and money and was upset that she
didn't get them.
   DiLuzio said Ms. Walton, who met the defendant several years ago
through her attorney, will testify that ``she did observe Hedda
Nussbaum mistreat the child on at least one occasion'' in 1983 or
1984.
   ``She's going to have some comments as to Joel's state of mind
with respect to the child and why Joel was always with the child _
because he was afraid to leave the child with Hedda,'' DiLuzio said
outside court.
   On another matter, prosecutors said they were considering asking
judge Harold J. Rothwax to drop the first-degree manslaughter charge
against Steinberg because their case is based on the theory that he
fatally beat Lisa out of recklessness and depraved indifference, not
because he intended to.
   First-degree manslaughter is charged when a defendant intends to
cause physical harm to a victim and, in doing so, ends up killing
the victim. The prosecution said it was considering requesting the
charge be dropped to avoid confusing the jury.
   ``Our theory is that the murder was depraved and not
intentional,'' said Peter Casolaro, an assistant Manhattan district
attorney.
   ``If they want to do that then I would be inclined to agree to
it, too,'' said DiLuzio.
   Rothwax has said he would drop the first-degree manslaughter
charge if both sides agreed.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former children's book editor, testified for
seven days as a prosecution witness. She had been charged with
Lisa's murder along with Steinberg but the charges were dropped and
she became a state's witness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
