<DOCNO> AP890106-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel Bjt   01-06 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, Bjt,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Radicals Form Anti-PLO Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab radicals announced Friday the formation of
a new anti-PLO alliance in the occupied territories that includes
Moslem fundamentalists and pro-Syrian extremists opposed to Yasser
Arafat's recent peace overtures.
   Palestinians in Bethlehem and the surrounding Christian villages,
meanwhile, observed a general strike to mark the day Orthodox
Christians celebrate Christmas. Graffiti painted on buildings called
for an escalation of the Arab uprising.
   Also Friday, police said they suspected Palestinian nationalists
were responsible for the killing of an Israeli shot to death in the
occupied West Bank the night before.
   Israeli hikers clashed with Arabs as they made their way past the
occupied West Bank village of Beit Inan on Friday, Israel Radio
said. The hikers opened fire at youths, who hurled large rocks at
them, but there were no reports of injuries, Israel Radio said.
   Soldiers evacuated the seven hikers, all of whom live on Jewish
West Bank settlements near Beit Inan, north of Jerusalem. Police
detained them briefly for questioning and confiscated their
firearms, the radio said.
   In a leaflet issued Friday, the Palestinian radicals accused
Arafat of ``selling out Palestine to imperialism and Zionism'' by
announcing he recognized Israel and renounced terrorism at a news
conference in Geneva last month.
   ``We demand the establishment of a militant leadership to replace
the diminishing leadership of Yasser Arafat,'' said the leaflet,
which was signed by the United National Front in Occupied Palestine.
   The group is an alliance of Islamic extremists and pro-Syrian
radicals, including members of Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command and Abu Moussa's breakaway
faction of Arafat's mainstream Fatah.
   The leaflet said the group ``rejected all surrenderist
solutions'' and advocated ``liberating the whole of Palestine
through armed struggle.''
   ``There can be no reconciliation with the Israeli killers and no
negotiations with Zionist criminals,'' the document said. ``We
oppose any kind of political settlement, whatever its source, and
consider negotiation with the enemy to be a grave treason and
unforgivable crime.''
   The leaflet also called for the formation of a new Palestine
National Council led by Palestinian militants who advocate armed
struggle.
   The present council, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
parliament in exile, adopted a declaration of independence in
November that implicitly recognized Israel.
   Pro-Syrian Palestinians said the new alliance was the result of
increasing cooperation between the two groups in recent months.
   ``The PLO has been moving from one mistake to another. We totally
reject the PLO's political compromises,'' said Sufian Khatib, a
Jerusalem doctor who opposes Arafat. ``There is a need to make
corrections in the PLO political line.''
   Also Friday, merchants closed businesses and all public
transportation was halted in Bethlehem and the nearby Christian
villages of Beit Jalla and Beit Sahour in compliance with a general
strike called by PLO-backed leaders of the Arab uprising.
   It was called to coincide with Friday's celebration of the
Orthodox Christian Christmas. A procession through Bethlehem by the
Greek Orthodox patriarch was subdued and traditional Christmas
decorations were absent.
   A cluster of about 70 Greek Orthodox worshipers, almost all of
them Palestinians, attended Christmas Mass at the Church of the
Nativity, built on the site where tradition says Jesus was born.
   The number of participants was down sharply from the usual
several hundred worshipers who have filled the church for past
Orthodox Christmas celebrations. The service was broadcast on
loudspeakers erected in Manger Square, which was empty except for
dozens of Israeli soldiers on patrol.
   A leaflet last month by underground leaders of the uprising
called for strikes on the Western churches' Christmas Eve and Jan. 6
to express sympathy for the suffering of Palestinians in the revolt.
   At least 347 Palestinians have died in the nearly 13-month
rebellion. Fourteen Israelis also have died.
   In other developments, Israel Radio said security forces suspect
Palestinians kidnapped and murdered Shmuel Edri, 42, a taxi driver
from the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva.
   Edri's body was found Thursday night at a junction near the
Jewish settlement of Yakir, about 24 miles north of Jerusalem. A
police spokesman said he was shot twice in the chest with a 9mm
pistol.
   Police confirmed they are considering nationalist motivations but
said their investigation has reached no definite conclusion.
   ``All directions in the investigation are still open,'' said the
chief of police in the northern section of the West Bank, Chaim
Malka.
   Police first noted Edri's police record as a possible sign the
murder was criminally motivated, but Malka later told Israel Radio:
``His criminal record was from the 1970s, not the 1980s, and his
crimes were not that great.''
   A police spokesman said Edri's taxi was found 1{ miles from where
he was killed.
</TEXT>
