<HEAD>Chicago Mayor Admits Late Income Tax Filing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer says he filed some federal
income tax returns late, but says he violated no laws and owed the
government no money.
   Sawyer blamed the late filings in part on his accountant's
frequent hospitalization, but his political rivals were quick to
criticize the delays.
   ``I would never try to escape an obligation to file my taxes,''
Sawyer told television station WBBM, which disclosed the mayor's tax
problems Thursday. ``They were late filing(s) and I admit that, but
they were filed.''
   WBBM reported that Sawyer's return for 1986 was filed more than a
year late, and said he also missed the deadline for filing his 1987
return. Both were filed last summer, the report said.
   The Internal Revenue Service also audited Sawyer's past returns
when he filed the late returns, and collected about $200 in back
taxes, the station said.
   Sawyer was elected by City Council a year ago to succeed Harold
Washington, who died of a heart attack. He is a candidate in the
Feb. 28 Democratic mayoral primary, seeking to fill the last two
years of Washington's term.
   Sawyer said the accountant, whom he did not identify, is a
diabetic who was frequently hospitalized. WBBM said Sawyer's
separation from his wife also left him without some necessary
documents.
   One of Sawyer's challengers, Alderman Lawrence Bloom, said, ``I
file my taxes on time; I think the voters expect everyone to file
their taxes on time, and the mayor should be no exception.''
