<HEAD>Inmate Charged With Robbing Banks on His Lunch Hour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf to CORRECT crime to manslaughter sted
robbery.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate on a work-release program has
been charged with robbing banks on his lunch hour.
   Lawrence Terry Jordan, 39, who worked as a laborer at a state
maintenance complex, was charged Wednesday in two hold-ups Nov. 28
and Dec. 9 in which a man who said he had a bomb stole a total of
$3,230, authorities said.
   Jordan was charged after he began offering cash gifts to friends
and a corrections officer saw a broadcast about the holdups and
recognized him, authorities said.
   Inmates at the maintenance complex are dropped at their work
sites in the morning and picked up in the evening. There are no
restrictions on where they can go to eat, said Corrections
Department spokesman Francis X. Archibald.
   Jordan, who is serving a 15-year sentence for manslaughter, was
transferred after his arrest from a dormitory-type work center to a
prison cell, Archibald said.
   Jordan began his sentence in 1981 and entered the work-release
program in 1984, said Archibald. The spokesman defended the 23-year
program, saying it has had few problems and allows inmates to help
``pay their room and board.''
