<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-UN 3rdLd-Writethru   01-06 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-UN, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0601,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Shows Pictures It Says Prove Self-Defense; Soviets Condemn Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with another photo, more quotes from U.S. and Libya.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters today
showed the Security Council large photographs showing what he said
were missiles under the wings of a Libyan jet shot down by U.S.
forces.
   ``We have photographs that show the planes were armed,'' Walters
said as two pictures, about 16-by-20 inches, were passed around.
   ``The missile parts show quite clearly. There were two different
types of missiles on the aircraft wings and hanging from other parts
of the fuselage,'' he said in an angry tone of voice.
   Libyan Ambassador Ali Sunni Muntasser refused to look at the
photographs when they were handed to him. He brushed them aside and
told reporters later they are ``all fakes.'' Walters denied it.
   Walters said the pictures were taken from a videotape shot inside
one of the two Navy F-14 jet fighters that shot down two Libyan
MiG-23s on Wednesday over the Mediterranean Sea.
   The U.S. planes ``were aggressively and hostilely challenged by
the Libyan air force,'' he said. The facts and the conversations of
the U.S. cockpit crews ``make it all the more clear that they acted
in self-defense.''
   Libya maintains its jets were unarmed and did not act in a
hostile manner.
   Earlier, the Soviet ambassador told the council the U.S. action
was ``absolutely unfounded'' and erodes the possibilities of peace
in the Middle East.
   ``Nobody attacked the aircraft or ships of the United States,''
Alexander M. Belonogov said after the council resumed discussion on
Libya's demand that it condemn the U.S. action. A vote on the
condemnation was not expected before the weekend.
   ``We cannot say the U.S. is entitled to open fire on aircraft of
another state simply because those aircraft have come close to one
another in international airspace,'' the Soviet representative said.
   Belonogov, who has blamed the incident in part on the U.S.
military presence in the Mediterranean, said the Soviet Union would
pull its navy from the waterway if the United States did the same.
   On Thursday, the Pentagon released the videotape it says was shot
from inside one of the U.S. jets. It shows one Libyan plane carrying
four missiles. The videotape showed the U.S. fighters tried
high-speed maneuvers five times to avoid the MiG planes before they
fired.
   Outside the council chamber, Walters rejected suggestions that
the photographs, blow-ups of the videotape, were doctored.
   ``If you want to believe there is nothing here, you can't because
there is something here,'' he said. ``Do you think this is a bouquet
of flowers hanging under the wing?'' he asked reporters.
   The U.S. action was deplored by all those who spoke this morning,
including Brazil, Madagascar, Nepal, Nicaragua and Uganda. On
Thursday, six speakers, representing the Arab League, Burkina Faso,
Bahrain, Cuba, Syria, and Tunisia, condemned the U.S. action.
   Walters, the last on today's list of scheduled speakers, said the
United States resents ``being taught the norms of international
behavior by nations governed by various forms of military or
civilian one-party dictatorships.''
   Libya wants the 15-member Security Council, the most powerful
U.N. body, to formally condemn the U.S. military action. Not all the
speakers are from member nations.
   A resolution of condemnation was expected to be vetoed by the
United States and Britain, two of the five permanent council
members. Permanent members, who also include the Soviet Union,
China, and France, have veto power.
   Belonogov said the U.S. military action ``is no way in accord
with the processes which are now occurring in the international
arena. It also is contradictory to the general tendency to shift the
Middle East process from a deadlock, thanks to the beginning of the
American-Palestinian dialogue.''
   ``We cannot agree that the United States should arrogate to
itself the right to punish or threaten any sovereign state that it
does not like, like Libya. Whatever the pretext, the use of force is
contrary to international law,' he said.
   Libya and the United States clashed sharply over the facts of the
incident when the emergency council session began Thursday.
   Muntasser, who sought the urgent meeting, called the U.S. action
a ``premediated act of aggression and a prelude to large-scale
aggression'' against economic and military installations.
   U.S. representative Herberg S. Okun told the council the U.S.
jets that shot down the Libyans faced ``imminent threat of being
shot down by the intercepting Libyan aircraft.''
</TEXT>
