<FIRST>r i AM-China-Africans     01-06 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Africans,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Africans Boycott Classes, Demand Protection; Diplomats Arrive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African students boycotted classes at a Beijing
college for a third day Friday to demand China release three
Africans detained after a racial brawl in Nanking.
   The 500 boycotting students at Beijing Languages Institute
demanded protection after Chinese students at the school distributed
anti-African leaflets. The Chinese claim an African male student
assaulted a Chinese woman student there Jan. 1, a charge the
Africans deny.
   The students also called on Beijing to change the Chinese name
for Africa, which literally means ``bad continent.''
   Officials at Beijing Languages Institute met representatives of
boycotting students Thursday and Friday but reached no agreement.
   African diplomats from Beijing arrived Friday in Nanking, where a
Dec. 24 clash between African and Chinese students triggered
protests and racial unrest in several other cities.
   The delegation included Congolese Ambassador Gabriel Emouengue
and Kwadwo Kwakye, acting head of the Ghana Embassy.
   Wills Tembo of Zambia, a student at Nanking's Hehai University,
said he and most of the approximately 140 African students in the
city plan to ask the diplomats to arrange for them to leave China.
   ``We are homebound,'' Tembo said in a telephone interview.
   Also Friday, Hehai University President Liang Ruiju denied
African students' claims the school now requires them to introduce
all Chinese girlfriends to school officials.
   ``It is nonsense,'' Liang said in an interview on state
television. He said the university encouraged friendly exchanges
between Chinese and foreign students, but accused the Africans of
breaking rules by bringing girlfriends to their dormitories.
   He said Chinese students who chanted offensive slogans about
Africans would be criticized and ``educated.'' It was the first
criticism by a Chinese official of Chinese students' behavior since
the unrest began.
   Liang accused some Western media of issuing ``distorted and
fictitious'' reports about the unrest.
   The trouble was caused by African students' dating of Chinese
women. Africans at Hehai tried to bring several Chinese dates to the
school's Christmas Eve dance but, according to officials, refused to
register their names in keeping with regulations.
   A fight broke out in which 11 Chinese and two Africans were
injured by official count.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Thursday three African
students detained by police have admitted they broke the law.
   One accused of seriously injuring a Hehai employee was under
arrest and apparently faces trial. Two others were accused of trying
to ``stir up trouble'' and were given 15 days' ``disciplinary
detention,'' Xinhua said. A fourth detained African was released,
apparently without charges.
   Following the fight, thousands of Chinese students stoned
Africans' dormitories at Hehai and other Nanking schools. Thousands
of young Chinese swarmed through city streets shouting slogans such
as ``Beat the black devils!''
   By Friday, all Nanking's African students had returned to their
schools following a stay at a suburban guesthouse.
   Police forced them to go to the guesthouse Dec. 27 when they
tried to board a train for Beijing. On Saturday, about 400 police
converged on the guesthouse, took four Africans into custody and
forced others to go back to school.
   African students and diplomats said the police attacked the group
at the guesthouse with electric cattle prods and wooden clubs, but
Chinese officials deny that.
   Many African students complain Chinese regularly discriminate
against them.
   Most of the approximately 1,500 African students in China are men
and social contacts with Chinese women frequently cause tension.
They study a wide range of subjects from the Chinese language to
engineering.
   Chinese also resent that Africans, many from countries as poor as
China, receive far better food and lodging than Chinese students.
   Chinese officials deny any prejudice, and say their long-standing
policy of giving scholarships to Africans shows China's solidarity
with the Third World.
</TEXT>
