<HEAD>Developer Fined For Disturbing Bald Eagles' Nest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined a developer for disturbing the
nest of a pair of bald eagles, an endangered species he claimed took
up residence in his $9 million subdivision after it was 90 percent
complete.
   Stephen M. Fedders was fined $4,000 Thursday and his company,
Flotilla Inc., was ordered to pay $20,000. He also must perform 100
hours of community service in a wildlife protection program under
terms of a plea agreement.
   Fedders pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of disturbing the
nest on Dec. 28, 1987.
   Someone tipped off state wildlife officers that the nest was
disturbed and Fedders was forced to devote 40 of the project's 176
acres as a preserve. The developer claimed the state's demand makes
it impossible to complete or sell his Braden River Lake subdivision
and he is on the brink of bankruptcy.
   Fedders admitted telling workers to continue to work near the
tree where the eagles had nested to try to frighten them off, but
denied destroying the nest. He said he didn't know who rocked the
tree with a bulldozer or who scaled the pine and removed the nest.
   The birds built a new nest, and the agency ordered Fedders to
create a 750-foot buffer zone around the site.
</TEXT>
