<HEAD>Panel Restores Teaching Credentials of Ex-Defendant In Molestation
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state commission today restored the
teaching credentials of a former defendant in the McMartin
Pre-School molestation case, entitling her to teach deaf and
learning-disabled children.
   The Commission on Teacher Credentialing voted 7-6, with one
abstention, to abide by the opinion of an administrative law judge
who found no reason to withhold Peggy Ann Buckey's credentials.
There was no debate or comment.
   Ms. Buckey, 32, was a teacher in the Anaheim Union High School
District in 1984 when she and six others were charged with molesting
toddlers at the now-defunct Manhattan Beach preschool. The
commission suspended her credentials.
   Charges against Ms. Buckey and four others were dropped in 1986
for lack of evidence.
   The remaining defendants _ Ms. Buckey's brother, Ray Buckey, 30,
and mother, 65-year-old Peggy McMartin Buckey _ are on trial on 65
child molestation counts.
   Ms. Buckey sued in 1987 to regain her secondary and special
education teaching certificates allowing her to teach deaf and
learning-disabled children. She has been working as a paralegal for
her brother's lawyer.
   Judge Ronald M. Gruen, in a ruling issued Thursday, said no cause
exists for denying her credentials.
   The judge, who presided over a hearing that included child
witnesses, sharply criticized testimony offered by the state
accusing Ms. Buckey of child molestation.
   ``It's great,'' Ms. Buckey said of the judge's ruling. ``I'm
overjoyed. It's the first good news we've had in five years.''
</TEXT>
