<FIRST>r a AM-AmbushConvictions     01-06 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ambush Convictions,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Court Upholds Convictions of UAW Members in Ambush Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday upheld the
convictions and sentences of four United Mine Workers members found
guilty of fatally shooting a non-union coal truck driver in an
ambush during a 1985 strike.
   The four participated in the slaying of Hayes West on May 29,
1985, in Pike County, Ky., federal prosecutors said. They were
convicted in U.S. District Court of endangering human life by
disabling a vehicle used in interstate commerce with reckless
disregard for human life, resulting in the death of West and the
injury of a non-union driver who was helping deliver coal.
   The four also were convicted of carrying a firearm during
commission of a felony. They received prison sentences ranging from
30 to 45 years.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously upheld the December 1987 convictions of James Darryl
Smith, Donnie Thornsbury and his cousin David Russell Thornsbury,
all of Canada, Ky., and Arnold Ray Heightland of Columbus, Ohio.
   The attorney for the defendants, all of whom remain in federal
custody, had sought to have the convictions thrown out. Edwin J.
Walbourn III disputed the prosecutors' definition of ``interstate
commerce'' and said the matter was not within federal jurisdiction
because West's truck did not, and was not scheduled to, carry cargo
across a state line when he was fired upon.
   The appeals court upheld the prosecutors' interpretation of a
federal law used to convict the men that held that West's truck was
part of interstate commerce because it hauled coal destined for
interstate shipment through West Virginia and Virgina.
   Walbourn was in court Friday and unavailable for comment on
whether he would appeal again.
</TEXT>
