<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Prisoners     01-06 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Prisoners,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Additional Political Prisoners To be Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban government has agreed to release 44
political prisoners it previously said would be exempt from a policy
under which all such detainees would be set free, according to
Western diplomats.
   The government had said initially the 44, many of whom had
engaged in armed insurrection against the regime, were too dangerous
to be released.
   In April, President Fidel Castro had promised to release all the
country's political prisoners, estimated by government officials to
be about 450.
   Since then, about 250 have been released and many have been
allowed to settle in the United States. Of the remaining 200 or so,
about 120 have been interviewed by American officials to determine
whether they wish to emigrate to the United States and their
eligibility for U.S. residency.
   U.S. officials are attempting to arrange interviews with the
remaining 80, who include the 44 who previously had been exempted
from the prisoner release policy.
   Cuban officials have not formally notified the United States
about the changed status of the 44 but did inform the U.S. Catholic
Conference about the new policy in November.
   Castro announced plans to release all political prisoners last
April during a visit by New York Cardinal John J. O'Connor.
   Castro had said the political prisoner release would be carried
out only if the United States agreed to give them residency papers.
   But the Western diplomats, who insisted on anonymity, said a
number prisoners were released even though they expressed a
preference for remaining in Cuba.
   Dissident sources rejected the suggestion that Cuba will be free
of political prisoners once all 450 are released.
   The sources, who asked not to be identified, said the government
routinely trumps up charges against politically unreliable Cubans
and then incarcerates them with common criminals. They offered no
proof that the government engages in such practices.
   The Western diplomats said they believe there are hundreds of
Cubans who can be described as political prisoners but whom the
Cuban government does not categorize as such.
   Included are Cubans who are serving out jail terms for trying
illegally to escape the island by boat or other means.
   Castro has acknowledged that in the early years of the
revolution, there were as many as 15,000 political prisoners.
</TEXT>
