<FIRST>r i AM-SharkSoup 1stLd-Writethru a0585 01-06 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shark Soup, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0585,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warn of Fake Shark's Fin Soup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT spelling of ladling.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fake designer clothes and other imitation brand
name goods are nothing new in Hong Kong, but now the government says
some restaurants are ladling out phony shark's fin soup.
   K.S. Tong, deputy commissioner of the Customs and Excise
Department, said Friday that enough of the imitation product to make
at least 1 million bowls of the prized soup was imported from
Singapore and Japan in the first nine months of 1988.
   The fake product _ a gelatin concoction that costs roughly
one-fifth the price of average-quality shark's fin _ is used in
``majority of lower class restaurants'' that sell the soup, he said.
   An ordinary bowl of shark's fin soup, which aficionados believe
can help preserve one's youth, can cost as little as $5 or less,
Tong said. Top-quality shark's fin soup, however, can run up to
about $35 a bowl.
   Tong believes some restaurants can offer the soup at the lower
prices only by mixing the phony product with the real shark's fins.
   Serving a soup containing a mixture of the gelatin and shark's
fin is not illegal unless the customer specifically requests genuine
shark's fin, Tong said.
   The official said the department and the Consumer Council intend
to conduct a survey to determine how widespread the use of phony
shark's fin is.
</TEXT>
