<FIRST>r a AM-CadetDeath     01-06 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cadet Death,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Settles Lawsuit Against Maritime Academy In Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a cadet killed by a mob
while on a training cruise on a Portuguese island have settled a
lawsuit for an undisclosed sum, attorneys said Friday.
   Leroy and Grace Blauvelt, the parents of Maine Maritime Academy
cadet Paul S. Blauvelt, 19, sued the academy last June for $350,000,
charging the academy with allowing their son to suffer ``great
physical and mental pain, shock and agony.''
   None of the parties would disclose the amount, but Steven Silin,
an attorney for Blauvelt's parents, said the settlement was fair.
   State law limits recovery against state entities such as the
academy to $300,000, and the settlement reached in December was
``far less than that,'' said attorney Thomas F. Monaghan, who
represents the academy's insurance companies.
   Blauvelt was one of 350 cadets on the academy's ship, State of
Maine, when it docked for a spring training cruise in June 1986 on
Madeira, about 400 miles off the West African coast in the Atlantic
Ocean.
   Midshipmen on shore leave and islanders engaged in a brawl at a
disco. Blauvelt was not involved in the fight, but when he returned
to the dock early in the morning, he was met by a pipe-wielding
gang, pulled from his taxi and beaten.
   The academy freshman staggered away from his attackers and fell
into the harbor and drowned.
   Two residents of Madeira were convicted in absentia in 1987 of
homicide and three others were found guilty of aiding in the crime.
   The Blauvelts' lawsuit charged that the academy failed to provide
adequate security and did not establish or enforce guidelines for
off-ship activities.
   In a statement following the settlement, Maine Maritime Academy
President Kenneth Curtis said ``the death of young person is a
tragedy that can never be forgotten.'' Academy officials declined to
comment further.
</TEXT>
