<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TurtleNursery     01-06 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtle Nursery,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Halts Head Start Program For Turtles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON ISLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sea turtles no longer will be
raised in captivity for release into the ocean with the suspension
of an experimental state Head Start program for reptiles.
   ``No one is sure if we were doing any good,'' said Alan Huff, a
state Department of Natural Resources biological administrator.
``They are not learning the survival skills they should be
learning.''
   But others said the suspension of the 25-year-old Head Start
program in Eastern Florida may endanger the reptiles just as
officials are seeing a rapid rise in the number of turtles hatched
here.
   Jaynie Wright, keeper of the House of Refuge on Hutchinson
Island, where the Head Start program was located, said Friday that
83 hatchlings were observed here in 1988, as compared to three
recently hatched turtles found in 1983.
   Wright said she believes the turtles that were turned loose when
the program began in 1964 are returning to the area, but since
officials did not start tagging turtles until 1974, no one is sure.
It takes 17 to 20 years for a turtle to return home to nest, she
said.
   Huff said the tagged turtles have been found ``anywhere from New
York to the Azores and Argentina.''
   ``What we lack is evidence that those animals are re-entering the
reproductive population in Florida,'' he said.
   There are still hatchling programs in the Florida Keys, India and
South America, Huff said.
   Wright said the reptiles hatched in the wild face dangers ranging
from red ants to disorienting lights from beach condos.
   ``They go for the sea mainly because the moonlight is hitting the
sea,'' she said. ``But when the condo lights are on they don't know
where to go and they've even found some in the mall.''
   But Huff said state resources, including $10,000 that would have
been required to have turtle tanks comply with state environmental
regulations, could be better used elsewhere to help turtles.
   He said the state plans to ``take our very limited resources to
other conservation activities we know work, like developing lighting
ordinances for local communities or helping them develop beach
protection plans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
