<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-Agents     01-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Agents,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former IRS Agent, DA's Investigator Convicted In Drug Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Andersson is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers reacted angrily after a
federal jury issued a mixed verdict in a drug trafficking case
against a former Internal Revenue Service agent and a former
district attorney's investigator.
   ``I think it's a compromise verdict, and I think that's unfair,''
said Mark Topel, the attorney for Dennis DiRicco, an IRS agent who
became a tax lawyer.
   ``It's frustrating to go through a long indictment and be
acquitted on all but the last count,'' said attorney William
Brockett, who represented former Alameda County district attorney's
investigator Kevin Leong.
   DeRicco, 40, was convicted Thursday of money laundering and
obstruction of justice but acquitted of seven other charges,
including conspiracy to distribute cocaine.
   Leong, 41, was found guilty of urging a witness to lie to a grand
jury. He was acquitted on five other charges, including conspiracy.
   The two had been accused by convicted drug smuggler Alion
Andersson of participating in a cocaine smuggling ring. Andersson
was given a reduced prison term in exchange for testifying against
DiRicco and Leong.
   The defense lawyers complained that the two defendants were
acquitted of a conspiracy charge that included alleged wrongdoing
for which they were convicted. Their motions for a new trial will be
heard Jan. 26.
   If the convictions stand, DiRicco could receive a maximum
sentence of 10 years, and Leong could spend up to five years in
prison.
</TEXT>
