<SECOND>AM-BRF-Productivity Awards,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Awards To Be Presented At Pentagon Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci will honor
65 servicemen and civilian employees next week with productivity
excellence awards for making work suggestions that saved an
estimated $255.9 million last year.
   The awards, to be presented during a ceremony at the Pentagon
Monday, are considered the Defense Department's highest honor for
individual productivity achievement, the Pentagon said.
   It said individuals cannot be nominated for the award unless
their initiative or idea ``greatly exceeds job expectation and saves
the government at least $1 million.''
   The Pentagon began the program in 1983. It has honored 275 people
who have been credited with saving a total of more than $1 billion.
