<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-India-Hanging Bjt   01-06 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Hanging, Bjt,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Police Patrol after Militants Threaten to Avenge Hangings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of police and paramilitary
troops patrolled the capital and three northern states Friday after
militants threatened to avenge two Sikhs hanged in connection with
the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi.
   Sikh shopkeepers closed their doors in New Delhi, Bombay and
across the Sikh-dominated state of Punjab, officials said. A bus was
set afire and two bombs were defused Friday in Punjab, but no
casualties were reported.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot by two Sikh bodyguards Oct. 31, 1984,
apparently to revenge an army raid she ordered on the Golden Temple,
the holiest Sikh shrine. More than 1,200 people died, most of them
Sikhs.
   Satwant Singh, the lone surviving gunman, and Kehar Singh,
convicted of helping plan the assassination, were hanged Friday
morning on the gallows of New Delhi's maximum-security Tihar Jail,
authorities said.
   According to a Home Ministry official, Kehar Singh proclaimed his
innocence but appealed to Sikhs to refrain from retaliatory attacks,
and Satwant Singh, who never denied shooting Mrs. Gandhi, said he
had no regrets.
   As the nooses tightened around their necks, the two men shouted
in their native Punjabi an ancient Sikh battle cry, ``Say the
faithful, God is great!''
   In Amritsar, temporal center of the Sikh faith, residents said
posters pasted on walls overnight threatened widespread killings of
Hindus if the executions took place. The posters, in Punjabi, were
signed by militant Sikhs blamed for 2,440 killings in the northern
state last year.
   Authorities fearing another communal bloodbath deployed troops in
New Delhi and the three northern states.
   At an Amritsar prayer service, Sikh head priest Darshan Singh
Ragi honored the executed men as martyrs and said they would never
be forgotten.
   ``They did the right thing in killing Mrs. Gandhi,'' he told a
gathering of 300 followers.
   The executions, carried out in a light drizzle inside the
prison's gray walls, ended four years of legal maneuvers.
   Shortly before 8 a.m., the two men were taken to an open
courtyard near their cells. Their hands were tied behind their backs
and their legs bound in chains.
   Dressed in white cotton pajamas and wearing yellow kerchiefs over
their hair, they were escorted to the scaffold.
   ``Both men were very calm, very composed and offered no
resistance,'' said the Home Ministry official.
   Black hoods were pulled over their heads and one inch-thick ropes
placed around their necks. Then, on a final signal from prison
Superintendent Jaidev Sarangi, the two hangmen pulled the bolts that
released the trap doors beneath them.
   Relatives of Kehar Singh, 54, waited outside the prison,
including his son Rajinder and wife, Jasbir. They broke down at the
time of the execution. Other relatives raised clenched fists and
shouted the same battle cry, ``Say the faithful, God is great.''
   Police would not permit relatives of Satwant Singh, 30, near the
heavily barricaded prison.
   The two are not related. All male Sikhs take the name Singh,
which means lion.
   Shortly after the two men were declared dead, their bodies were
cremated within the prison compound according to Sikh religious
rites, another Home Ministry official said.
   Prison officials said they feared a funeral procession could be
used to incite violence.
   A magistrate and the doctor who pronounced them dead witnessed
the hangings. Hours before the executions, human rights activists
and opposition politicians appealed to President Ramaswamy
Venkataraman and Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to spare the lives of
the condemned men.
   ``The government will rue this day,'' warned opposition leader R.
Hegve.
   Mrs. Gandhi was gunned down in the garden of her official
residence by two of her Sikh bodyguards on Oct. 31, 1984. One of the
assassins, Beant Singh, was gunned down by other security guards
minutes after Mrs. Gandhi fell. Satwant Singh was arrested after he
recovered from bullet wounds.
   Kehar Singh, Beant's uncle, was arrested and charged with
conspiracy a month later.
   After an eight-month trial in a makeshift courtroom at Tihar
Jail, both were convicted and sentenced to death Jan. 22, 1986. The
convictions and sentences were upheld by the High Court and Supreme
Court.
   In London, several dozen Sikh protesters demonstrated outside the
Indian High Commission and 23 were arrested for obstruction. They
later were cautioned and released, Scotland Yard said.
   Sikh leaders in Britain accused the Indian government of doing
nothing to bring to justice people involved in anti-Sikh riots
following Mrs. Gandhi's death. They claim the riots resulted in
killings of 10,000 Sikhs.
   Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but
they are in a majority in northern Punjab state. Sikh militants
began fighting for an independent homeland in 1982, and the movement
quickly acquired violent overtones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
