<FIRST>r a AM-LongestServing     01-06 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Longest Serving,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Carolina Official Retires After 52 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the cheers of admirers who donned red bow
ties in his honor, Secretary of State Thad Eure bade farewell Friday
as his 52-year tenure ended.
   The 89-year-old official was in a buoyant mood at a ceremony in
his honor in the rotunda of the state Capitol, where he has occupied
the northeast corner office since 1931. He was clerk of the state
House for five years before his first election as secretary of state
in 1936.
   President Reagan said Eure was the longest-serving state elected
official in the nation's history.
   ``You're going to see me around some more,'' Eure told the crowd
of about 150. ``For all of you Democrats and for all of you
Republicans, I pledge ... that I'm going to spend the rest of my
life helping Democrats get elected to public office.''
   Eure did not seek a 14th term because of his wife's poor health.
   He traded friendly verbal jabs with Republican Gov. Jim Martin,
delighting the crowd that included legislators, members of Congress
and lobbyists.
   Eure said he had served with 13 governors and that none had
``accorded me more courtesies'' than Martin.
   ``I like this man,'' Eure said, putting a hand on Martin's
shoulder. ``I told him that ... I wanted to do everything I could to
help him in any way I could, except one thing: I'd never vote for
him.''
   Students and administrators of Elon College, where Eure is
longtime chairman of the board of trustees, distributed red bow-tie
stickers to people who weren't wearing the real thing.
   The red bow tie is a trademark of the flamboyant Eure.
   Martin read a proclamation declaring Friday as ``Red Bow Tie
Day.''
   The governor said his aides had done research to determine
whether any official had outlasted Eure.
   ``I have to say to you that we found one: Ramses the Great,'' the
governor said as the crowd roared and applauded. ``Ramses the Great
held the same office for 65 years. But you also can be consoled to
know that he was not elected ... to that office. His daddy gave it
to him.''
</TEXT>
