<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Sulfites-Grapes     01-06 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sulfites-Grapes,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA to Continue Limit on Sulfite Residues on Grapes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said Friday
it plans to make permanent the temporary limit on residues of
sulfite pesticides on grapes.
   Grape shippers and importers have been permitted to sell grapes
containing sulfite residues up to 10 parts per million for the past
two years while EPA investigated what the permanent limit should be.
   The agency said it would receive public comments for the next 30
days on making 10 ppm the permanent limit.
   Sulfur compounds have been used on grapes for more than 60 years
to prevent rotting during shipment. Until 1986, no legal residue
limit was in effect because the compounds were listed by the Food
and Drug Administration as ``generally recognized as safe,'' a
status the FDA revoked that year.
   Sulfites can trigger adverse reactions in a small number of
sensitive people, mostly asthmatics.
</TEXT>
