<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Gulf-Ship     01-06 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Ship,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Tanker Sinks While Being Towed After Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Saudi Arabian tanker split in two and
sank while being towed to port Friday after an explosion and fire
killed six crewmen in the southern Persian Gulf, shipping executives
reported.
   The 36,904-ton Sagheera may have been hit by a drifting mine when
it was rocked by an explosion Thursday during a storm in the Strait
of Hormuz, the gateway to the gulf, the executives said on condition
of anonymity.
   They said the vessel's Greek captain, Constantinos Sardinis, was
among six crew members killed and that the Oman coast guard rescued
the other 26 crewmen from lifeboats on Thursday. Two other Greeks
were killed along with three Sri Lankan seamen.
   The vessel split as it was being towed by a tug boat toward the
coast of Oman. Its stern section sank quickly and the forward
section went down several hours later, the executives said.
   The explosion rocked the Sagheera and set it on fire as it was
steaming into the storm-lashed Strait of Hormuz, headed for the
Saudi Arabian port of Mina Saud.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which
monitors shipping traffic around the world, reported that an
explosion in the tanker's pump room triggered the fire.
   It did not say what could have caused the blast. U.S. Navy
officers have warned for weeks that mines laid during the Iran-Iraq
war could be torn loose from their moorings during winter storms and
sent adrift into shipping lanes.
   Winds gusted more than 30 mph Thursday, whipping waves as high as
30 feet.
   The stormy weather grounded a small Honduran freighter, the
Moajil-5, off the southern Gulf port of Sharjah.
   An Iranian ferry with about 420 passengers on board sailing from
Sharjah to the Iranian port of Bandar Abbas was forced to anchor in
the neighboring port of Ras Al-Khaimah, the shipping executives said.
   The U.S. Navy has estimated as many as 200 mines are still in the
gulf, despite mine sweeping operations by the United States and
other countries.
   Several vessels were hit by mines during the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq
war before a U.N.-mediated cease-fire took effect Aug. 20. Since
then, no ship has been confirmed to have been hit by a mine.
   The Sagheera, owned by the Dammam-based General Contracting
Importing and Service Enterprises, was hit by Iranian gunboats April
4 last year, but there were no casualties and the ship was only
slightly damaged.
</TEXT>
