<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LibyaTapeCamera 220   01-06 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya Tape Camera, 220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fight Recorded on New Cameras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The camera system that produced photos of this
week's dogfight between U.S. and Libyan fighters is a relatively new
one whose principal purpose has nothing to do with recording images
of aerial action.
   The system operates with videotape and was installed in the
Navy's F-14 Tomcat fighters starting in the early 1980s.
   But according to Lt. Cmdr. Craig Quigley, a Navy spokesman, the
system's principal purpose ``is to magnify vision to a range of
20-to-30 miles.''
   ``The system is designed to increase the visual identification
range of the pilot,'' Quigley added. ``The pilot can use the camera
system to pick up targets far beyond normal sight.''
   ``Obviously, its second purpose is to serve as a gun camera and
record any action.''
   The spokesman said the installation of target, or gun, cameras in
Navy aircraft is nothing new, dating back to the days of World War
II. The only serious change in the procedure over the past decade
has been the switch from 16mm camera film to the magnetic videotape
now used.
   Cameras also are installed on the Navy's attack aircraft, like
the A-6 Intruder. The Pentagon previously released videotape shot by
A-6's and Air Force F-111 bombers after the U.S. raid on Libya in
1986.
</TEXT>
