<DOCNO> AP890106-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Derailment-Drugs     01-06 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derailment-Drugs,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amtrak, Tower Operator Share Blame For Accident, NTSB Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amtrak train derailment in Pennsylvania was
likely caused by a tower operator who tested for positive for drugs,
and by problems with Amtrak's system of keeping trains off
out-of-service tracks, federal officials said Friday.
   The National Transportation Safety Board divided blame for the
January 1988 accident, which injured 25 people, between control
tower operator Thomas Connor and the passenger line.
   The NTSB report said Amtrak should develop a procedure ``to
prevent locomotives or trains from entering out-of-service track
sections, unless permission has been received from the person in
charge of the out-of-service track ... ''
   Connor, who resigned after the accident, was on duty when the
train struck a work vehicle in Chester, Pa., near Philadelphia Jan.
29. Officials said he let the train to travel on a section of track
undergoing maintenance.
   Connor fled his post, and did not submit to required drug tests
until more than 72 hours after the accident. Marijuana and small
traces of cocaine and methamphetamine were detected in his system.
   The NTSB said Connor, ``because of impairment by drugs or
distraction or both,'' did not hit a switch to let the train cross
to the proper track.
   But the agency also said Amtrak failed ``to adequately monitor
the activities and job performance of the tower operator.'' The NTSB
recommended the line establish standards for the selection, training
and responsibilities of tower operators.
   Amtrak spokesman John Jacobsen said he hadn't yet seen the NTSB
report.
   But after being read its conclusions, Jacobsen said he did not
know if the NTSB was aware Amtrak is been phasing out tower
operators.
   ``They're clearly dealing with what was, not what is. It's being
shifted to remote control by computer,'' he said.
   But Jacobsen said the old system was safe, too.
   ``While the system we're moving to has more safeguards, the old
system was a safe system. All one had to do was follow it.''
   Connor, Jacobsen said, ``had standing orders that the track had
been taken out of service (by the dispatcher). We're just lucky in
this situation that no one was killed.''
   An assistant conductor on the train also tested positive for
marijuana, but he was not believed to have played a role in the
accident, according to the Federal Railroad Administration.
   The FRA announced the drug test results last February, but it was
left to the NTSB to determine the accident's likely cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890106-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-ReaganFarewell     01-06 0108</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Reagan Farewell,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Sets Fairwell Review For Commander-In-Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department will stage a special
farewell review for President and Mrs. Reagan next week to mark the
completion of his eight years as commander-in-chief.
   Co-hosts for the ceremony Jan. 12 at Andrews Air Force Base in
suburban Maryland will be Secretary of Defense Frank C. Carlucci and
Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Reagan will be given an award from each military service and will
review ceremonial troops, and there will be a display of aircraft
and other equipment representing all the armed forces, the Pentagon
said.
</TEXT>
