<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra     01-06 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge May Delay North Trial If Key Charges Dismissed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge indicated Friday he might delay
the Jan. 31 start of the Iran-Contra trial of Oliver L. North
because prosecutors have sought dismissal of conspiracy and theft
counts against the fired National Security Council aide.
   ``All dates now scheduled'' will be reviewed at a hearing Monday
in light of the dismissal motion by independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh, U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell said in a one-sentence
order.
   Gesell will consider Walsh's dismissal motion at the hearing.
Dropping the two main counts is expected to require significant
adjustments in the documents both sides plan to present in the case.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, meanwhile, defended the Reagan
administration's position to limit disclosure of classified
information in the case.
   The administration's position contributed to Walsh's decision to
abandon the charges that accuse North of illegally diverting more
than $14 million in U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan
rebels. Three others are also charged with the same counts, but
their trials have been severed.
   An interagency intelligence group in the administration refused
to permit the release of additional classified material which Gesell
said must be disclosed in order for North to get a fair trial.
   Dropping the conspiracy and theft counts is ``hardly'' going to
provide ``a precedent in every case,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``In every case, there is going to have to be the type of
balancing ... Walsh carried out here,'' he said.
   ``One the one hand, is it more important to go ahead with a
particular criminal prosecution that involves a particular defendant
and a particular offense as against what harm might come to the
country's long-term interests from exposing of sensitive
information?''
   Walsh ``made the decision here to protect this information rather
than go forward with these counts in the indictment that was
returned,'' Thornburgh added.
   Walsh said he also based his decision on North's insistence on
introducing classified information in his defense and on Gesell's
refusal Tuesday to reconsider his order of last month on what
classified information must be disclosed. The judge said the
administration had deleted too much information from the secret
government documents Walsh wants to use as evidence.
   Meanwhile, in a motion filed in federal court, Walsh's office
said North's lawyers are impermissibly trying to increase the number
of classified documents they will be allowed to use at trial to at
least 550.
   Walsh's office plans to use 300 classified government documents
to prosecute North and Gesell has limited the defense to the same
number.
   The prosecution asked Gesell for an order reducing the number of
documents North plans to use.
   If the conspiracy and theft counts against North are dismissed,
12 charges would remain carrying maximum total penalties of 60 years
in prison and $3 million in fines.
   Nine of the 12 counts that would remain focus on North allegedly
concealing from Congress and former Attorney General Edwin Meese III
his efforts on behalf of the Contras. Four of the nine deal with
alleged concealment of the diversion of money to the Contras from
the administration's secret arms sales to Iran.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Secord, converting to his own
use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader Adolfo
Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury of tax revenue in
connection with charitable contributions supporting the Contras.
</TEXT>
