<DOCNO> AP890106-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting 810   01-06 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Recruiting, 810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recruiting Goals Met Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's military services met or exceeded
their recruiting goals for the ninth consecutive year in fiscal
1988, but concern is growing about the future, the Pentagon said
Friday.
   Even though the Defense Department does not need to recruit as
many men and women this year as it did last, ``Delayed Entry Program
participation has declined to the lowest level in five years,'' the
Pentagon said in a new report.
   Moreover, the reduction in recruiting goals should make it easier
to improve the current record-high number of high school graduates
among the volunteers, but that is not happening, the Pentagon added.
   The Delayed Entry Program lets individuals sign up for military
service but delay the start of basic training until a later date or
when specific job openings occur. That pool of individuals is a key
tool for recruiters who need to spread the flow of new enlistments
throughout the year.
   ``With a strong economy and the shrinking pool of youth available
for military service, the services are facing significantly more
competitive market conditions,'' said Grant S. Green Jr., the
assistant defense secretary for personnel.
   ``The services' ability to obtain high-quality volunteers and
retain the best and brightest of them ... will depend upon support
of the Congress and the American people for adequate military
compensation, quality-of-life initiatives and recruiting resources
and incentives.''
   The new recruiting and re-enlistment results released Friday
cover fiscal 1988 _ the 12 months ending last Sept. 30. During that
period, the Pentagon significantly cut its recruiting goals because
of a decision by the administration to reduce the size of the Army,
Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps to accommodate congressional budget
cuts.
   The new report shows 93 percent of the recruits who joined the
military in fiscal 1988 had a high school diploma, exactly matching
the figure reported in fiscal 1987.
   Those results are significantly above the high school graduation
rates for the American youth population as a whole _ roughly 75
percent.
   Re-enlistment results, meantime, were ``satisfactory despite slow
starts in some areas,'' the Pentagon continued.
   The percentages of men and women re-enlisting in the Air Force
and Marine Corps dipped slightly on a percentage basis of those
eligible, but the declines caused no problem because the services
also had reduced their goals in that area.
   All told, the four services recruited 286,700 men and women
between Oct. 1, 1987, and Sept. 30, 1988, slightly exceeding the
combined objective of 286,400. Of that total, 272,600 were men and
women who had not previously served in the military, while the
remaining 14,100 were individuals returning to the services after
breaks in their military careers.
   Of the 272,600 first-time recruits, 254,000 or 93.2 percent had
graduated from high school.
   Moreover, the recruits who entered the service during the past
year scored unusually well on the Armed Forces Qualification Test, a
special standardized skill exam given all new enlistees. Ninety-five
percent of the recruits scored average or above on the test this
past year, just one percentage point below the all-time record of 96
percent set in fiscal 1986.
   The United States switched to an all-volunteer military in 1973.
After years of trying to establish the system and attract
high-quality recruits, the Defense Department finally met its annual
recruiting objective in fiscal 1980 and has managed to meet or
exceed the annual goals ever since.
   According to the latest report, the Army signed up 115,300 men
and women during fiscal 1988, slightly exceeding its goal of
115,000. The Navy recruited 94,000 individuals, precisely matching
its goal, while the Marine Corps recruiting 35,900 men and women,
matching its goal. The Air Force recruited 41,500 individuals, also
matching its goal.
   Overall, 67 percent of the men and women who were eligible to
re-enlist in their respective services did so in fiscal 1988 _ or
251,300 of the 374,600 eligible. That slightly exceeds the previous
year's tally of 65 percent.
   Of the first-time recruits who joined the military in fiscal
1988, 34,400 were women _ or 12.6 percent _ and 238,200 were men.
That overall percentage for women exceeds the fiscal 1987 rate of
12.2 percent.
   Of the four services, the Air Force continued to attract by far
the most women _ 8,100 out of 41,200 total, or 19.7 percent.
   The report shows blacks comprised 56,500 of the first-time
recruits who joined in fiscal 1988 _ or 20.7 percent, up one
percentage point compared to fiscal 1987.
   The Pentagon said there were 110,500 individuals in the Delayed
Entry Program as of Sept. 30, down sharply from the 123,700 reported
a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
