<DOCNO> AP890106-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeadlyHoldup     01-06 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deadly Holdup,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Mourns `Everybody's Dad' Slain in Holdup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cleophus in 4th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Piles of flowers remained outside a
corner market Friday as tearful residents mourned their 68-year-old
grocer, ``everybody's dad,'' shot to death during a holdup.
   ``There isn't a man, woman or child who isn't affected by this,''
said Judy Jarvis, who had joked with Robert Young, owner of the
Santa Fe Market, only hours before his death Thursday.
   ``Without Bob, the Point will never be the same,'' she said.
   Young and his assistant, Brent Moriwaki, 34, were killed by a
still-unidentified gunman who then died, gun in hand, in an exchange
of fire with police, authorities said. Cleophus Clark, 36, also was
shot at the store and remained in serious condition Friday.
   Young ran the small market for 40 years, and customers who laid
candles and created a sad garden outside its door remembered him as
a friend who delivered groceries to the elderly and disabled,
extended credit, and saved bones for dogs.
   Neighborhood kids who stopped for free sesame cookies the San
Francisco resident kept in a tin below the counter knew him as
``Cookie Bob.''
   ``It was like someone walked into your living room and shot your
family,'' said Grey Wolf, an artist whose wood carvings are sold in
the store next to Young's. ``Bob was everybody's dad.''
   Young also served as the banker for Point Richmond, which doesn't
have a bank. For years, he cashed payroll checks for workers at the
nearby Chevron oil refinery.
   Richmond police believe that practice, for which customers said
Young kept tens of thousands of dollars in cash on hand, may have
lured his killer to the Santa Fe Market.
   ``I kept telling him, `Bob, you keep too much money in here.
...Something's going to happen sometime,' '' said Officer Jim
Ingram, also a customer. ``He wouldn't listen.''
   Police and witnesses said the gunman walked into the market
shortly before 1 p.m. and waited in line during the lunch-hour rush.
When he reached the counter, the man said he wanted to cash a check,
then pulled out a .45-caliber pistol.
   ``This is a robbery,'' the man reportedly said before opening
fire.
   The sequence of the shootings was not immediately known. But
Young, shot point-blank in the temple, died before help arrived.
   Moriwaki, an El Cerrito resident Young was grooming to replace
him when he retired, died early Friday from a bullet wound in the
head.
   Clark, of Richmond, remained in serious but stable condition at
John Muir Medical Center in Walnut Creek. It was unknown if Clark
was a delivery man, customer or both, police said.
   The gunman then fled in a red pickup, said police Lt. Raymond
Howard. Police were uncertain if the suspect took any money.
   A few minutes later another officer, Lou Pereira, spotted the
suspect's truck on a freeway and pulled it over. The gunman fired at
Pereira, who then shot and killed the man, Howard said.
   The suspect, shot twice in the head and upper body, was slumped
behind the steering wheel, the gun still in his right hand. Police
said he carried no identification and the pickup was not registered.
   The southbound lanes of the freeway were closed after the
shooting, causing a traffic jam for several hours.
</TEXT>
