<FIRST>u i AM-Crash-Germany     01-06 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Germany,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Probers Believe Bomb Planted In London, Paper Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British investigators believe the
bomb that exploded aboard Pan Am Flight 103 last month was attached
to the outside of the airliner at London's Heathrow airport, a West
German newspaper reported Friday.
   A spokesman for the government press office in Bonn said he could
not confirm or deny the report.
   The Munich Abendzeitung newspaper said, ``British flight
officials have informed the Bonn Interior Ministry that
investigators now feel that the bomb that caused the Pan Am
explosion shortly before Christmas was affixed to the outside of the
plane at London's Heathrow airport.''
   The brief report, made available to other news media, also said
British officials believe that ``at least 100 people had access'' to
the Boeing 747 in London before it departed and crashed over
Lockerbie Scotland on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people on board and
11 on the ground.
   The newspaper cited West German security sources for its
information.
   Government press spokesman Ulrich Strempel said by telephone: ``I
cannot confirm or deny such a report.
   ``We don't like to comment on reports that simply cite security
sources,'' Strempel said.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Michael-Andreas Butz also said he
could not comment on the report.
   ``I find that all this sort of speculation should stop,'' Butz
said. ``I cannot confirm or deny the report.''
   Since the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, speculation on how the
bomb was placed on the airliner has been widespread. Flight 103
began in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727, but in London switched to the
Boeing 747 that crashed over Lockerbie, Scotland, as it headed to
New York.
   West German investigators repeatedly have said they have found no
evidence that the bomb may have slipped through security checks in
luggage placed aboard the flight in Frankfurt and later transferred
to the Boeing 747.
</TEXT>
