<FIRST>r w AM-Banks-Insurance     01-06 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Insurance,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Citibank Can Operate Subsidiary To Insure Municipal
Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court, in a ruling cited by
the banking industry as precedent-setting, said Friday that
Citibank, the largest bank in the nation, can operate a subsidiary
to insure municipal bonds.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit
said the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the chief
regulator of nationally chartered banks, properly permitted Citibank
to purchase the American Municipal Bond Assurance Corp., known as
AMBAC.
   The decision by Comptroller Robert L. Clarke had been challenged
by the American Insurance Association as a violation of the Bank
Holding Company Act. Citibank is owned by Citicorp, a bank holding
company regulated by the Federal Reserve Board.
   The insurance association, after losing in U.S. District Court,
won an appeal. In August, the appeals panel said the Bank Holding
Company Act, and thus Federal Reserve jurisdiction applied. Friday's
ruling, however, reverses that part of the August decision.
   Even though Citibank is a nationally chartered bank, Stephen
Verdier, an attorney with the Independent Bankers Association of
America, said the latest court ruling represents a blow to a
proposal by the Federal Reserve to extend its jurisdiction over the
activities of subsidiaries of state banks owned by holding companies.
   The Fed in November proposed a regulation requiring state banks
owned by holding companies to get its permission before establishing
real estate, insurance and other non-banking operations, even when
state law permits the operations. Banks have opposed the Fed
proposal as a power grab.
   ``The significance obviously goes well beyond whether Citibank
can own an insurance subsidiary. ... It really pulls the rug out
from under the Federal Reserve,'' Verdier said.
   Stephen Katsanos, a spokesman for the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., which insures bank deposits and is the primary regulator of
state-chartered banks that are not members of the Federal Reserve,
said FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman was ``quite pleased'' with the
decision.
   ``It tracks very well with his philosophy that banks should be
allowed to expand their activities through bank affiliates or
subsidiaries provided adequate safeguards are set up,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
