<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     01-06 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a plucky gift, to be sure. When
William Benson returned home from his 50th birthday party, he found
50 pink, plastic flamingos planted in his front lawn.
   The gaudy, pink birds were a gift from Benson's brother, Robert,
of West Palm Beach, Fla.
   Benson said his brother shipped the plastic birds to an uncle and
cousin, who live in nearby Bristol, Wis.
   The two men apparently arrived at Benson's home on the night of
Dec. 16 to drill 100 holes in the frozen ground and stand the
Florida flamingos on their wire legs while Benson was gone.
   Benson said he decided to leave the birds in the ground until his
brother arrived for a visit over the holidays.
   ``I wanted him to see what he had done,'' said Benson, who owns
an oil company.
   But a deep freeze that followed after Christmas left the ground
so hard that the plastic birds will have to wait for the spring thaw
to be removed, Benson said.
</TEXT>
