<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0667 01-06 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667, 000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Prepares For Surgery to Fix Curved Finger</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Surgery Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Desk: Top 4 grafs new with Reagan's arrival, picks up ``The presidential
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, saying he felt fine, entered
Walter Reed Army Hospital on Friday to prepare for surgery early
Saturday morning to correct a curvature of his left ring finger.
   The president, accompanied by his wife Nancy, waved to reporters
as he entered the emergency room of the military hospital. Asked how
he felt, the president called out, ``Fine.''
   Due to heavy cloud cover, the president went to the hospital by
motorcade, rather than by helicopter.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the operation is
scheduled for 7:30 a.m. EST and doctors expect the president to be
``up and around ... following the operation.''
   The presidential physician, Col. John Hutton, has said Reagan's
arm would be numbed for the two- to three-hour procedure and he did
not expect general anesthesia to be used.
   Reagan will remain at the hospital until Sunday as a
precautionary measure, Fitzwater said, to ``be sure everything goes
well.''
   The surgery, designed to alleviate an ailment known as
Dupuytren's contracture, is considered to be routine and often
doesn't require an overnight stay in the hospital.
   The affliction causes the progressive, and usually painless,
contraction of the fingers and occurs due to a thickening of the
tissue called fascia in the palm of the hand.
   The contracture was minimal when Reagan took office in 1981 but
has progressed enough during the past year to require surgical
treatment, Hutton said.
   Fitzwater said he expected the president to wear ``some kind of
bandage'' afterward, but that the president was expected to be back
to work Monday.
   ``He has a full schedule for next week,'' Fitzwater said.
   The president is to leave office Jan. 20, but the spokesman said
Reagan chose to go ahead with the surgery while still in Washington
because he preferred to make use of the ``experts in this kind of
surgery'' at the military hospital.
   ``He wanted to have it done at Walter Reed. ... After he leaves
office, of course, he's going to California,'' Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman added that Reagan has been putting off the
procedure for some time, even though his doctors had been suggesting
it be done for several months.
   Hutton said the physicians involved, besides himself, would be
Dr. George Bogumill of Georgetown University, a consultant at Walter
Reed; Col. Alan Smith and Maj. Paul Perlik of the Hand Service at
Walter Reed.
   The anesthesiologist will be Lt. Col Charles Gandy. Lt. Col.
Lawrence Mohr of the White House medical unit and members of the
Department of Medicine at Walter Reed will take part as consultants,
Hutton said.
</TEXT>
