<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MinersKilled     01-06 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miners Killed,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miner Who Escaped Tried To Warn Three Who Died</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLESBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A probe of the worst coal mine cave-in
accident in 2{ years began Friday with a federal official saying
that one survivor saw the accident coming but was too late to save
the three miners who were killed.
   ``He tried to warn the others, but the fall came too quick,''
U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration spokesman Joey Lucas said
Thursday of Roger Wilder, 37, of Cubbage.
   Wilder, who was operating machinery with an overhead canopy and
was not harmed in the accident Wednesday, saw the overhead dipping
and tried to alert the others when the roof caved in.
   Wilder was trapped for about 20 minutes until other miners
cleared fallen rock and shored up the roof, Lucas said. The cave-in
occurred as the men were removing coal about 2,400 feet into the
mine.
   The accident was at Cumberland Valley Contractors Co. Inc.'s No.
2 Mine. The company was formed in late 1986 by Stanley Ditty, David
Howard, Robert Roane and Gerald Burleson, according to Clyde Goins,
their former employer.
   All four ``were well-trained in safe coal mining, and I'd be
surprised to find out if they were doing it any differently,'' Goins
said.
   The new company has a ``somewhat average'' federal mine-safety
record, Lucas said.
   MSHA records show that the No. 2 Mine had five serious and
significant violations in 1987 and four last year. All the most
serious violations MSHA inspectors cited at the mine were corrected.
   During the last MSHA inspection, completed Dec. 15, only one
violation was cited, a non-serious one involving storage of
compressed-gas cylinders, according to records.
   Federal inspectors have cited the mine for safety violations 24
times, but only one, on May 14, 1987, involved roof support.
   ``It has absolutely nothing to do with the accident there this
week,'' said Lucas, who characterized the 1987 violation as ``more
of a paper-work violation.''
   State Mines and Minerals Commissioner Willard Stanley said
Thursday that the state and federal investigations would begin
Friday and a spokesman in his office confirmed they had begun.
   ``We've had no problems with getting anything corrected that
needed to be corrected,'' at the mine, Stanley said.
   The last coal mine accident in which three people were killed was
July 9, 1986, according to Kathy Snyder, a spokeswoman for U.S. Mine
Safety and Health Administration in Arlington, Va.
</TEXT>
