<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     01-06 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Hungary-Israel Ties Imminent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary will resume diplomatic ties with
Israel within four months, a state news agency reported on Friday.
   Hungary would be the first East European nation to resume full
ties with Israel since all Soviet bloc nations except Romania broke
off relations over the Middle East War in 1967.
   The news agency MTI, in a report from Tel Aviv, quoted
unidentified sources close to the Israeli Foreign Ministry as saying
Israel and Hungary will establish full ties within four months.
   Hungarian Agriculture Minister Jeno Vancsa is visiting Israel. He
met Thursday with Israeli Premier Yitzhak Shamir and handed over
messages from Communist party leader Karoly Grosz and Premier Miklos
Nemeth, Hungarian media said.
   Hungary's increasingly close ties to Israel were believed to be
behind a New Year's Eve terrorist threat to blow up a plane of the
Scandinavian airline SAS. The threat was telephoned to Budapest
police, prompting a Europe-wide terrorist alert on SAS flights.
   State radio said Friday that unidentified Palestinian terrorists
had threatened to attack John's Hospital, Budapest's oldest
hospital. It said the threat came in a phone call to the hospital,
but gave no details.
   Hungarian reporters for the daily Magyar Nemzet newspaper said
hospital administrator Gyoergy Toeroek told them the hospital had
been sealed off since late Thursday as a precaution.
</TEXT>
