<FIRST>u w AM-US-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0664 01-06 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Confident West Germany Taking Assertions Seriously</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs at end to include Reagan comment; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed confidence
Friday that West Germany is taking seriously and fully investigating
American assertions that West German firms have helped Libya build a
chemical weapons production plant.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley repeated the U.S.
declaration that the plant represents a ``serious danger.''
   She said: ``We and other governments are seeking to deny Libya
the foreign assistance we believe is essential for full development
of this capability.''
   Mrs. Oakley said that the U.S. information on the role of foreign
companies in assisting the Libyan chemical weapons effort is
conclusive.
   ``With regard to West Germany, we are confident that it is taking
the information we have provided very seriously and is investigating
fully,'' Mrs. Oakley said. ``It has in the past year vigorously
pursued and prosecuted such cases.''
   ``With regard to the Libyan CW program, we understand that the
appropriate West German authorities are still conducting their
investigations,'' she said.
   ``As with other countries with which we have talked regarding
this problem, this is an ongoing matter. West Germany has also
announced that it is reviewing its export control laws. We
understand an interim report on this subject will be presented to
the cabinet soon.''
   The comment came in the wake of news reports quoting unnamed U.S
officials as complaining that West Germany was not moving fast
enough to respond to the American appeal for cutting off technical
assistance and critical material which might help Libya go into
actual production of chemical weapons.
   Mrs. Oakley was asked about a West German statement that the
United States was running an ``unhelpful'' media campaign to put
pressure on the Bonn government.
   ``I don't have any comment on that,'' she replied. ``I think that
I have addressed it, that we have full and close cooperation with
the government of West Germany, and we fully expect that to
continue.''
   She was asked whether her statement on behalf of the State
Department had been requested by Bonn to ``clear West Germany's
name'' and to end complaints of ``West Germany bashing.''
   ``That would not be accurate at all,'' Mrs. Oakley replied. ``I
don't think we're in any position of bashing any country. We're
working closely with the West German government, other interested
governments on this issue. We'll continue to bring to their
attention relevant information that assists in their ongoing
investigations.''
   ``It's our understanding that the West German investigation is
not yet complete, that they're continuing to investigate, and we
remain in touch with them on the matter,'' she said.
   President Reagan, interviewed Friday on CBS television, defended
Wednesday's action by U.S. warplanes in shooting down two Libyan
MiGs over the Mediterranean Sea.
   ``That was self-defense, and now it's proven by film of the
planes in the air, that their planes were not disarmed,'' Reagan
said. `` Their planes were carrying weapons, missiles and so forth,
and they were the ones that when our pilots changed the direction,
altitude and so forth, they followed every time ... finally, it is
so apparent that you don't wait for them to push the button because
then you die.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
