<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0657 01-06 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Militias Battle In Beirut, South Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with fighting spreading to
west Beirut. Picks up 4th graf pvs: The battle ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias backed by
Syria and Iran battled with artillery and rockets in west Beirut and
south Lebanon on Friday, ignoring a plea by Iran's president to stop
fighting.
   Police said four people were wounded in midday clashes that
pitted the pro-Syrian Amal militia against Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God.
   After dark, fighting spilled into residential districts in
Syrian-controlled west Beirut, breaking a 5-week-old truce in those
areas.
   The thud of exploding shells echoed throughout the capital long
into the night.
   A police spokesman said combat with mortars and rocket-propelled
grenades centered in the old Jewish quarter of Wadi Abu Jmil, in
Azarieh and the former downtown commercial district near the Green
Line which divides Moslem west from Christian east Beirut.
   No immediate word on casualties emerged from west Beirut. It was
the first serious violence there since November, when 40 people were
killed and 87 wounded in Shiite militia street fighting.
   In south Lebanon, the two sides dueled with mortars, 106mm guns
and rocket-propelled grenades in Iklim el-Tiffah, a former
apple-growing district, a police spokesman said.
   The battle centered around Jbaa, Ein Bouswar, Jarjou and
Louwaizeh, which are mostly deserted villages on the edge of
Israel's self-proclaimed ``security zone'' north of its border with
Lebanon. The fighting dwindled into sniper fire and occasional
rocket blasts before sundown, said the police spokesman, who cannot
be identified under standing regulations.
   He said two of the wounded are Amal militiamen and another is a
Hezbollah fighter. The fourth casualty, a 21-year-old woman, was
wounded when a stray shell fell near her house in Jbaa.
   In Tehran, President Ali Khamenei of Iran said ``vengeance will
not solve anything in Lebanon,'' the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   ``I address our Lebanese brothers in Amal and Hezbollah to end
the bloodshed,'' Khamenei was quoted as saying by the news agency,
monitored in Nicosia.
   ``If any of the two groups sees violations and attacks from the
other group, they should disregard it,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Khamenei accused the United States and Israel of instigating the
clashes between the militias, which are struggling for dominance of
the 1 million Shiites, the country's largest sect.
   Friday's clashes shattered a two-day-old lull in the fighting
that began Dec. 31 in the slums of Beirut and in southern Lebanon.
   At least 29 people were killed and 76 wounded in five days of
fighting with artillery, mortars and automatic weapons before Syrian
troops stopped the violence in Beirut.
   Syria, which maintains an estimated 40,000 troops in Lebanon
under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League, considers
the country its sphere of influence. There are no Syrian troops in
southern Lebanon.
   In May, the Syrians deployed 7,500 troops in Moslem-controlled
west Beirut and 4,500 soldiers in the slums of south Beirut to halt
a three-week bloodbath between Amal and Hezbollah that killed nearly
300 people and wounded 1,000.
</TEXT>
