<FIRST>u i AM-ChemicalConference 2ndLd-Writethru   01-06 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Conference, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0740,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Minister Says U.S.-Libyan Clash `Poisons' Chemical Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `He called...' to CORRECT quote to ``unacceptable''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said
the U.S. downing of two Libyan jet fighters this week has ``poisoned
the atmosphere'' of an international conference on chemical weapons
that opens Saturday.
   He called the incident over the Mediterranean ``unacceptable''
upon arriving at Orly airport Friday.
   There has been speculation that the conference risks being
dominated by U.S. charges that Libya is building a chemical weapons
plant. Nations will strive at the five-day meeting, the largest such
gathering ever held, to revive the taboo on the proliferation of
chemical weapons.
   At least 141 nations are attending the conference, about 80 of
them led by their foreign ministers, according to French officials.
   Earlier Friday, France, Canada and Egypt joined Britain in
supporting U.S. contentions that Libya is developing poison gas in a
factory at Rabta, 60 miles southwest of Tripoli, a senior U.S.
official said.
   Shevardnadze told reporters, ``It is very important that 1989
begin with a major event like the Paris conference.''
   Asked about the downing of two Libyan MiG-23s on Wednesday by two
U.S. F-14s, the Soviet minister said he felt the incident ``poisons
the atmosphere on the eve of the Paris conference.''
   Shevardnadze also said American accusations about a Libyan
chemical weapons plant were out of order.
   ``Without proof, no government has the right to present such
accusations,'' he said.
   However, the U.S. official reported added agreement among U.S.
allies that Libya under Col. Moammar Gadhafi now is developing
chemical weapons in its own factory.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in Paris for the
conference, has said he will try when he meets Shevardnadze on
Sunday to persuade the Soviets about the nature of the plant and ask
their help in closing it.
   The U.S. official, briefing reporters under rules that barred
disclosing his name, said foreign ministers Michel Rocard of France,
Joe Clark of Canada and Esmet Abdel-Meguid of Egypt all told Shultz
in separate meetings Friday they did not doubt the Libyan plant was
engaged in producing chemical weapons.
   Shultz said Thursday the plant had not yet actually produced
poison gas.
   President Francois Mitterrand, apparently trying to bring the
conference back to its original intent, told reporters Thursday
night that ``at the moment, there is no ban'' on producing chemical
weapons.
   The 1925 Geneva Protocol bans only the use of chemical weapons.
   The conference aim is to reaffirm the Geneva Protocal and press
delegates now meeting in Geneva to resolve problems blocking
agreement on a universal accord that would forbid use, production
and stocking of chemical arms.
   ``Chemical weapons do not constitute weapons of dissuasion,''
Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France wrote in Friday's edition of
the newspaper Le Monde. ``As we know, they do not stop war, just
underline its horrors.''
   Shultz said Thursday on the plane to Paris that the conference
``is a conscience-raising operation to get people to see the
seriousness of the problem of the use of chemical and biological
weapons.''
   The opening session is likely to be tense, with Shultz facing
Foreign Minister Jadallah Azzuz al-Talhi of Libya in the meeting
hall at the headquarters of the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization.
   The United States has not ruled out a military strike against the
Rabta factory.
   U.S. officials say the downing of the Libyan jets fighters was in
self-defense and not linked to the chemical factory issue.
   The United States plans to appeal to industrialized nations to
deny chemical weapons technology and expertise to Libya and approve
economic sanctions to nations that use toxic arms, U.S. officials
have said.
   Shultz indicated to reporters the United States may be willing to
work out a deal with Libya that would not require destroying the
plant.
   Gadhafi insists pharmaceuticals were being manufactured at the
complex. But Shultz contends he has adequate evidence to support the
U.S. allegation.
   Capability to produce chemical weapons, which U.S. officials say
has spread to about 20 countries, will be a primary topic at the
conference.
   Britain said Wednesday night that an independent investigation
led to the conclusion that poison gas was under development at the
Libyan plant.
   Still, West Germany and a number of other countries, where firms
are suspected of assisting Libya, were skeptical.
   Shultz was expected to meet Saturday with West German Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   In Moscow on Thursday, Lt. Gen. Anatoly Kuntsevich, deputy chief
of Soviet chemical weapons troops, gave his country's first
acknowledgement that Libya may be able to manufacture chemical
weapons, but he said such weapons would be in quantities too small
to wage war.
</TEXT>
