<SECOND>AM-Panama,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Answers Letter From Ousted President Delvalle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has
responded to a letter from ousted President Eric Delvalle that
proposed talks to solve Panama's current political crisis.
   Head of state Manuel Solis Palma told reporters Friday that
Noriega, Panama's de facto leader and the commander of the Defense
Forces, answered Delvalle's letter Thursday. Solis Palma refused to
reveal what Noriega wrote.
   It was the first official reponse to the letter Devalle sent
Noriega from Washington D.C. on Dec. 27. The letter, printed on
Panamanian Embassy stationary in Washington, was given to The
Associated Press by Noriega opponents on condition of anonymity.
   The letter was sent six days after Delvalle met with
President-elect George Bush and outgoing President Reagan.
   ``We can and should carry out a serious and expeditious
negotiation to establish preliminary base for the national
reconstruction and open the way for Panama's recovery,'' the letter
said.
   In February 1988, Delvalle tried to fire Noriega after he was
indicted by a federal grand jury on drug trafficking and money
laundering charges.
   The National Assembly then ousted Delvalle, replacing him with
Solis Palma, the education minister. The United States continues to
recognize Delvalle as Panama's president and has imposed economic
sanctions against the country in an attempt to force out Noriega.
   Delvalle said in his letter to Noriega that Panama's economic and
political crisis has created serious problems for its citizens
because the government no longer has the funds to provide basic
public services.
   Delvalle signed the letter ``president of the Republic of
Panama''.
   Raul Saint Malo, a counselor at the Panamaian Embassy in
Washington, told the AP in a telephone interview this week that the
letter was sent by way of the Vatican Embassy in Washington to the
Vatican Embassy in Panama City.
   Diplomatic sources have said Delvalle has returned to Panama and
is in hiding.
</TEXT>
