<FIRST>u i AM-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru   01-06 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0698,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechs To Join Probe; Report Says Bomb Planted In London</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with report that bomb may have been
placed in Frankfurt, denial by Britain, Jibril denial, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bomb experts from Czechoslovakia will help Britain
determine whether a Czech-made plastic explosive blew up Pan Am
Flight 103, the Foreign Office said Friday.
   Yasser Arafat was quoted as telling a Saudi newspaper that his
Palestine Liberation Organization had ``plenty of important
information'' on the Dec. 21 bombing, which killed all 259 people
aboard the jumbo jet and 11 on the ground.
   Also Friday, tighter security measures aimed primarily at U.S.
airlines went into effect at all British airports, including more
rigorous luggage searches.
   Part of Heathrow's Terminal 3 departure building was evacuated
for 20 minutes Friday while bomb squad officers checked an
unattended black plastic bag near the Air-India check-in desk. It
turned out to be harmless.
   In the Scottish town of Lockerbie, where parts of the wings and
fuselage fell, police said 20 more bodies were released to relatives
Friday, bringing the total released so far to 196.
   Searchers have recovered 242 bodies and are hunting for 28 others.
   A West German newspaper, Munich Abendzeitung, said British
aviation authorities believe the explosive that blew up the Boeing
747 was placed aboard the flight in London, rather than in
Frankfurt, West Germany, where Flight 103 originated.
   The report said investigators believe the bomb was attached to
the outside of the aircraft while it was at London's Heathrow
airport.
   West German government press spokesman Ulrich Strempel said: ``I
cannot confirm or deny such a report.''
   NBC News quoted U.S. government sources as saying British
investigators believe the bomb was in the front cargo hold of the
aircraft, indicating the bomb may have been in luggage that came
from Frankfurt or that someone in London slipped it in with
Frankfurt luggage.
   A British Department of Transport spokesman late Friday dismissed
the reports.
   ``We don't know what the bomb was made of. We don't know where
the bomb was placed in aircraft, nor indeed do we know ... at which
airport the bomb was placed on board,'' said the spokesman, whose
name cannot be used under standing regulations.
   Flight 103 began in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727, then changed
planes in London before departing for New York.
   Arafat was quoted by the newspaper Al-Madina as saying the PLO
was ``cooperating with a number of European states and the United
States in a joint international bid to expose the perpetrators.'' He
did not elaborate.
   Czechoslovakia has offered to send experts to join the forensic
investigation, and ``the British government are grateful for this
offer,'' the Foreign Office said. The Czechoslovak experts are
expected next week.
   Czechoslovakia is a major manufacturer of Semtex but has disputed
charges that it may have made the explosive that downed the jumbo
jet.
   In Prague, Czechoslovakia on Friday reiterated to British Embassy
charge John MacGregor that it ``unequivocally opposes all forms of
terrorism and has never supplied weapons, explosives or any other
material to any terrorist organization,'' the official news agency
CTK reported.
   Orange-colored Semtex can be detected only by extremely
sophisticated monitoring machines still undergoing tests in the
United States. Britain says it has asked Czechoslovakia five times
to make Semtex more easily detectable, and until now has received no
response.
   Anti-terrorism experts and U.S. State Department officials say
Syria and Libya have obtained Semtex from Czechoslovakia and passed
it on to terrorists. Transport Secretary Paul Channon announced
stepped-up security checks on cargo, mislaid luggage and cabin bags
following a crisis meeting Thursday of the National Aviation
Security Committee in London.
   News reports have said authorities are investigating, among
others, a Frankfurt-based Palestinian terrorist group affiliated
with Ahmed Jibril's hardline Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   Jibril on Friday denied involvement. ``We are not involved. We
renounce and reject all such acts,'' he said on ABC News.
</TEXT>
