<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Rebels     01-06 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Rebels,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Government, Rebels Begin Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of President Virgilio
Barco opened peace talks Friday with leftist guerrillas, government
sources said.
   The talks come after Barco, a civilian president, announced Sept.
1 an offer of free political activity to rebels who give up their
weapons. A newspaper reported last month that the April 19th
Movement, known as M-19, intended to do so.
   Official sources said on condition of anonymity that presidential
adviser Rafael Pardo traveled Friday to a mountainous area of
southern Colombia to meet with M-19 leader Carlos Pizarro. They gave
no details.
   The government and the guerrillas reportedly made initial
contacts over the past few weeks.
   M-19 has carried out the most notorious guerrrilla attacks in
Colombia in recent years. They included the kidnapping of about 50
diplomats at the Dominican Republic Embassy in 1980 and the attack
on the Palace of Justice in 1985 in which 85 people were killed,
including 11 Supreme Court justices.
   But M-19 has been inactive for the last six months. It takes its
name from the date of a 1970 presidential election that dissidents
say was fraudulent. Another guerrilla group, the communist-leaning
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, announced a unilateral truce
with the government last month and asked Barco to open peace talks.
   The government says the revolutionary forces have repeatedly
violated the truce and that they attacked a cement factory and
killed four executives Thursday.
   An estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas operate in Colombia.
</TEXT>
