<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hirohito-MarineBiology     01-06 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito-Marine Biology,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fellow Marine Biologists Praise Hirohito As A Scientist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Emperor Hirohito was a highly
respected and dedicated marine biologist whose contributions to his
field will be ``virtually immortal,'' other scientists said after
his death.
   ``The poor man didn't really get to do what he wanted to do. He
had to be emperor first, then second a scientist and normal human
being,'' Robert Hessler, a professor of biological oceanography at
the Scripps Institution of Oceanography in La Jolla, said Friday.
   Hirohito died Saturday (Friday in U.S. time zones) of intestinal
cancer. He was 87.
   He was an expert on invertebrate marine animals, and a world
authority on hydrozoans, which are small creatures related to sea
anemones and corals and which look something like mossy plants, said
William ``Barnacle Bill'' Newman, another biological oceanographer
at Scripps.
   The emperor wrote or co-wrote at least 12 books on hydrozoans.
   Hessler said Hirohito was very competent in classifying marine
animals he collected during summers in Sagami Bay, south of Tokyo.
The emperor published his last book on hydrozoans, part of his
series of volumes on the sea animals of the bay, shortly before he
became ill, Newman said.
   ``The fauna of Sagami Bay is one of the best known in the world
because of his efforts,'' Newman said by phone from Scripps, which
is part of the University of California, San Diego.
   ``While it's not the kind of thing that ever makes the front
page, that kind of science is virtually immortal because the
descriptions that are made and the names assigned to these newly
described animals will last forever,'' Hessler said. ``People will
be consulting them centuries from now.''
   Hirohito spent hours, often working far into the night, in his
laboratory at the palace in Tokyo. Sometimes he collected specimens
at the royal summer home on the seashore south of Tokyo and gathered
fungi in the palace gardens.
   ``He was very dedicated in his interest,'' Hessler said. ``He was
no dilettante.''
   When Hirohito toured Scripps on Oct. 9, 1975, during his only
U.S. tour, he spent about an hour in the laboratory with Hessler and
Newman, although Hessler said they had expected to spend a full day
with him.
   ``Then all the administrators got into the business'' and
insisted on guiding the emperor on various tours, Hessler recalled.
   ``We entertained him for about an hour in the lab, where he
studied hydrozoans and other things,'' Newman recalled. ``He was
very down to earth. ... He was very impressed and would `ooh' and
`aah' when we showed him something very exciting and new. They had
to drag him away when his time was over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890106-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hirohito-JapanReax     01-06 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito-Japan Reax,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese React Calmly To Emperor's Death ^With AM-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prepared by the emperor's extended illness, Japanese
people reacted calmly to Hirohito's death Saturday, and many
businesses and shops remained open.
   Thousands of people began lining up at the Imperial Palace in
central Tokyo after the emperor's death was announced early Saturday
to sign registries expressing their condolences.
   ``Of course it's a shock. I had hoped that the emperor would live
as long as possible,'' said Masakichi Koizumi, 69, one of those in
line. ``But it was inevitable.''
   Television newscasters changed into dark clothing as an
expression of mourning, and all stations were expected to cancel
advertisements and regular programming for at least a day.
   Stock exchanges canceled their regular half-day Saturday sessions
and some factories shut production lines, but banks announced they
would remain open. Department stores and chain stores also said they
would keep regular hours.
   Subways and trains remained crowded with commuters and shoppers,
but some offices decided to close at midmorning.
   Tokyo Disneyland said it would remain open, but would reduce the
volume of music by 50 percent.
   The Japan Sumo Association said the 15-day sumo wrestling
tournament scheduled to begin Sunday would be postponed by one day,
and the horseracing association said races would be canceled for two
days.
   Government officials called for six days of national mourning and
announced the cancellation of government-sponsored festive events,
but said Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno would not return immediately
from a trip to Europe, where he is attending a conference on the
elimination of chemical weapons.
   After the emperor fell gravely ill on Sept. 19, Uno canceled a
trip to Washington and the United Nations.
   At that time, Japan was hit by massive cancellations of concerts,
festivals, weddings, diplomatic visits and other events as part of a
wave of ``jishuku,'' or ``self-restraint.'' People and government
officials initially were unsure how to react.
   ``The sad news of the passing of his late majesty the emperor has
left me grief-stricken,'' Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said in a
statement Saturday. ``Our sincere prayers for his recovery were in
vain, and I am at a loss for words.''
   Despite continuing controversy over the emperor's role during
World War II, when he was officially commander in chief of the
nation's armed forces, Takeshita said Hirohito ``ardently wished for
world peace and the well-being of the people, and devoted himself to
these ideals in his daily life.''
   Hirohito's fifth daughter, Takako Shimazu, said her father had
``battled gallantly'' against his illness. ``I hope he now will be
able to rest peacefully,'' she said.
   ``He lived for as long as he could,'' said Shizue Otsuki, 69, a
shopkeeper. ``I cried as soon as I heard he had passed away.''
</TEXT>
