<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0762 01-06 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Hirohito obit, which moved as a separate as a0754</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Emperor Hirohito</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, who held divine status until
Japan's defeat in World War II and endured to reign for 62 years,
died Saturday of intestinal cancer. He was 87.
   Hirohito was born April 29, 1901, first son of Crown Prince
Yoshihito, who became the Emperor Taisho in 1912 upon the death of
the Meiji emperor. Hirohito, called Prince Michi as a boy, was taken
from his parents and raised by nurses and chamberlains to become
emperor.
   Hirohito's reign covered almost half the turbulent times of
forced modernization, repeated warfare and a vigorous rise from the
radioactive ashes of World War II that together have made Japan a
formidable world force since it was pried out of its island
isolation in the 1850s.
   With no direct political power, Hirohito is known to have made
only one major decision of state: to tell his generals and
ministers, who were deadlocked on the Allies' surrender demand even
as Japan reeled from two atomic bombs, that the people had suffered
enough.
   Hirohito in 1972 surpassed the record for a long-reigning
Japanese emperor set by his grandfather, the Meiji emperor, whose
tenure was 45 years.
   In 1982 Hirohito became the oldest living monarch in the world
when King Sobhuza of Swaziland died at age 83.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Pilar Franco</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilar Franco, the sister of the late Spanish
ruler Gen. Francisco Franco, died Friday from a cerebral hemorrhage
after remaining in a coma for three days. She was 94.
   Her 1980 book, ``We, the Francos,'' told the history of the
family.
   Mrs. Franco had been the last survivor of the two brothers and
two sisters of the former head of state, who died Nov. 20, 1975. He
ruled Spain for 39 years following the victory of his rebel army
officers in the 1936-39 Civil War.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Duncan Koontz</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALISBURY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth ``Libby'' Duncan Koontz, head of
the women's bureau under President Nixon, died Friday of a heart
attack at her home. She was 69.
   Ms. Koontz was named the first black president of the National
Education Association in 1968. She resigned the post a year later to
take the position under Nixon, whom she served until 1973.
   From 1973-75, she was coordinator for nutrition programs in the
North Carolina Department of Human Resources. In 1975, she was named
assistant state school superintendent, a post she held until she
retired in 1982.
   Ms. Koontz was named U.S. delegate to the United Nations
Commission on the Status of Women in 1975.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John William Bainton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John William Bainton, an engineering
executive who led an innovative career worldwide, died Thursday
night at Jefferson University Hospital of melanoma. He was 63.
   Bainton, who was born in New York, began his engineering career
with the Sharples Co., a centrifuge manufacturer in Philadelphia. As
head of the company's Latin American division, he was instrumental
in developing a fish-meal industry in Peru, which helped it become
one of the world's leading fishery producers.
   Bainton had been vice president for 10 years of marketing for the
Chemtex Corp. of New York, an international contracting firm which
specialized in introducing film and fiber technology in developing
countries.
   At the time of his death, Bainton was vice chairman of the board
and chairman of the executive committee of the Viatech Inc., an
international engineering and packaging firm based in Syosset, N.Y.
</TEXT>
