<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MultipleTransplant 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 01-06 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Multiple Transplant, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experimental Surgery in Infancy, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The deaths ... with 3 grafs to UPDATE with doctor's
comments on rejection; picks up 7th graf pvs: ``But this . ..</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's fifth recipient of an abdominal
transplant of multiple organs died Friday, and experts said her
swift decline shows that the procedure for replacing the digestive
system is still in its infancy.
   Three-year-old Rolandrea Dodge was with her parents, Brandon and
Cyndi Dodge of Fruitland, N.M., when she died of multiple organ
failure at 4:45 p.m. at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   The little girl was attached to a respirator and had been in very
critical condition. ``She really was a tremendous fighter,'' said
Lynn McMahon, a hospital spokeswoman. ``Her system just eventually
shut down.''
   Rolandrea, better known as Rolly, received a new liver, pancreas,
stomach, small intestine and part of a large intestine Nov. 29. Her
name was placed back on the transplant waiting list Wednesday night.
   All five transplanted organs were rejected by the girl's natural
immune system, Ms. McMahon said. Because the procedure has been
performed so few times, doctors are not sure why the transplant
failed.
   Dr. Marc Rowe, the hospital's chief of pediatric surgery, said
tests showed on New Year's Eve that Rolly's small intestine was
being rejected by her body's immune system. It's not immediately
known whether any of the other four transplanted organs were
rejected or, if so, to what degree, he said.
   ``We're in areas that are essentially uncharted,'' he said.
``What we're doing is making tentative steps and then very carefully
analyzing where we've been and what we've learned before we make any
decision about the next one, when we'll do one or whether we'll do
one.''
   The deaths of the first four patients and Rolandrea's decline
were ``very disappointing,'' said Dr. James W. Williams, director of
transplantation at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center in
Chicago, in an interview before Rolandrea's death.
   ``But this is what happened in the early days of liver
transplantation,'' he added.
   ``Every organ that's been transplanted has had its early
problems. There are hurdles that you have to go over and along the
way you have to learn from everything that's been done in order for
things to progress,'' agreed Dr. Tony D'Alessandro, a transplant
fellow at the University of Wisconsin.
   ``The surgeons who are working with this case are, at this point,
feeling defeated,'' Ms. McMahon said earlier Friday. ``However,
that's not to say they would abandon the concept of multiple organ
transplants.''
   Rolandrea was born with intractable secretory diarrhea, a
disorder that prevented her intestines from absorbing food and
liquids. She spent virtually all of her short life in hospitals.
   Earlier Friday, Dr. Thomas E. Starzl of the University of
Pittsburgh described Rolly's chances of survival as slim. Starzl
pioneered liver transplants and performed the nation's first
multiple abdominal organ transplant in 1983. That first patient, a
6-year-old girl, lived only a few hours.
   The nation's latest such patient, Calvin Oliveira, 14 months, of
Deerfield Beach, Fla., was doing well Friday despite a seizure
earlier in the week and a bout of pneumonia, D'Alessandro said. The
boy received a small intestine and liver Dec. 31 at the University
of Wisconsin Hospital and Clinics in Madison.
   Arthur Caplan, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at
the University of Minnesota, questions the legitimacy of the
procedure.
   ``Even if it worked well and people were living with a good
quality of life, I'm still not sure there are enough potential
donors,'' Caplan said. ``It's very rare to have someone with five
good organs.
   ``I'm also not sure society is going to view giving them all to a
single person is the best thing to do. I don't. I think if you can
spread the organs to more people, that is what should be done. The
ethical principle should be to save the most lives.''
   Intestines are particularly difficult to transplant, according to
D'Alessandro, because of the extremely technical nature of the
surgery, the lack of biological markers indicating organ rejection,
and the bowel's ability, unique among organs, to counterattack the
patient's immune system.
   Williams has performed such operations on two children. One died
three days after surgery. The other survived 3{ months.
   He is seeking a third transplant candidate with short gut
syndrome, a potentially fatal intestinal deformity, and whose liver
is failing as a result of intravenous feedings. Those were the
problems experienced by the world's longest survivor of a
multi-organ abdominal transplant, Tabatha Foster, 3{, of
Madisonville, Ky.
   Tabatha died last May, six months after receiving five organs at
Children's Hospital.
   ``This is an awful, devastating, hopeless condition in these
children and the truth is there isn't any treatment for them,''
other than transplantation, Williams said.
</TEXT>
