<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica     01-06 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Says Summit Should Be Postponed To Give Bush Time To Formulate
Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias on Friday said
the Jan. 15 summit of Central American nations should be postponed
until February to give President-elect George Bush time to develop a
policy for the region.
   But officials from some of the participating countries said they
still planned to attend the two-day gathering in El Salvador.
   Arias, who won a Nobel Peace Prize for spearheading a regional
peace plan, called on his counterparts in Honduras, Guatemala,
Nicaragua and El Salvador to delay their meeting.
   He added that it would be helpful to wait under after the Feb. 2
inauguration of President Carlos Andres of Venezuela and ask his
country's support in the peace process.
   The presidents had planned to discuss reviving the regional peace
plan they signed in 1987.
   Arias said the Central American leaders should give Bush, who
takes office on Jan. 20, and James Baker III, his designated
secretary of state, time to consider U.S. policy in Central America.
   ``It would be worth it to postpone the meeting until February,
after the inauguration of Mr. Bush,'' Arias said. He spoke at a
press conference Friday after giving reporters copies of a letter he
sent to the other Central American leaders.
   While the administration of President Reagan ``didn't fully
understand the plan for peace in Central America,'' Arias said ``the
statements of Mr. Baker make it appear that there is a commitment to
give diplomatic support to resolving the conflicts in Central
America.''
   The United States has financed the rebels trying to overthrow
Nicaragua's leftist government. It is backing the governments of El
Salvador and Guatemala in their conflicts with leftist rebels and
considers Costa Rica and Honduras strong allies.
   In addition to sending the letter, Arias said he telephoned
presidents Joses Azcona Hoyos of Honduras and Jose Napoleon Duarte
of El Salvador, as well as vice presidents Sergio Ramirez of
Nicaragua and Roberto Capio of Guatemala.
   Arias said he was unable to contact Nicaraugan President Daniel
Ortega, who was in Cuba for the 30th anniversary celebration of the
communist island state's revolution.
   Arias said he did not ask the Central American leaders what they
thought of his proposal, but simply told them why he thought the
meeting should be postponed.
   There was no immediate reaction to Arias' proposal from Nicaragua.
   Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez said that despite Arias'
proposal, Honduran officials still planned to attend the meeting.
   ``Honduras still has the good will to participate in the
presidents' meeting,'' said Lopez.
   In Guatemala, Vice President Roberto Campio Nicolle said he would
do everything he could to see the summit takes place as planned next
week in El Salvador.
   Duarte said he knew nothing about Arias' proposal. ``If there is
information like that, I don't have it,'' Duarte told reporters on
Friday. ``I'm still preparing for the meeting.''
   In August 1988, Arias told reporters that it was urgent that the
Central American leaders meet in January because ``it is dangerous
to let the time pass by.''
</TEXT>
