<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Soviet     01-06 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Soviet,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Minister Talks of Improved Tehran-Moscow Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's deputy foreign minister said on
Friday after returning from a special mission to Moscow that
Iran-Soviet relations have taken a turn for the better, Iran's
official news agency reported.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said
Mohammad Javad Larijani spoke at a news conference after delivering
a special message to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev from
Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Larijani returned home Thursday.
   Although the contents of Khomeini's letter were not revealed,
Larijani said the message praised Gorbachev for his bold new
leadership style, for his decision to pull troops out of
Afghanistan, and for permitting more religious freedom, IRNA said.
   Tehran radio, also monitored in Nicosia, on Thursday quoted
Khomeini's son and confidant, Ahmed Khomeini, as saying the letter
also urged Gorbachev to seriously study Islam.
   The Soviets agreed to help complete the Ramin and Beheshti power
plants, left unfinished when Soviet technicians were pulled out
during the Iran-Iraq war.
   Last month, Iran said it will resume supplying natural gas to the
southern Soviet Union through a pipeline shut down in 1980 over a
price dispute.
   Ranking Soviet officials have shuttled to Tehran in recent months
to enforce Moscow's commitment to strengthening ties with Iran.
   A visit to Tehran by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Sheverdnadze
is under consideration.
</TEXT>
