<FIRST>r a AM-Steinberg     01-06 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Testifies Hedda Nussbaum Abused Lisa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, the lover of a man on trial for
the murder of a 6-year-old girl he illegally adopted and the
prosecution's key witness, once flung the girl several feet and
slapped her, a witness testified Friday.
   ``I told Hedda that if she ever struck that child like that again
in my presence, I would (retaliate violently),'' said the witness,
Marilyn Walton.
   Ms. Walton, 38, a cabaret singer from Dallas and longtime friend
of the defendant, Joel Steinberg, appeared as a defense witness to
rebut Ms. Nussbaum's testimony that she never abused Lisa Steinberg.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with second-degree
murder in the beating death of Lisa, who was illegally adopted from
an unwed Long Island teen-ager.
   Lisa was taken unconscious from Steinberg's Greenwich Village
apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She was hospitalized and died of a brain
hemorrhage three days later.
   Steinberg told police he did not hit the child, and his lawyers
are suggesting that Ms. Nussbaum could have struck the fatal blow.
   Ms. Walton said the slapping incident occurred on a very cold day
in February 1983 after Ms. Nussbaum refused to let her and Lisa into
the building where Steinberg lived after they had gone to get ice
cream.
   The two finally were able to get in and went to the third-floor
apartment. Ms. Nussbaum opened the door and seemed angry, Ms. Walton
said.
   Ms. Nussbaum grabbed Lisa by the collar of her coat and yanked
her, the witness said. ``Lisa's body went pretty far across the ..
.'' Ms. Walton said before being interrupted.
   An objection by Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro was
sustained.
   ```Pretty far' is a characterization,'' Judge Harold Rothwax told
Ms. Walton. ``Just tell us what happened.''
   ``She flung Lisa,'' Ms. Walton replied. ``I saw Lisa look
stunned. I saw her almost lose her balance. I said, `Hedda, What are
you doing?'''
   ``Hedda raised her hand,'' the witness went on. ``Lisa was
squirming and she told her to stop. Lisa still squirmed and she (Ms.
Nussbaum) came down like that (bringing her hand down forcefully)
and hit her on the neck.''
   ``I went over to Lisa,'' Ms. Walton said. ``I tried to shield
her.''
   She said the child ``looked dazed; she recoiled; she looked
frightened; she backed away.'' At this point, Ms. Walton said, she
threatened Ms. Nussbaum.
   Steinberg then entered the apartment, Ms. Walton said. ``Hedda
suddenly became very docile,'' she said. ``It was as if nothing had
happened.''
   Ms. Nussbaum was intially charged with murder in Lisa's death
along with Steinberg. Charges against her were dropped and she
became a prosecution witness.
   Ms. Walton said Steinberg and Lisa had a ``loving father-daughter
relationship.''
   ``Did you ever see him hit her?'' asked Steinberg lawyer Adrian
DiLuzio.
   ``Not once.''
   Trial resumes Monday at 10 a.m. in Manhattan's State Supreme
Court.
</TEXT>
