<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Chess     01-06 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Chess,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judit Polgar, 12, Wins Challengers Tournament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judit Polgar of Hungary, the
highest-ranked 12-year-old chess player in history, won the
prestigious Hastings Challengers Tournament on Friday, and experts
hailed her as a future world champion.
   ``I was deeply impressed,'' said grandmaster Michael Wilder of
Princeton, N.J., the current U.S. champion.
   ``Never in history has anyone of this age played nearly this well
_ not Bobby Fischer, not Garri Kasparov, not even close. It's scary
to think about what she already accomplished.''
   At the closing ceremony, tournament director Stewart Reuben
introduced Miss Polgar as a ``future world champion.''
   She defeated Glenn Flear, a British grandmaster, in the final
round of the 99-player tournament to seize first place with eight
points out of a possible 10.
   Her result overwhelmed that of another prodigy whom she also
beat, 14-year-old Matthew Sadler of England who came in second with
7.5 points.
   A win scores one point and a draw half a point.
   The Challengers field included four grandmasters and a host of
international masters from around the world.
   Miss Polgar now qualifies for next year's Premier Tournament at
Hastings, an eight-player event featuring the world's leading
grandmasters. This year's Premier finishes Jan. 14 and is led by
England's Nigel Short, the world's third-ranked player.
   Following a year of stunning victories, the International Chess
Federation on Thursday declared Miss Polgar the world's
highest-ranked female player on their ranking lists, which are
updated every six months.
   On a joint list of men and women she would share 55th place with
two men and ahead of most of the 270 grandmasters in chess.
   Miss Polgar is the youngest of a remarkable trio of three sisters
from Budapest who appear likely to break the male domination of
chess.
   At November's Chess Olympiad in Salonica, Greece, the four-member
Hungarian women's team, which included the three Polgar sisters,
defeated the Soviets and took the gold medal in the separate women's
competition.
   The sisters' parents, Laszlo and Klara Polgar, educate their
children at home, having given up their professions to do so. Polgar
is a psychologist and his wife a teacher.
   After her final win in Hastings, a south England resort that was
staging its 64th Chess Congress, Miss Polgar and her mother went to
see the movie, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?'' before the closing
ceremony.
   Red-haired Judit told The Associated Press she was pleased with
her results but had missed the company of her sisters, Szofia, 14,
and Zsuzsa, 19.
   Asked how she managed to combine modesty in interviews with
crushing performances over the chess board she replied: ``It's
better than the other way.''
   All three sisters speak several languages. Judit speaks English
and Russian as well as her native Hungarian. From the age of five
the sisters have concentrated on chess and languages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
