<SECOND>AM-Barry-Drugs,1stLd-writethru, a0711, 530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Mum on Drug Tests, Medical Records</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Four grafs new at end to update with Lewis interview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. made no move Friday to
clear up a discrepancy between his contention that he has passed
drug tests the past five years and his doctor's statements that he
doesn't remember such tests.
   Barry, who is under federal investigation in connection with a
drug case targeting a former city employee, kept out of the public
eye Friday, spending the day in his office while reporters pressed
his aides for the mayor's medical records.
   He said Thursday, ``I've taken a drug test five years in a row''
as part of routine physical examinations. ``I've released them twice
a year.''
   However, spokesman John White said he knew nothing of any such
drug tests. And Barry's physician, Vincent J. Roux, said much the
same thing.
   ``I'm not sure I have ever given the mayor a drug test,'' Roux
told WUSA-TV. ``I don't remember.''
   Roux said he would not release the mayor's medical records
without Barry's authorization.
   Spokesman White said Friday that Barry was aware of repeated
requests for release of the records, but he added that he had no
idea whether the mayor would make the documents public.
   Barry, who has repeatedly denied drug use, is facing the worst
political crisis in his decade as mayor of the nation's capital
after disclosure of the fact that he had been visiting the former
city employee, Charles Lewis, at a Washington hotel at a time city
police were arriving to try and make an undercover drug buy from the
man.
   Police left when they learned Barry was at the hotel, authorities
have said, and a federal investigation is under way. Barry has
denied interfering with the city's drug probe, but has acknowledged
calling an assistant police chief who was supervising the drug
investigation. Barry said he was only trying to speed up the probe.
   White had said that Barry's physical examinations included urine
samples, but one medical expert said Friday that more than a routine
test would be needed to find indications of drug use.
   ``The drug tests are so specific, drugs won't show up there
unless the doctor is looking for them,'' said Dick Bast, senior
technical adviser at the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug
Abuse Information in Rockville, Md. ``They would not show up in a
normal urinalysis.''
   Most physicians do not have the sophisticated equipment and
labratory facilities necessary to conduct exhaustive drug tests from
urine samples, Bast added.
   Lewis, in his first public comments since the incident, was
quoted as saying the media was conducting ``a smear campaign''
against him and Barry.
   Lewis' comments came in an interview with the Virgin Islands
Daily News. Parts of the interview were published in Saturday's
editions of the Washington Post.
   Lewis denied in the interview that he had offered drugs to the
hotel housekeeper, as she has allegedly told police.
   ``I wasn't selling nothing, I wasn't enjoying nothing and neither
was the mayor,'' Lewis was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
