<SECOND>AM-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0854</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Says 14 U.S. Planes Involved in Air Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 25th, `ABC News...' with report U.S. rejected
Saudi offer to mediate. Pick up 26th pvs, `The diplomat...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya said Friday that 14 U.S. jets
attacked the two Libyan fighters shot down this week over the
Mediterranean, not two U.S. planes as Washington says.
   Meanwhile, warplanes in position for takeoff appeared on the
tarmac at Tripoli's airport, and soldiers guarded the fortress of
Col. Moammar Gadhafi, who was reported to fear a U.S. attack.
   A Western diplomat said he was told that Gadhafi had ousted his
military chief, but he said the report could not be confirmed. He
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Rajab Abou Dabbous, secretary of the Libyan information ministry,
told a news conference Friday evening that the U.S. account of
Wednesday's air attack was ``a fabrication.''
   He said 14 U.S. jets were involved and that the shooting was
premeditated. U.S. officials have said two U.S. jets fired after the
Libyan MiG-23s pursued them.
   ``The truth is that 14 (U.S. planes) _ count them _ attacked two
Libyan planes on a normal reconnaissance flight,'' said Dabbous.
   Libyan television broadcast similar charges.
   Libyan officials say the planes were unarmed reconnaissance
craft, but U.S. officials have produced video footage that they say
shows missiles on the Libyan planes.
   The atmosphere in Tripoli was tense, and many residents took
flight. The Western diplomat compared the mood in the city to the
days surrounding a U.S. raid on Libya in April 1986.
   Gadhafi has not been seen or heard from since Wednesday, when he
vowed to challenge the United States over this week's air battle.
   Tensions between the United States and Libya already had been
high because of U.S. allegations that a plant outside Tripoli was
designed to manufacture chemical weapons. Libya says the plant is
for manufacture of pharmaceuticals.
   The diplomat said he received a telephone call Friday from ``a
usually credible source'' saying Gadhafi had dismissed his military
chief, Col. Abu Bakr Younis Jaber.
   However, the diplomat said he was unable to confirm the report
and added that such rumors have circulated before. He said Gadhafi
reshuffled the military a few weeks ago, but it was unclear if the
military head had been affected.
   Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency said Wednesday that Gadhafi fired
his military chief to tighten control over the military in
anticipation of a U.S. assault.
   Diplomats in the capital said if true, the report could mean
Gadhafi feared his top military leaders might resist his orders in
the heat of an attack.
   The military chief, who like Gadhafi holds the highest rank in
the Libyan military, is one of a handful of survivors of the clique
that supported Gadhafi's 1969 coup, which overthrew the
Western-backed monarchy.
   At least two MiG-23 jet fighters sat at Tripoli's airport Friday,
poised to enter the takeoff runway. On Thursday, no military planes
were seen on any runway.
   Soldiers with machine guns and protected by sandbags guarded the
fortified complex of offices and housing where Gadhafi makes his
headquarters in Tripoli. As usual, tanks with mounted anti-missile
guns were parked inside.
   The compound, ringed by 25-foot concrete walls topped by barbed
wire, was a target of the 1986 U.S. raid. Gadhafi's whereabouts were
not known.
   The Western diplomat said that on Friday, as the capital closed
for the Moslem Sabbath, rumors circulated the United States bombed
the alleged chemical weapons plant at Rabta, 60 miles outside
Tripoli.
   The fears of a U.S. attack prompted many Tripoli residents to
leave the city.
   President Reagan has said he would not rule out military action
against the disputed plant.
   The diplomat also said he believed there were ``contacts between
the United States and Libya through a third, neutral country that
has sufficient relations with both'' since the air battle. He
declined to name the country or provide further details.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley confirmed Thursday that
Libya has attempted some back-channel contacts with the United
States recently, but she refused to define the substance of the
messages or how they were transmitted.
   ABC News reported Friday that Gadhafi last week asked Italy's
foreign minister to relay to Reagan a proposal to work out a deal so
the United States would not bomb the plant.
   The New York Times reported Saturday that two weeks before the
planes were shot down, the Reagan administration rejected an offer
from Saudi Arabia to mediate between the United States and Libya.
   The diplomat said the government was sending many civilians to
visit or stay at the plant, including schoolchildren.
   According to Libyan media, doctors and nurses have been holding a
sit-in at the factory to ``defend'' it, and demonstrations have
occurred there frequently in recent days.
   The diplomat said the government apparently wanted to ensure that
in the event of a raid, the plant would appear to be a civilian
target.
</TEXT>
