<HEAD>Boy Dies After Being Shot at School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with ID of arrested youth; ADDS details, quotes
from school spokeswoman; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy was fatally shot
Thursday on the playground of a junior high school as students and
faculty members watched, authorities said.
   Edward Burnett, a ninth-grader at Henderson Junior High School,
died shortly after being shot in the chest with a .22-caliber gun,
officials said.
   Willie J. Standley, 19, of Little Rock, was charged with
first-degree murder in the slaying of Burnett, Lt. Bert Jenkins
said. He said no charge would be filed against a second person taken
into custody.
   Jenkins said authorities were unable to come up with a motive for
the shooting at point-blank range. He said officers found a gun
believed to be the murder weapon.
   The shooting occurred 10 minutes before the start of school, said
Julia McGehee, a school district spokeswoman.
   ``There were supervisors on the grounds, not very far from where
he was killed and there were no indications of anything untoward at
all. They were unloading the buses as usual,'' Ms. McGehee said.
   Some parents picked their children up from school early, and the
school was providing counselors for others. But school was to remain
in session.
   ``We have sent in extra nurses. Students have been and are being
notified of the tragedy. We have counselors and have brought in
extra people,'' Ms. McGehee said.
   The district also brought in counselors in November 1987 when
when two children who were students in the district were shot to
death in their home with other relatives.
   ``We know tragedy can strike and it can traumatize children who
knew the victim. We're trying to do all we can to work through this
situation,'' she said.
