<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailers who expected only a modest pickup in their Christmas
business got a big _ and welcome _ surprise as consumers, caught up
in the holiday spirit, shopped with renewed enthusiasm in December.
   Analysts said Thursday that holiday sales were higher than
expected, rising in a range of 6 percent to 7.5 percent, an
improvement over the 6 percent gain forecast before the start of the
season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Booming year-end car and truck sales at General
Motors Corp. and a jump in car sales at Ford Motor Co. contributed
to an overall increase in domestic sales of cars and light trucks in
1988.
   Manufacturers said Thursday that sales of U.S.-made cars and
light trucks averaged 44,477 a day in the Dec. 21-31 period, up 20.7
percent from the same period in 1987.
   For the year, domestic car and light-truck sales reached 11.7
million, averaging 38,060 a day in 1988, up 7.5 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. will be allowed to keep the
name of its new Lexus line of luxury cars, at least temporarily.
   An appeals court in New York extended on Thursday a reprieve
given the company earlier this week after a federal judge issued a
restraining order last week forbidding Toyota from using the Lexus
name. It resumes hearings Jan. 30.
   Mead Data General Inc. has sued Toyota claiming that the Lexus
name diluted the business of its Lexis legal information retrieval
service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover speculator Paul Bilzerian pleaded
innocent to 12 counts of fraud and said he hoped to clear his name
and resume hunting for companies to buy.
   The 38-year-old financier, who heads Singer Co., was arraigned
Thursday in Manhattan federal court on a dozen felony counts linked
to four failed takeover situations in 1985 and 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high-yield bond
financier Michael Milken is facing unprecedented pressure to strike
a plea deal with prosecutors after his firm agreed to expel him and
withhold his 1988 compensation as part of its settlement of criminal
fraud charges.
   Sources familiar with the negotiations Thursday confirmed press
reports about terms of a probable departure by Milken, who has
continued to assert innocence in a deepening criminal investigation
of his financial dealings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top lawyer defending GAF Corp. against stock
manipulation charges hammered away at the credibility of the
government's star witness, who admitted he'd discarded records that
documented the alleged crime.
   Defense attorney Arthur Liman's grilling Thursday of former
securities broker Boyd Jefferies dominated the latest session in the
trial of GAF and one of its senior officers, now in its third week
at Manhattan federal court.
   GAF and vice chairman James Sherwin have vowed to vindicate
themselves.
