<DOCNO> AP890106-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel     01-06 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pressure Intensifies on Top Drexel Financier To Capitulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pressure is mounting on Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.'s high-yield bond financier Michael Milken to strike a
plea deal with prosecutors who have been investigating his financial
dealings.
   Sources familiar with the negotiations, who spoke on condition
they not be identified, confirmed on Thursday press reports that his
firm agreed to expel him and withhold his 1988 compensation as part
of its record settlement of criminal fraud charges.
   Milken, one of the most powerful financiers of the 1980s, is
expected to be indicted on fraud and racketeering charges shortly
unless he agrees to plead guilty in exchange for more lenient
treatment.
   But Milken has repeatedly asserted innocence.
   Drexel, which had stood by Milken for more than two years in
asserting innocence, agreed to plead guilty to charges stemming from
its links with the now-imprisoned inside trader Ivan F. Boesky.
   The nation's fifth-largest investment firm said it would pay a
record $650 million in fines and restitution, admit guilt to six
felony counts and cooperate in the government's expanding probes of
Wall Street corruption, in effect making Drexel a source of evidence
against Milken.
   The financier has faced tremendous pressure to reach a plea
agreement because of Drexel's reversed position. But lawyers said
his expulsion from a firm he helped build into a powerhouse,
compounded by the withholding of compensation due him, provided even
more of an incentive for him to capitulate.
   ``The pressure mounting on Milken is just so intense now,'' said
one former assistant U.S. attorney now in private practice in New
York. ``He's getting it from all directions.''
   Milken is said to be one of the wealthiest investment bankers in
the country, but forfeiture of his lucrative annual compensation
from Drexel could seriously crimp his legal warchest for fighting
criminal charges.
   He has never disclosed his annual compensation but once was
quoted as saying he has paid hundreds of millions of dollars in
taxes and given millions more to charitable foundations.
   Milken and his small team of aides reportedly earned more than
$250 million in annual bonuses alone in 1986. He also is said to own
a 6 percent interest in Drexel, which is privately held but
extremely profitable. It was unclear how his expulsion from the firm
would affect that stake.
   Drexel's settlement of criminal charges, reached Dec. 21 with the
Manhattan U.S. attorney's office, was contingent on a Jan. 10
settlement of parallel civil charges against Drexel filed by the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Senior emissaries from Drexel have been meeting with SEC officers
in Washington to negotiate the settlement, where terms of Milken's
departure were said to be reached. A source familiar with those
discussions said Thursday they have been ``without acrimony and
positive in spirit.''
   The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that the SEC was
seeking to alter the structure of Drexel's operations in so-called
junk bonds, the high-yield debt securities pioneered by Milken into
a $175 billion market.
   Quoting unspecified sources, the Journal said SEC negotiators
want Drexel to transfer supervision of the junk-bond unit, which is
based in Beverly Hills near Milken's home, to New York where Drexel
is headquartered.
   In addition, the Journal said the SEC wants to approve a
compliance officer that would monitor Drexel's trading operations
and other activities.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder declined to comment on any aspect
of the negotiations with the SEC. Kenneth Lerer, a public relations
executive who speaks on Milken's behalf, also declined to comment.
   SEC spokesman Chiles Larson said the enforcement agency was not
commenting on the Drexel matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
