<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GAFTrial     01-06 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Trial,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAF Defense Grills Government's Chief Witness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top lawyer defending GAF Corp. against stock
manipulation charges hammered away at the credibility of the
government's star witness, who admitted he'd discarded records that
documented the alleged crime.
   Defense attorney Arthur Liman's grilling of former securities
broker Boyd Jefferies dominated Thursday's session in the trial of
GAF and one of its senior officers, now in its third week at
Manhattan federal court.
   The defense also repeated an earlier request for a mistrial on
grounds the government withheld evidence suggesting a key document
was tampered with. U.S. District Judge Mary J. Lowe declined to rule
on the mistrial motion and gave no indication when she would do so.
   The trial has attracted widespread interest because GAF and vice
chairman James Sherwin are the first defendants in a federal
crackdown on securities fraud to reach the trial phase. They have
vowed to vindicate themselves.
   In addition, GAF also is the first industrial concern implicated
in a network of criminal probes emanating from the 1986 downfall of
inside trader Ivan F. Boesky, now serving a three-year prison term
for securities fraud.
   The trial also marks the court debut of Jefferies, himself a
victim of Boesky's disclosures to federal prosecutors. Jefferies is
the lead witness in the GAF case and at least two other prosecutions.
   He has claimed his Los Angeles brokerage, Jefferies &amp; Co.,
arranged to manipulate up the price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in
late 1986 at the behest of GAF, which had abandoned a takeover
attempt of the larger chemical company and wanted to sell its chunk
of Carbide at a maximum profit.
   Jefferies testified earlier this week that Sherwin had guaranteed
his brokerage against loss for the alleged manipulation. Jefferies
ultimately lost about $40,000 and Sherwin promised to pay it through
a phony invoice for investment banking charges, the broker testified.
   Under Liman's cross-examination, Jefferies admitted he'd thrown
out records kept on legal-size yellow pads of the transaction after
he was implicated in securities fraud by Boesky. Jefferies agreed to
turn state's evidence on March 16, 1987, about five months after the
alleged manipulation took place.
   ``Yes they (the legal pads) were thrown out,'' Jefferies said.
``My secretary and I cleaned out my office on March 30, 1987.''
   He described it as a routine housecleaning.
   Under further questioning, Jefferies said he couldn't remember
why the alleged agreement with GAF wasn't included in details of a
plea bargain he made with the Securities and Exchange Commission and
federal prosecutors.
   The 58-year-old broker resigned from Jefferies after Boesky
implicated him in securities fraud. Jefferies himself has agreed to
plead guilty to two felony counts, for which he could face a maximum
sentence of 10 years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
