<FIRST>u f PM-AutoShow Bjt   01-06 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Show, Bjt,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadgets Galore in Store For '90s Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The North American International Auto Show may be
intended as a showcase for domestic and foreign automakers, but
gadgets also on display _ such as compact disk players, television
sets and other electronic devices _ are themselves a tribute to high
technology.
   Recent advances in computer chips are the reason for the
explosion of gadgets being exhibited alongside the 700 or so
vehicles at the season's first automotive show.
   Dozens of cars have on-board computers that buzz, flash or beep
to tell drivers about engine performance, fluid levels and the
climate inside and outside the vehicle. Without chips, these gadgets
wouldn't exist.
   One of the most complicated items is an optional video display
screen inside an Oldsmobile Toronado Trofeo that can help a driver
keep track of dozens of things, ranging from how much oil is in the
crankcase to what appointments he has scheduled the next day.
   By touching the screen at the center of the dashboard, a driver
or passenger can change the radio station, alter the temperature in
the car or learn the compass direction in which the car is traveling.
   But the screen doesn't come cheap. It's a $3,000 option that,
until May, can be had for $2,000. There's a mock up of a front seat
and dashboard in the Oldsmobile exhibit in Cobo Hall here so
show-goers can see how it works.
   Other cars, including some made by the Acura division of Honda,
have odometers that can figure mileage left in a trip and fuel
economy.
   One of the cars getting the most attention at the show is the
Lexus LS400, a luxury car by Toyota Motor Corp. slated to go on sale
beginning this fall.
   In the trunk, on the right side, is a compact disk player that
can hold up to six CDs. On the dashboard are controls for the unit,
which is a standard feature on a car expected to retail for about
$40,000.
   ``I think you're seeing a tremendous amount of minor changes,''
analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York said Thursday
while at the show, which opens to the public Saturday and runs
through Jan. 15.
   He and other analysts have said that overall, 1989 model cars and
trucks don't offer much that is new. But big changes are due in the
1990s, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
