<FIRST>r f BC-China-USSoftware     01-06 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-US Software,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Company, Chinese Form Software Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese software developers will write programs
for overseas customers in a joint venture with a U.S. conglomerate
that was launched Friday.
   UniHorn Inc., a San Francisco-based subsidiary of Unison Inc.,
joined with six institutes of the Chinese Aerospace Ministry and
China Great Wall Industry Corp., which is trying to sell Chinese
satellite-launching services.
   The venture is called Astro-UniHorn Computer Technology Co.
   The research institutes have several thousand people who already
have developed software that ``is very interesting and can be
commercialized and shows a lot of potential,'' UniHorn Vice
President James H. Spear Jr. said.
   The joint venture will develop and package the software for
international markets, including the United States, Spear said.
Projects will include software that enables computers to do
engineering design work, called computer-aided design, he said. He
refused to give specifics.
   Although Great Wall Industry Corp. is trying to sell Chinese
satellite-launching services abroad, the joint venture does not plan
any projects in aerospace or missiles, Spear said.
   ``We're not focused that way and we don't believe our Chinese
partners are focused that way,'' he said. He said UniHorn sought out
the Chinese partners because of their low-cost expertise.
   The research institutes have had their budgets cut in recent
years and are interested in doing outside work, Spear said, adding
that the venture also could help develop China's infant computer
industry.
   Most Chinese computer-related companies have merely adapted
foreign hardware and software.
   Unison has four other joint ventures in China, including the
Great Wall Hotel in Beijing, one of the city's largest hotels
directed at foreign tourists.
</TEXT>
