<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-06 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Open Higher; Wheat Retreats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and corn futures prices opened a bit
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade but wheat futures
retreated slightly, reflecting nervousness about next week's
Agriculture Department crop report.
   The report, which is due out on Wednesday afternoon, will contain
the government's first estimates of 1989 planted acreage plus new
grain-surplus tallies and the final 1988 crop production numbers.
   Analysts said the early strength in the soybean market stemmed
from strong spot prices for soybean meal, possibly linked to new
purchases by the Soviet Union.
   The USDA has denied rumors that it plans to expand to 20 million
metric tons the maximum amount of U.S. grain the Soviets may
purchase annually under the long-term grain agreement between the
United States and the Soviet Union.
   But analysts say such an expansion is almost certain, since the
Soviets already are approaching the current maximum of 16 million
metric tons.
   ``Our sources feel there is a high probability the maximum will
be extended,'' said Steve Freed, a grain market analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``We feel it's a done deal.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.47 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to { cent higher with March at $2.87 a bushel; oats were unchanged
to \ cent higher with March at $2.45 a bushel; soybeans were 3\
cents to 5{ cents higher with January at $8.17 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .10 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in February at 73.42 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .05 cent lower to .22 cent higher with January at 84.67
cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
February at 47.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent
to .30 cent higher with February at 44.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
