<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Collins 1stLd-Writethru   01-06 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Collins, 1st Ld-Writethru,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>William Collins Backs Murdoch's Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT that News International controls 54
percent, sted 43.3 percent; CORRECTS last graf pvs to show that Murdoch
owns five British national papers, sted four; ADDs new final graf to show
share prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Collins PLC said Friday it would recommend
shareholders accept a takeover bid by publisher Rupert Murdoch's
News International PLC which values the British publishing company
at $725 million.
   News International, a subsidiary of Murdoch's News Corp., has
provided Collins with assurances of editorial independence which it
had sought in exchange for recommending the takeover bid.
   ``Collins will remain free to pursue its existing editorial
policy of publishing authors with a wide variety of beliefs and
views,'' News International said in a statement.
   News International said it controls 54 percent percent of
Collins' voting stock and has offered $15.84 a share for the
remainder of the Collins shares it doesn't already own.
   News International originally bid only $527 million for Collins,
an offer scorned by the publisher as ``ludicrously low.''
   But Murdoch raised his offer by 37 percent to $725 million
following an identical rival bid by Groupe de la Cite, France's
second largest book publisher.
   Groupe de la Cite approached News International on Wednesday with
an improved offer for Collins on condition the Murdoch group would
sell its voting stake in Collins. But News International refused and
the French firm withdrew its offer.
   News International, a publisher of newspapers and magazines in
Britain, first gained a major stake in Collins in 1981 in an earlier
takeover attempt.
   Trade and Industry Secretary Lord Young said early Thursday that
he would not refer the News International bid to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission, which has the power to prevent mergers deemed
harmful to competition.
   Bryan Gould, the opposition Labor Party's trade and industry
spokesman, called on the government Friday to halt the takeover and
refer Murdoch's entire media empire to the commission.
   ``Government indifference to Rupert Murdoch's bid for the
publishers Collins underlines once again that Tory media supporters
are immune from any normal competition policy,'' Gould said in a
letter to Young.
   ``Press, media and publishing businesses are already far too
concentrated in this country, with Rupert Murdoch the worst
offender,'' he said.
   Murdoch's media empire spans the globe, with television,
newspaper and magazine interests concentrated in the United States
and Britain.
   Murdoch owns five national newspapers in Britain, the Times of
London, The Sunday Times, Today, News of the World and The Sun, and
has interests in satellite television.
   Around midday on the London Stock Exchange, News International
shares were up 1 penny (2 cents) at 214 pence ($3.85), while Collins
shares were off 12 pence (22 cents) at 870 pence ($15.66).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
