<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   01-06 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>UPDATES throughout With Closing Share Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange rose
Friday, boosted by more speculative buying and another jump in the
dollar.
   The major dollar-earning companies turned in another strong
performance as the U.S. currency rose sharply following the release
of U.S. employment data in the afternoon.
   Dollar stocks provided a firm underpinning for the market, which
was otherwise preoccupied by another bout of speculative buying in
the leading shares.
   Various rumors about the progress of General Electric Co. and
Siemens AG's joint 1.7 billion pound bid for Plessey Co. prompted
heavy trading in General Electric's and Plessey stock. The stores
sector, which has suffered recently from higher British interest
rates, also saw active trading.
   The FT-SE 100 index closed 11.8 points, or .66 percent, higher at
1811.3.
   The Financial Times 30 share index closed 9.8 points higher at
1481.3. Volume was a moderate 456.2 million shares, up from 448.0
million shares a day earlier.
   The market opened on a nervous note as Chase Manhattan announced
it would withdraw from trading in British equities.
   Several U.S. brokerage firms recently have trimmed their British
operations, citing low trading volume following last year's stock
market crash and strong competition among market makers in the wake
of the Big Bang, the 1986 deregulation of Britain's financial
markets.
   Last month, Citicorp and Smith Barney Harris Upham International
Inc. said they were cutting back their equity trading operations in
Britain. The market managed to shake off the Chase news, helped by
the stronger dollar. After some uncertainty before release of U.S.
employment data, the market climbed to the day's high in the
afternoon.
   GEC, which is not related to the U.S. company of the same name,
closed 4 pence higher at 202 pence amid heavy trading.
   A total 16 million GEC shares changed hands before the close.
Trading was also active in GEC options. More than 3,000 GEC
contracts were traded, the second most heavily traded stock on the
options market Friday after British Gas.
   Plessey shares advanced 4 pence to 228 pence after GEC@Siemens
entered the market for the first time since launching their bid to
purchase 5 million Plessey shares, less than 1 percent of the total.
   The Financial Times 500 share index was 1019.89, up 6.80.
</TEXT>
