<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Close Higher; Grains Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately higher
Friday in a mostly technical rally on the Chicago Board of Trade
while grain futures finished narrowly mixed.
   Soybeans advanced despite forecasts for a rainy weekend in the
South American soybean belt, where a recent dry spell had prompted
concern about the newly planted crop.
   In addition to bullish technical market signals, soybean buying
was spurred by expectations that next week's Agriculture Department
crop report will underline the tight supply situation caused by the
past summer's drought, analysts said.
   ``The stocks-to-usage ratio is one of the tightest in the last 30
years,'' said Mickey Luth, soybean market analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   The USDA report, which will be released Wednesday afternoon, will
contain the government's first estimates of 1989 planted acreage
plus grain-surplus tallies and the final 1988 crop production
numbers.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 2} cents lower to { cent
higher with the contract for delivery in March at $4.48} a bushel;
corn was 1{ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with March at $2.89 a
bushel; oats were 2\ cents lower to \ cent higher with March at
$2.42} a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7{ cents higher with
January at $8.18 a bushel.
