<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HealthCrusader Bjt   01-06 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Crusader, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millionaire Health Crusader Poorer But Says Consumers Richer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillionaire is $2 million poorer, but
he's convinced American consumers are richer as the result of his
one-man quest to rid food of highly saturated tropical oils he calls
poison.
   ``It's a story of the little guy against the giant and the giant
is backing down,'' said Omaha businessman Phil Sokolof, who spends
almost all his time on his anti-cholesterol campaign.
   The 66-year-old Sokolof poured $2 million into nationwide
newspaper advertising in an effort to persuade the public to stop
buying foods high in saturated fat because of tropical oils, chiefly
coconut oil and palm oil.
   Saturated fats increase blood cholesterol levels, which can lead
to heart attacks.
   Sokolof has claimed victory over four major food processors _
Kellogg's, Sunshine Biscuits, Pepperidge Farm and Keebler.
   Keebler became the latest corporate trophy head in Sokolof's
health crusade when its president announced Wednesday that all
tropical oil, lard and beef fat would be removed from Keebler
products.
   ``I think it's great for the American public that thousands of
lives will be extended because there are now four major companies
that are reformulating literally hundreds of products to eliminate
tropical oils,'' he said.
   Sokolof, who blames high cholesterol for a near-fatal heart
attack he suffered 22 years ago, said he is honored to be referred
to by health news writers as ``America's No. 1 cholesterol fighter.''
   ``I think I got that title because it is vacant. There is no
Ralph Nader of the cholesterol world,'' he said.
   His ad campaign targets foods that are high in saturated fats,
yet portrayed as healthful through such label claims as ``no
cholesterol,'' ``low-salt,'' ``non-dairy'' and ``made with 100
percent vegetable shortening.''
   ``You can say it has no cholesterol, but if you eat palm oil and
coconut oil, they turn into cholesterol inside your body,'' Sokolof
said.
   ``Amost everyone has known that fatty meats and ... most dairy
products are high in cholesterol and saturated fat. But they didn't
know about coconut oil and palm oil. Hopefully they do now.''
   Keebler President Thomas Garvin told the Washington Post that the
change in his company's food formulas had no connection with
Sokolof's campaign. He accused Sokolof of sensationalizing the issue.
   Brian Dobson, a spokesman for Sunshine Biscuits, made similar
comments when he announced last month that Sunshine would eliminate
palm oil and palm kernel from its cookie and cracker products.
   Sokolof, however, said he was confident his full-page ads warning
of the ``poisoning of America'' helped put public pressure on the
corporations to respond to consumers' concerns.
   ``It's pretty coincidental that four of the majors did that
within two months of my first ad, isn't it?'' he asked. His favorite
example is Kellogg's and its Cracklin' Oat Bran cereal.
   ``To start with, they (Kellogg's corporate officers) said I was
irresponsible. They said I was practicing quackery. Then two weeks
later they called and asked to take them out of the ads because they
were going to take tropical oils out of the cereal,'' he said.
   Sokolof's biggest single-day expenditure was $140,000 to place
full-page ads in the Wall Street Journal and USA Today.
   He also advertised in the New York Times and New York Post, but
some newspapers, including the Washington Post, objected to the term
``poison'' and refused to run the ads.
   His initial advertising blitz in November singled out Kellogg's
Cracklin' Oat Bran, Sunshine's Hydrox cookies, Pepperidge Farm's
Goldfish crackers, Keebler's Club crackers, Nabisco's Triscuit
crackers, Procter &amp; Gamble's Crisco shortening and three non-dairy
coffee creamers _ Coffee Swirl from Kraft, Carnation's Coffeemate
and Borden's Creamora.
   ``There is still a long way to go. Nabisco has 50 products with
coconut or palm oil,'' Sokolof said.
   Sokolof declined to discuss his wealth, except to confirm he is a
multimillionaire and say that the $2 million expenditure has not
placed much of a dent in his net worth.
   The energetic widower describes himself as a workaholic.
   He made his fortune in his father's Omaha-based construction
business, Phillips Manufacturing Co. He founded the National Heart
Savers Association in 1985, supporting it largely through his own
contributions.
   His name became synonymous with the fight against fatty foods
after he offered free cholesterol tests on Capitol Hill. His
promotional packets include endorsement letters signed by dozens of
congressmen and senators.
   ``People who get involved with our campaign actually feel like
they have been misled and deceived by the food giants,'' he said.
   ``They can go to their food pantry and find three or four of
these products and throw them away. ... You and I can't control
world peace, but we can control what we eat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890106-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ThunderbirdTrouble Bjt   01-06 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thunderbird Trouble, Bjt,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderbird: Car of the Year Tough to Get</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. proudly boasts about receiving
Motor Trend's Car of the Year award for its new Thunderbird SC. But
don't fall in love with the car just yet _ only a few hundred of
them are available.
   The rest are delayed while Ford replaces defective crankshafts.
   Television advertisements, touting Ford as the winner of the
Motor Trend award in three of the last four years, carry a
disclaimer that the cars are available only in limited quantities.
   ``It's kind of ironic,'' said Christopher Merriman, a Ford dealer
in Flat Rock, Mich. ``But Ford is sticking to its original plan not
to bring the car out until it's ready.''
   Large supplies of the Thunderbird Super Coupe won't be available
until March, Ford Division General Manager Thomas Wagner said
Thursday.
   ``There's very few on the road today, but they are for sale out
there,'' he said.
   Max Jurosek, the company's vice president for car product
development, said during testing last August and September it was
decided that a forged iron crankshaft, instead of a cast iron one,
should be used in the Thunderbird SC and the Mercury Cougar XR7,
both of which are made at Ford's plant in Lorain, Ohio.
   ``The variability of the cast process meant we were getting a lot
of scrap,'' Wagner said. ``We wouldn't use them all.''
   Crankshafts change the up-and-down motion of pistons into rotary
motion that goes to wheels. Forged crankshafts, which are stamped
into shape, are stronger and more expensive than cast crankshafts,
shaped by pouring molten metal into molds.
   Crankshaft castings were produced by Ford at a factory in Canada.
The forged crankshafts are being made by Sumitomo Metal Co. in Japan.
   Sumitomo began shipping the forged crankshafts to Ford this month
and will deliver at least 50,000 a year, said Kiyoshi Imanishi,
sales and marketing manager for the Japanese company.
   Ford spokesman Bert Serre said 390 XR7s and Super Coupes were
built before the end of last year, and most were distributed inside
the company. Wagner said the cars with cast crankshafts pose no
safety problem.
   Ford officials said dealers have ordered about 25,000 Super
Coupes and 3,000 XR7s.
   Jack Nerad, executive editor of Motor Trend, said the magazine
wasn't aware of the crankshaft problem when it gave Thunderbird the
award, but it would have made no difference because ``our Car of the
Year test is not a durability test.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
