<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-06 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply; Gold Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply for a third straight day
Friday as traders interpreted comments by a West German official as
being bullish for the U.S. currency.
   Gold prices fell. In New York trading, Republic National Bank
quoted a bid of $406.25 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EST,
down from $408.25 late Thursday. Gold also declined on overseas
markets.
   The dollar surged after Helmut Schlesinger, vice president of the
Bundesbank, said the West German central bank had not intervened
recently to influence exchange rates.
   Dealers said Schlesinger's remarks were taken to mean the central
bank did not intend to defend certain exchange levels, which would
allow the dollar to gain against the West German mark.
   However, the Bundesbank and the Federal Reserve did enter the
market Friday to stem the dollar's rise against the mark, said Dan
Holland, an assistant vice president at Discount Corp. But the
dollar still put in a strong performance.
   On Thursday, Schlesinger said the Bundesbank would maintain a
slightly restrictive monetary policy to thwart inflationary
pressures in the West German economy. Those comments had a different
effect on the dollar, putting a slight damper on its rally that day.
   Holland said the Labor Department's announcement Friday that
civilian unemployment in December dropped from 5.4 percent to 5.3
percent had no effect on the dollar.
   However, foreign currency dealers said the dollar gained on the
news because it indicated strength in the U.S. economy and raised
the possibility of higher U.S. interest rates.
   Friday was the third consecutive day of strong gains for the
dollar. It began its advance Wednesday following news that U.S. jet
fighters had shot down two Libyan war planes over the Mediterranean
Sea.
   The British pound lost more than 4.5 cents against the dollar in
three trading sessions in London, where one pound cost $1.7797 late
Friday, cheaper for buyers than late Thursday's $1.7970. Sterling
also declined in New York, slipping to $1.7780 from late Thursday's
$1.7940.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late prices, included: 1.8170 West German marks, up from 1.7985;
1.54825 Swiss francs, up from 1.5380; 6.1985 French francs, up from
6.1415; 1,331.00 Italian lire, up from 1,318.50; and 1.19725
Canadian dollars, up from 1.9025.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with Thursday's late rates,
included: 1.8140 West German marks, up from 1.7955; 1.5475 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5195; 6.1830 French francs, up from 6.1155; 2.0480
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0220; 1,330.50 Italian lire, up from
1,316.25; 1.1912 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1877.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 125.97 Japanese yen, up
from Thursday's late 124.50. In London late Friday the dollar traded
higher at 126.40 yen, and in New York, it rose to 126.725 yen from
late Thursday's 125.975.
   Although gold prices fell, the metal remained resilient, traders
said, and was helped by increasing demand from Middle East buyers
worried about the U.S.-Libyan situation.
   Gold closed in London, the major market, at a bid $405.75 a troy
ounce, down from $407.75 on Thursday. The closing price in Zurich,
Switzerland, was $405.50 bid, down from $407.20.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at a bid $410.44, down from
$410.94.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold fell to $406.30 a
troy ounce from $407.90 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.97 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday and the metal's lowest level since March
1987. However, silver edged higher on the Comex in New York, closing
at $5.988 a troy ounce in comparison to Thursday's $5.965.
</TEXT>
