<FIRST>u f AM-GM-Smith Bjt   01-06 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Smith, Bjt,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM's Smith: More Concerned Now than a Year Ago About '89</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith said
Friday his concern about the health of the U.S. automobile industry
in 1989 _ particularly the second half _ is growing.
   ``I'm more concerned now than I was a year ago,'' Smith said
before speaking to a luncheon meeting of the Economic Club of
Detroit. ``A year ago, we were predicting a good market and I felt
confident about it.
   ``I feel pretty good now about the first and second quarters,''
he added. ``I'm very concerned about the third and the fourth
quarter ... because we've got a new administration down there and I
hope that they solve that deficit problem.
   ``It's a more acute problem now. It's been festering for a year.''
   The 1988 calendar and model years were among the best in
automobile history with more than 15 million cars and light trucks
sold. Analysts and officials for GM, Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp. have predicted a slower sales year in 1989.
   On other matters, Smith:
   _Said GM was negotiating with officials of the Soviet Union about
vehicle and component production in Russia. But he said no agreement
was close.
   ``I would hope all of us (GM, Ford and Chrysler) could sign an
agreement with the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   _Welcomed Nissan Motor Corp.'s and Toyota Motor Corp.'s new
luxury car lines being prepared for the U.S. market.
   ``I don't see that this is competition any different than
before,'' Smith said. ``If I had one wish, it would be that they
built (the cars) in the United States.''
   _Said quality and technology has improved in the U.S. auto
industry so much lately ``that if the Japanese market were to really
open up to us, we'd have an excellent competitive opportunity
there.''
   _Denied a report in Friday's Wall Street Journal that an
agreement had been reached with Toyota to produce pickup trucks at
the GM-Toyota plant in California. ``We are negotiating with them,
but we have not reached an agreement,'' he said.
   But when asked if an agreement to make such a vehicle at the New
United Motor Manufacturing Plant in Fremont, Calif., was close,
Smith said flatly, ``Yes.''
   _Called on the government to let industry take the lead in
environmental and safety issues. Smith suggested economic incentives
for companies to spur efforts to clean up the environment and
provide a safe workplace.
   ``Certainly, in a free society, you want to control people as
little as possible,'' he said, ``in our own society, that means
leaving most economic decisions to the marketplace.''
</TEXT>
