<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-06 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steep Copper Sell-Off Linked To Exchange Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices fell sharply Friday on New York's Commodity
Exchange in a sell-off linked to profit-taking and the dollar's
strength against the British pound.
   On other markets, coffee futures also plunged; cotton was sharply
higher; energy futures rose; precious metals, livestock, meat, grain
and soybean futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Copper settled 3.4 cents to 7.2 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in March at $1.36 a pound. Copper for spot delivery settled
at $1.478 a pound.
   Analysts said there had been no change in the bullish supply and
demand factors that helped boost the price of spot copper to a
record $1.6475 a pound on Dec. 8.
   ``There's no fresh news to account for the decline,'' said Peter
Cardillo, an analyst with the brokerage firm Josephthal &amp; Co. in New
York.
   New York-based analyst James Steel of Refco Inc., a large
commodities brokerage company, said the copper market was pressured
by arbitrage selling linked to the dollar's strength against the
pound.
   Copper futures are traded in dollars on the Commodity Exchange
and in pounds on the London Metal Exchange. When the shifting
exchange rate makes the dollar worth more in pounds, as happened
Friday, large-scale players can profit by simultaneously selling
copper on the Commodity Exchange and buying the same amount of
copper in London.
   ``They actually end up with a flat position (on the copper
market) but they make money on the currency exchange,'' Steel said.
   Analysts said the dollar was boosted by rising U.S. interest
rates, continuing tension in the Mediterranean and by the Labor
Department's announcement that civilian unemployment in December
dropped from 5.4 percent to 5.3 percent.
   The dollar's gain drew a negative reaction in the gold market but
silver futures advanced on perceptions that recent declines were
unwarranted, analysts said.
   Gold settled $1.60 to $2.20 lower with February at $408.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.3 cents to 2.7 cents higher with March at $6.075
a troy ounce.
   Coffee futures finished sharply lower on New York's Coffee, Sugar
&amp; Cocoa Exchange on speculative selling tied to bearish technical
market signals, analysts said.
   ``The fact that the market failed to push through the highs of
the last couple of days undermined the bullishness from a technical
perspective,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Coffee settled 3.5 cents to 5.25 cents lower with March at
$1.5772 a pound.
   Cotton futures surged in the final 20 minutes of trading on the
New York Cotton Exchange but analysts could cite no particular
reason for the advance.
   Cotton settled .50 cent to 1.69 cents higher with March at 59.82
cents a pound.
   Most energy futures rose modestly on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 10 cents
higher with February at $17.55 a barrel; heating oil was .02 cent to
.13 cent higher with February at 53.60 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .15 cent lower to .32 cent higher with February at
47.72 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures ended narrowly mixed ahead of the
Agriculture Department's quarterly U.S. hogs and pigs report.
   In the report, which was released after the close of trading, the
USDA estimated the nation's hog-and-pig herd at 55.3 million head as
of Dec. 1, a 1 percent increase over 1987's figure. The number was
slightly below most analysts' pre-report estimates and analysts said
they expected pork futures to open higher on Monday.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with
February at 73.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower
to .08 cent higher with January at 84.35 cents a pound; live hogs
were .43 cent lower to .17 cent higher with February at 47.12 cents
a pound; frozen pork bellies were .07 cent lower to .35 cent higher
with February at 44.45 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures closed moderately higher Friday in a mostly
technical rally on the Chicago Board of Trade while grain futures
finished narrowly mixed.
   In addition to bullish technical signals, soybean buying was
spurred by expectations that Wednesday's USDA crop report will
underline the tight supply situation caused by the past summer's
drought, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 2} cents lower to { cent higher with March at
$4.48} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with
March at $2.89 a bushel; oats were 2\ cents lower to \ cent higher
with March at $2.42} a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 6} cents
higher with January at $8.17} a bushel.
   Stock-index futures settled slightly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The contract for March delivery of the Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 index settled .40 point higher at 283.40. Each point is
worth $500.
</TEXT>
