<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ElectronicsShow     01-06 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Electronics Show,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disneyland for Adults Opens in Vegas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE> Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual Consumer Electronics Show, an
electronic Disneyland for adults, opens Saturday with 1,450
exhibitors touting wares ranging from camcorders and computers to
TVs, video games and adult flicks.
   Between 90,000 and 100,000 members of the multibillion-dollar
industry are expected to view exhibits in four locations covering
space the size of 17 football fields.
   Industry executives say they are looking for a big year in their
diverse industry, despite concerns about the economy.
   ``We keep hearing talk of inflation, recession,'' show spokesman
Tom Lauterback said Friday. ``But we've come off a sensational
Christmas. The mood here is very positive, very upbeat.
   ``There's nobody singing the blues here,'' Lauterback said.
   The hottest news at this year's show is home automation,
Lauterback said.
   ``We've developed a language which allows your appliances to
speak with and control one another,'' Lauterback said. ``The system
can do things as simple as turning on a light by remote control, or
as complex as having your dishwasher assess when rates are down,
maybe not doing the dishes until 3 a.m.
   ``Items such as cellular phones will allow you to start your
appliances at any time, any place,'' Lauterback said.
   Home automation is still in its infancy, but is being
standardized to the point where various products will soon be
working off each other, Lauterback said.
   ``Another hot category will be `pocket smarts' _ portable
computers that may be as small as credit cards,'' Lauterback said.
``They may serve as memo pads, dictionaries, a thesaurus, etc.''
   Many of the products on display during the show's four-day run
will be popping up on dealers' shelves later this year.
   Products range from electronic watches to satellite earth
stations, home office equipment, audio and video hardware and
accessories, car and home security systems, computer games,
telephone products, watches, video camcorders, compact disc players
and color TVs.
   ``We'll sell 20 million color TV sets this year,'' Lauterback
said.
   The number of exhibitors is a record for the 17th annual winter
event. A summer Consumer Electronics Show is held annually in
Chicago.
   Those attending the show will include nearly 5,500 foreign
buyers, manufacturers and electronics experts from 70 countries,
including the Soviet Union and China.
   Corcoran said this year's show will see growth in areas such as
home office products and ``edutainment,'' or
education-entertainment, with the amount of exhibit space tripling
in some categories.
   The show, which is closed to the public, is produced by the
Electronic Industries Association, a Washington, D.C.-based trade
association that represents most electronics manufacturers.
   This year's show is expected to provide a $100 million boost for
the Las Vegas economy. This show and the Comdex computer show in the
fall are the city's two largest conventions.
</TEXT>
