<DOCNO> AP890106-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid 1stLd-Writethru f0279 01-06 0885</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0279,0908</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Polaroid comment, background; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday upheld a controversial
Polaroid Corp. employee stock ownership plan, effectively blocking a
hostile $2.6 billion takeover bid by Disney family-owned Shamrock
Holdings Inc.
   The ruling by Vice Chancellor Carolyn Berger of Delaware Chancery
Court comes more than two months after the companies squared off in
court over the validity of the stock plan, which was unveiled just
before Shamrock's bid for the instant camera pioneer.
   ``Looks like they won,'' said William Relyea, a Polaroid analyst
with Eberstadt Fleming Inc. in New York. ``It just raises the odds
even higher that Polaroid is safe in the hands of management.''
   Shamrock, based in Burbank, Calif., maintained that Polaroid
enacted the 10-million-share, $300-million stock plan specifically
to block the takeover. Polaroid said it was a long-planned effort to
benefit employees.
   In a 53-page ruling, Berger said the employee stock ownership
plan, or ESOP, was partly defensive in nature but not unfair to
shareholders or workers ``and should not be invalidated.''
   ``It is structurally fair in its voting and tendering provisions
and I do not find either the timing of its implementation or its
possible anti-takeover effect objectionable under the facts of this
case,'' Berger wrote.
   ``This is a defensive device _ assuming it is one _ that is
designed to and appears likely to add value to the company and all
of its stockholders,'' she added. ``It does not prevent stockholders
from receiving or considering alternatives.''
   Shamrock spokesman John Grimaldi said the company would not
comment until reading the decision.
   The decision all but blocks a takeover because it puts 14 percent
of Polaroid stock in the hands of employees. Under Delaware takeover
law, a hostile bidder must acquire more than 85 percent of a
target's outstanding shares for control. Polaroid is incorporated in
Delaware.
   Polaroid, which was founded by Edwin H. Land in 1938 and
introduced instant snapshots 10 years later, also faces the
favorable prospect of a trial in federal court in Boston to
determine how much it will receive of a $5.7 billion damages request
against Eastman Kodak Co. for patent infringements.
   Polaroid closed Friday at $38.25, up 50 cents, in composite New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Shamrock on July 19 made a friendly but unsolicited $40-a-share
bid for Polaroid. It later made a hostile $42-a-share offer valuing
the company at $2.6 billion that Polaroid has urged its shareholders
to reject. The takeover hinged on the outcome of the trial.
   Polaroid President I. MacAllister Booth said in a statement: ``We
are, of course, delighted with this result as it supports what we
regard as a key component of Polaroid's future.''
   Shamrock, a television and radio concern wholly owned by the
family of Roy E. Disney, the animator's nephew, had said it would
purchase Polaroid shares under the $42 offer if the stock plan was
invalidated.
   The company, which already owns about 5 million shares of
Polaroid, now is faced with acquiring a controlling interest under
the $40 offer, a proposition analysts said was almost impossible.
Shamrock can appeal the ruling to Delaware Supreme Court. Polaroid
has about 71.6 million shares outstanding.
   Even if Shamrock threatens to acquire close to the 85 percent,
Polaroid could turn to a ``white squire'' who could buy 2 percent or
3 percent and secure the company's defense, analysts said.
   ``Unless they can find some hole in the way the judge has ruled,
it seems the the odds favor Polaroid on appeal,'' said Eugene Glazer
of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``Without the reversal of that ESOP, it
becomes very difficult for Shamrock to acquire Polaroid under
Delaware law.''
   Both the timing and intent of the employee stock plan were at
issue in the Delaware trial in October. Polaroid announced the plan
in July just one day before a scheduled meeting with Shamrock.
   Polaroid said its board of directors envisioned a 5 percent ESOP
in March before increasing it to 14 percent at its July meeting. The
company said the plan was undertaken to increase worker motivation
and that Polaroid had talked about an employee stock plan as long as
15 years ago.
   Ms. Berger said the timing, changes in the allocation of the
shares and other actions ``all had to have been motivated, at least
in part, by a desire to add one more obstacle to Shamrock's
potential acquisition bid.''
   But she said the plan would not harm workers' productivity.
   Polaroid's employees, a majority of whom signed a petition
opposing Shamrock's bid, are paying for the ESOP shares with a 5
percent pay cut. Polaroid had to borrow $285 million to fund the
plan.
   The decision and the upcoming Kodak trial, scheduled to begin Jan
17 in U.S. District Court, mark a turnaround for Polaroid, which has
struggled in the last decade as the popularity of instant
photography has declined.
   The company late last year completed a reduction of 1,700 jobs in
a major corporate restructuring. Polaroid now employs 8,300 people
in the United States.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Polaroid reported losses of
$15.1 million on sales of $1.33 billion, compared to earnings of
$76.3 million, or $1.23 a share, on sales of $1.25 billion in the
same 1987 period.
</TEXT>
