<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms     01-06 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Boosts Offer for Holly Farms To $1.2 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poultry giant Tyson Foods Inc. sweetened
a hostile takeover offer for Holly Farms Corp. to $1.2 billion cash
Friday, a move that appeared to push it closer to acquiring the
rival after a two-month brawl.
   It was the third time Tyson has sweetened the price and came a
week after the company won a court ruling that at least temporarily
prevented Holly from completing a friendly merger with ConAgra Corp.
to escape Tyson's overtures.
   In a sign Holly was willing to negotiate, the company said it
would consider Tyson's $60-a-share offer, raised from $54 a share or
$1.1 billion. Holly also said it would ask if ConAgra wished to
amend the merger proposal, a stock swap that has been valued by
securities analysts at about $1 billion.
   Holly said its board of directors would deliberate on the matter
at a special meeting next Wednesday and had urged the two potential
acquirers `to submit their best proposals before that meeting.''
   The developments pushed Holly's stock price up $2 a share to $60
in composite New York Stock Exchange trading. Tyson fell 37{ cents a
share to $16.50 in the over-the-counter market where its shares
trade. ConAgra was unchanged at $29.75 a share on the NYSE.
   Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., is the nation's leading poultry
company, producing more than 2 billion pounds a year. Omaha-based
ConAgra turns out about 1.5 billion pounds, and Memphis-based Holly
about 1.2 billion pounds.
   A Tyson acquisition of Holly would give it a major share of the
lucrative market for poultry, which is growing in popularity over
other meat.
   The latest chapter in the struggle followed a ruling last week
from a chancery judge in Delaware, where Holly Farms is
incorporated, that the proposed Holly-ConAgra merger wasn't in the
best interest of Holly shareholders because it didn't give them an
opportunity to consider Tyson's offer.
   The judge, ruling in a suit brought by Tyson's, prevented Holly
and ConAgra from acting on a merger agreement reached Nov. 17.
   Tyson said that other terms and conditions of the increased offer
will be described in documents that are to be mailed shortly to
Holly Farms shareholders.
   Tyson's attempt to buy Holly Farms began with a friendly offer
for about $900 million in cash and stock. After Holly Farms rejected
the offer, Tyson began pursuing a hostile takeover attempt with a
$52-a-share offer that was later raised to $54 a share.
</TEXT>
