<FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoTrade     01-06 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Trade,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ambassador Hopes for General Trade Agreement Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union hopes to reach a general trade
agreement soon with a consortium of seven U.S. companies, the Soviet
ambassador to the United States said Friday.
   Ambassador Yuri V. Dubinin, visiting Detroit as a guest of Ford
Motor Co., said trade talks are continuing with the consortium and
other companies, including General Motors Corp.
   ``The relationship was particularly good with Ford,'' he said.
   Ford officials have said they are negotiating with the Soviet
Union over making cars near Gorky in an existing plant or in a new
one. Officials have said the talks involve assembling a version of
Ford's West German-built Scorpio.
   ``We have some difficulty in our relations with Ford,'' Dubinin
said. ``Also we have contacts with General Motors, as you know, but
not on such a scale as we are projecting now with Ford.''
   Dubinin's comments came before a luncheon, at which GM Chairman
Roger Smith was guest speaker.
   The ambassador, his wife and other Soviet officials planned to
attend a private reception held by Ford Chairman Donald Petersen
before going to a black-tie charity dinner in conjunction with the
North American Auto Show, which opens to the public on Saturday.
   ``To buy an autocar in the Soviet Union is a double problem,''
Dubinin said. ``First of all, you have to have money and secondly
you have to have (a buyers) card to buy.
   ``We have a good production of cars in the Soviet Union, but we
have to modernize.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
